</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 26.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BLACK DOG OF FATE: A MEMOIR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Balakian. Broadway, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The author, an American poet of Armenian descent, describes his
awakening to his ethnicity and the suffering of his family and
ancestors at the hands of the Turkish government, which
exterminated more than a million Armenians in 1915. The result is a
``fascinating and affecting memoir ... written in sorrow and
anger,'' Lore Dickstein wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PUTTERMESSER PAPERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Cynthia Ozick. Vintage International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Puttermesser is a New York Jew whose imaginary life is
richer than all the financial markets and political offices she
floats through in her mundane daily existence. In this painfully
comic novel, which was selected by the editors of the Book Review
as one of the best books of 1997, she creates a golem who gets her
elected mayor of New York City (with disastrous results), casts
herself as George Eliot and her new lover as Eliot's paramour and
winds up in heaven, where her best dreams and worst apprehensions
are realized. Last year our reviewer, Jack Miles, called this
``crazy delight'' the inspired work of ''a literary centaur, half
artist and half scholar.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO GOES FIRST? THE STORY OF SELF-EXPERIMENTATION IN MEDICINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lawrence K. Altman. University of California, $17.95.
</P>
<P>
   A physician and the medical correspondent for The New York Times
argues that self-experimentation in medicine has been extremely
common and valuable over the years and is also a vital measure of a
researcher's integrity. In 1987 in these pages, Fitzhugh Mullan
called this a ``fascinating and thoroughly original exploration.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE MEMORY OF THE FOREST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles T. Powers. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   A murder in a Polish village sets off an investigation that
sheds light on the brutalities of the recent communist era. But the
central mystery is the deeper past and the disappearance of the 80
percent of the village's prewar population who were Jews. ``This
superb novel ... is remarkable for the acuity of its moral vision
and the vivacity of its language,'' Ken Kalfus said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOT LIKE US: HOW EUROPEANS HAVE LOVED, HATED, AND TRANSFORMED
AMERICAN CULTURE SINCE WORLD WAR II &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Pells. Basic Books, $16.
</P>
<P>
   A historian contrasts the government-sponsored attempts to
persuade Europeans of the glories of the United States with the far
less predictable commercially driven encounters between ``them''
and ``us.'' What he uncovers is less the Americanization of world
culture than the globalization of culture, period. This is a
``skeptical, informative book,'' Alan Ryan said here in 1997.
 &UR; LONDON: A SOCIAL HISTORY &LR; , by Roy Porter (Harvard University,
$19.95), takes a Darwinian view of an elusive city, treating it as
both habitat and evolving organism. In 1995 our reviewer, John R.
Stilgoe, called this a ``stunningly successful look at London
between the Elizabeths.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PORTRAIT OF THE WALRUS BY A YOUNG ARTIST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Laurie Foos. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $11.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen-year-old Frances Fisk is a sculptor of aquatic animals
who grapples with her muse after her father's death, but what
really drives this novel are odd plot details like sharks and chain
saws that somehow make sense by the end. Last year in these pages,
Sally Eckhoff praised the author's ``bold and tuneful'' voice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T TELL THE GROWN-UPS: THE SUBVERSIVE POWER OF CHILDREN'S
LITERATURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alison Lurie. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $14.
</P>
<P>
   These essays focus on the wicked, often hidden honesty of
classic folk tales and their challenge to conventional adult
values, as well as on the human creators of our favorite fantasies.
The result is a ``thoroughly absorbing collection'' by an
''unillusioned and cheerfully clearheaded guide,'' Rosellen Brown
said here in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A DEATH IN CHINA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Carl Hiaasen and Bill Montalbano. Black Lizard/Vintage Crime,
$12.
</P>
<P>
   Two newspaper reporters spin a yarn about an American professor
who stumbles onto an art-smuggling ring after the suspicious death
of a Chinese-American colleague. In 1984 in the Book Review,
Herbert Mitgang called this an ``imaginative thriller.'' The same
publisher has reissued an earlier collaboration,  &UR; POWDER BURN &LR; 
($12), in which an architect infiltrates the Miami drug scene after
he is marked for death for accidentally witnessing a murder. In
1982 in these pages, Newgate Callendar called this an ``expertly
plotted'' novel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURPASSING THE LOVE OF MEN: ROMANTIC FRIENDSHIP AND LOVE
BETWEEN WOMEN FROM THE RENAISSANCE TO THE PRESENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lillian Faderman. Quill/Morrow, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The author maintains that until recently women were usually free
to love one another, and that the male world tolerated or even
praised romantic friendship between women as pure and ennobling; it
was only in this century that such love was condemned. This is ``a
welcome and needed history,'' Carolyn G. Heilbrun wrote here in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONKEY BRIDGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lan Cao. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of this first novel tells how her Vietnamese family
was fractured by the war and how its members struggled to reinvent
themselves amid the mind-boggling possibilities and confusions of
their adopted American life. This is ``an impressive debut,''
Michiko Kakutani wrote in The New York Times in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
