<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINAL-IMMIG-SPECIAL-A     07-19 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINAL-IMMIG-SPECIAL-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(th) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to a
three-part series moving this weekend on the new identity being
forged by America's immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike immigrants of the past, many of today's new Americans are
choosing to straddle two worlds. They may live in the United
States, but with cut-rate phone cards and frequent-flier miles,
with modems, fax machines and video cameras, they can participate
in life back home with an immediacy unimagined by any previous
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The three articles will move in two forms: full length as
published in The New York Times and in abridged versions of perhaps
half or less of the full length. They will move on Saturday, Sunday
and Monday in the ``a'' news file and are for publication beginning
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the series follows:
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-IDENTITY (Undated) _ For a New York City couple, many a
day can start in blaring traffic on the Grand Central Parkway in
Queens County and end on horseback in the verdant countryside of
their native Dominican Republic, cantering down to a river to feast
on rum and goat. They, like many modern immigrants, no longer
consign their homeland to the mist of memory or nostalgia. As the
world has grown smaller, the immigrant experience has become one of
remaining connected, economically, culturally, politically. Such a
fluid exchange between the homeland and the new land, which
inevitably alters both places, has unsettled many Americans, and
this unease underlies the current debates about immigration,
multiculturalism and bilingualism. By Deborah Sontag and Celia W.
Dugger. (6,400 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (For use Sunday, July 19, and thereafter.)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-TRADITION (Undated) _ In modern immigrant families, where
the bindings between here and there are stronger than ever before,
children almost inevitably find themselves pushed and pulled
between the culture and values of their parents and those of the
larger American society. Such ambiguities are perhaps never more
acute than when a decision about marriage is at hand. But what
emerges at defining moments like Vinit Sethi's traditional Indian
wedding, arranged by his parents, is the way many of these children
search for and find solace and grounding in their connections to
the world back home. By Celia W. Dugger. (5,000 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (For use Monday, July 20, and thereafter.)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-GLOBALVILLAGE (Undated) _ Almost every migration story is
the psychodrama of a family, its aspirations and frustrations, its
separations and reunions, its traditions and compromises. For some
Latin American and Caribbean immigrants, as for the Cruz family of
Chinantla, Mexico, it is also the story of a town, a global village
in the most literal sense. By Deborah Sontag. (6,100 words.)
</P>
<P>
   (For use Tuesday, July 21, and thereafter.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABRIDGED VERSION SLUGS &LR;  (With word count):
</P>
<P>
   ABR-IMMIG-IDENTITY (2,400 words)
</P>
<P>
   ABR-IMMIG-TRADITION (2,100 words)
</P>
<P>
   ABR-IMMIG-GLOBALVILAGE (2,800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FREE PHOTOS, GRAPHICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Photos and graphics to accompany the articles are being made
available free to clients and non-clients of the NYT News Service
graphics and photo desk.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT101) UNDATED _ IMMIG-IDENTITY-1 _ Stella and Fernando Mateo
on a flight between their homeland, the Dominican Republic, and
their home in New York. Fernando has been shuttling between the two
cities his entire life. ``I believe people like us have the best of
two worlds,'' he says. ``We have two countries, two homes.''
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT102) NEW YORK _ IMMIG-IDENTITY-2 _ Hamid Ali, a cab driver,
talks with his sister, Shamim Kusar, who lives in Islamabad,
Pakistan, from a New York City videophone parlor. He had not seen
her in four years. ``I will tell everyone in town that I saw my
brother on TV,'' Ms. Kusar giggled. ``They won't believe me. We are
simple people.'' (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT103) NEW YORK _ IMMIG-IDENTITY-3 _ Eric Beckford, a Jamaican
immigrant, packing a barrel of food and clothing to send to his
parents back home. Barrel-shipping companies, taking advantage of
low prices for staples in America, are part of an entrepreneurial
subculture that taps immigrants' ties to their homelands. Beckford,
as well as his four siblings who live in New York, frequently send
staples to Jamaica because American prices are relatively low.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT105) UNDATED _ IMMIG-IDENTITY-4 _ Fernando Mateo at his
company's headquarters in Manhattan, right, and in Bani, Dominican
Republic, at the home of Jose Antonio Ortiz Sanchez, who had just
received money from his son in the United States. Mateo, who owns a
money-transfer company, commutes frequently between New York and
Santo Domingo. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NYT106) JAIPUR, India _ IMMIG-TRADITION-1 _ Vinit Sethi, whose
mother found his wife in Jaipur, India, is teased by his friends
before the ceremony. ``I always knew I'd probably end up getting
married to someone who wasn't very American, because I'm not myself
in some ways,'' he says. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT107) JAIPUR, India _ IMMIG-TRADITION-2 _ Vinit Sethi rides
to his wedding ceremony with his Indian-born bride on horseback.
The path is illuminated by green fluorescent lights. Sethi, 24, is
marrying a woman of his mother's choosing. ``I had an incredible
feeling that this was the right thing to do,'' Sethi says. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT108) NEW YORK _ IMMIG-TRADITION-3 _ Vinit Sethi explains
baseball to his new wife, Anshu Jain, at a recent New York Yankees
game. Sethi, a 24-year-old investment banker born and reared in New
York, has urged his wife to become a more independent, modern woman
_ to go back to college, wear jeans and to do what would have been
unthinkable to her only a year ago: call her husband by his first
name. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT109) NEW YORK _ IMMIG-TRADITION-5 _ Anjali Rawat in her dorm
room at Barnard. Miss Rawat, whose marriage has been arranged, has
given up finishing her education and her dream of becoming a
television news announcer and will, instead, follow her husband to
London or India. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT110) JAIPUR, India _ IMMIG-TRADITION-4 _ Anjali Rawat sits
with her future husband during a visit to India. While Miss Rawat,
a Barnard College freshman, had always known that she would ``be
arranged,'' she was shocked that it had happened soon. ``I wish it
didn't have to be this way, but I can't really do anything about
it.'' (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT111) CHINANTLA, Mexico _ IMMIG-GLOBALVILLAGE-1 _ Zoela Cruz,
a former New York factory worker, listening to an accordion player
at her home in Chinantla, Mexico. Her maid, Cristo Rey, watches
from the kitchen. Mrs. Cruz, who spent decades folding fabric in a
Brooklyn sweatshop, retired to Chinantla and opened a small store
from which she dispenses rice and advice. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT112) CHINANTLA, Mexico _ IMMIG-GLOBALVILLAGE-2 _ Elizabeth
Cruz preparing her son, Christian de Jesus, for his baptism.
Helping her is her sister Monica, brother-in-law Claudio, and his
daughter, Samantha. Elizabeth, a bilingual education teacher, who
lives with her husband in New York, brought her son to Chinantla to
fulfill a promise she made to herself. (Jim Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT113) CHINANTLA, Mexico _ IMMIG-GLOBALVILLAGE-3 _ Melissa
Cruz, near right, and her mother, Zoela in a procession for Padre
Jesus. The procession is an all-night devotional. When not in
Mexico, Melissa, 26, is a nurse St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital in
Manhattan. (Jim Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT114) NEW YORK _ IMMIG-GLOBALVILLAGE-4 _ Antonia Cruz and her
daughter, Samantha, outside their building in Brooklyn. Antonia,
who infuriated her parents by dropping out of high school when she
got engaged, lives with her sisters and her own family in the same
small apartment in which the girls were raised. (Jim Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
