   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   FARMING-GENETICS (Dallikon, Switzerland) _ Throughout the world
last year more than 30 million acres of commercial farmland were
planted with genetically modified seeds _ ten times as much as the
year before. But not one of those acres was in the 15 countries of
the European Union. By Michael Specter.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ As Americans yearn for a forceful new
prime minister to emerge in Japan and take charge of the economy,
it is worth remembering that Ieyasu Tokugawa, the
``barbarian-subduing shogun'' who lived four centuries ago, was
arguably the last really strong and dynamic leader to reshape
Japan. Since then, Japan has had good rulers and bad rulers; but
only rarely has it had a strong leader. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FIGHTING (Orahovac, Yugoslavia) _ In what could the
beginning of a significant new phase of the fighting in the Serbian
province of Kosovo, ethnic Albanian separatists said on Sunday that
they have taken Orahovac, their first city, and that they will use
their newly acquired weapons to keep it. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israelis and Palestinians hold their
first direct negotiations in months. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-POLITICS (Dateline TK) _ Abubakar is expected to unveil
his plans for democracy in a broadcast early on Monday. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Tucuman) _ Antonio Domingo Bussi, the
barrel-chested, cigar-chomping Governor of this tiny northwestern
province, has been getting a lot of bad press lately. By Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-TRADITION (Undated) _ In modern immigrant families, where
the bindings between here and there are stronger than ever before,
children almost inevitably find themselves pushed and pulled
between the culture and values of their parents and those of the
larger American society. Such ambiguities are perhaps never more
acute than when a decision about marriage is at hand. But what
emerges at defining moments like Vinit Sethi's traditional Indian
wedding, arranged by his parents, is the way many of these children
search for and find solace and grounding in their connections to
the world back home. By Celia W. Dugger. (5,000 words.) An abridged
version, slugged ABR-IMMIG-TRADITION (2,100 words), will be moved
at the same time. In addition, photos and graphics to accompany the
article are being made available free to clients and non-clients of
the NYT News Service graphics and photo desk.
</P>
<P>
   TEENSMOKERS-COURT (Plantation, Fla.) _ Once a month for a couple
of hours, Judge Steven G. Shutter of Broward County clears his
courtroom of lawyers and defendants to make room for restless
teen-agers and their inconvenienced parents for what is known as
Teen Smoking Court. It is a new weapon in Florida's fight against
teen-age smoking, combining combines education, health warnings and
parental nagging with the weight of the law. The Teen Smoking Court
is part of a large-scale campaign against underage smoking that the
state is financing with $200 million of the $11.3-billion
settlement it reached with tobacco companies last year after suing
to recover Medicaid payments for smoking-related illnesses. By
Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Dateline TK) _ With the president on his weekend
travels in Little Rock and New Orleans. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-POLITICS (Washington) _ Republicans in Congress appear
headed toward a showdown with President Clinton over tax and
spending bills for next year, as the two sides battle over issues
like education and seek political advantage heading into the fall's
congressional elections. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEDEBATES-FINANCE (Washington) _ Call it the capital's
rendition of ``Eine Kleine Nachtmusik,'' the sometimes discordant
strains of the campaign finance debate that is relegated to the
post prime-time hours of the House's summer agenda. The vistors'
galleries are empty. The reporters and television crews that cram
the Capitol in daylight have all but dispersed. But like
nightwandering vampires, a small coven of lawmakers arises in full
majesty to take the floor for a debate that often does come close
to drawing blood. They only come out at night, and they are
scheduled to resume debate after the sun sets on Monday. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-PATIENTRIGHTS (Washington) _ The struggle over patients'
rights legislation has scrambled old alliances and created some
extraordinary new ones. It is throwing together doctors, trial
lawyers and consumers and pitting them against insurers and managed
care companies, who in many cases are fighting each other over how
much regulation they can take. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
