<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   CONCERTS-CORPORATE (Los Angeles) _ Over the past year and a
half, the rock and pop concert business has quietly been going
through the biggest transformation in its history. The business,
the last stronghold of independence in a rapidly consolidating
entertainment industry, had long been a world of self-made and
often ruthless local moguls. But with the sudden entry onto the
scene of a deep-pocketed, publicly traded company called SFX
Entertainment, the business has begun to go the way of the movie
and recording industries, and is fast becoming consolidated under
the aegis of a sprawling corporate conglomerate. By Neil Strauss
and James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-OPERA (Barcelona, Spain) _ Barcelona's opera house is
restored to its former grandeur. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   TITAN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
`Titan: The Life of John D. Rockefeller Sr.'' by Ron Chernow.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLISM-DRUG (Undated) _ A French company may bring a new
drug, already widely available in Europe, to the United States in
2000 that would help alcoholics remain abstinent after they
complete detoxification. But it has already generated a heated
controversy in the health-care community over whether it should be
used at all. On the one side, are specialists who argue that
alcoholics and other addicts should be treated by counseling alone.
On the other, are doctors who insist that prescription drugs are
crucial tools in rehabilitating them.
</P>
<P>
   ADVERTISING-AD-COL (Undated) _ Advertising about advertising. It
has been a popular trend for some time, but is now getting bigger
and bigger. Even in public service ads (the crying Indian), ads now
reference earlier ads because of the belief consumers are so savvy
about advertising as an adjunct to popular culture. Some ads spoof
ads for other products, while some spoof their competitors. A look
at whether this is good marketing, or just lazy mining of the past
for no good result. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-STOCKS (Undated) _ After years of being coddled by
cradle-to-grave social security systems, Europeans are being urged
by financially strapped governments to take a larger hand in
planning their financial futures, and the result is a stock market
boom. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CONUNDRUM (Undated) _ Sometimes it seems like
Microsoft is damned if it does and damned if it doesn't. While
reviewers complain that Windows 98 lacks significant new features,
the Justice Department and 20 states accuse the company of
including in the operating system features that should be separate
programs. It is this conundrum that makes the lawsuits and
questions about Microsoft's monopoly so challenging from both legal
and computer science standpoints. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST-INTERNET (Undated) _ Broadcast.com is the latest
red-hot Internet IPO. Who are these guys? By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAXBILL (Undated) _ Big changes are being made in the
Internet tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Digital Commerce column; details
TK. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-PRODUCERS-MEDIA (Undated) _ The general expansion of prime
time news magazine shows has created new opportunity for producers,
but raised some concerns among them that the competitive
environment has increased their responsibilities and intensified
potential journalistic hazards _ from accelerating the careers of
less experienced producers to raising the volume of news stories.
By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   VOGUE-MEDIA (Undated) _ The fallout at Vogue, after the Ron
Galotti departure. By Robin Pogrebin.
