<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-MIDEAST-TALKS20-CO     07-19 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-MIDEAST-TALKS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAR BOMB ATTEMPT RAISES MIDEAST TENSION AS PEACE TALKS RESTART
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A failed car-bomb attempt in the height of rush hour
Sunday served as a pointed reminder of Israel's security risks,
even as negotiators restarted talks in the deadlocked peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said a Palestinian man was badly burned as he
tried to ignite 160 gallons of explosive liquids in a van on the
main downtown street at about 8:30 a.m., the start of the Israeli
work week.
</P>
<P>
   An off-duty police officer reportedly noticed smoke in the van,
which had non-matching license plates. Police told The Associated
Press that the injured man was an activist in Hamas, a Palestinian
group opposed to the existence of Israel and the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted bombing, which police said could have caused
extensive damage and injuries, came nearly a year after a bombing
in a Jerusalem produce market killed 16 Israelis and derailed an
attempt then to restart the Oslo process. The Oslo accords are
based on Israel turning over occupied land in return for
Palestinians' peaceful acceptance of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The incident may have been an attempt by Hamas to derail
Sunday's talks.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu spoke to reporters a
few hours after the attempt, saying that it showed why he must hold
Palestinians to their commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have our concerns,'' Netanyahu said. ``You can
understand why we insist that the Palestinians carry out their
responsibilities, first of all with fighting terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai met in
Tel Aviv with Mahmoud Abbas, the top aide to Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat and one of the architects of the peace process begun
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was urged by U.S. officials who are trying to end a
17-month freeze in the peace process. The two sides agreed to meet
again this week, but both had entered the meetings with
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians have accepted the basis of a U.S. plan to break the
deadlock, which would have Israel turn over another 13 percent of
the land it has occupied in the West Bank since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Such a turnover would leave about 40 percent of the West Bank in
full or partial control of the Palestinians and open the way for
long-delayed negotiations of the final, most difficult issues in
the peace process, such as the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinians said they saw little reason in meeting until
Israel agreed to the plan, because the 13 percent was already much
lower than they had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israeli leaders said they were eager to meet, but
have for months resisted U.S. pressure to turn over the land. They
maintain that the Palestinians have not worked hard enough to
combat extremists such as Hamas in the areas they now control.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock has raised warnings from leaders on both sides that
fighting could break out between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu repeated Sunday that he would be willing to meet
directly with Arafat. But Arafat has said that the Israelis should
first accept the U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
