<P>
   HEALTHCARE-CODE (Washington) _ As legislation that would protect
patient privacy languishes in Congress, ideas are being discussed,
like assigning every American a computer ID code that could be used
to track someone's medical history from cradle to grave.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-POLITICS (Washington) _ Republicans in Congress appear
headed toward a showdown with President Clinton over tax and
spending bills for next year, as the two sides battle over issues
like education and seek political advantage heading into the fall's
congressional elections. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEDEBATES-FINANCE (Washington) _ Call it the capital's
rendition of ``Eine Kleine Nachtmusik,'' the sometimes discordant
strains of the campaign finance debate that is relegated to the
post prime-time hours of the House's summer agenda. The vistors'
galleries are empty. The reporters and television crews that cram
the Capitol in daylight have all but dispersed. But like
nightwandering vampires, a small coven of lawmakers arises in full
majesty to take the floor for a debate that often does come close
to drawing blood. They only come out at night, and they are
scheduled to resume debate after the sun sets on Monday. By Alison
Mitchell.
