<DOCNO> NYT19980719.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASB-STOCK-DISCOUNT-N     07-19 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASB-STOCK-DISCOUNT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDARDS BOARD BACKS OFF STOCK-DISCOUNT PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with opposition from the technology industry and other
companies, accounting rule makers have stepped away from a proposal
that had threatened to end certain lucrative employee stock plans.
</P>
<P>
   The rules relate to stock purchase plans in which employees can
buy company stock at a discount of more than 15 percent. While tax
laws limit the discount to 15 percent, many companies give their
employees a better deal by applying the discount to the market
price at either the beginning or the end of a certain period,
whichever price is lower. New York Times Co. has one of these plans
as do many technology companies, including Intel Corp. and National
Semiconductor Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board proposed this spring
that if companies wanted to give employees what is effectively more
than a 15 percent discount from the market price on the date the
stock was purchased, they would have to treat the discount as an
expense. Such an expense, in turn, would cut into earnings. To
avoid that expense, many companies were expected to limit their
stock programs.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the board decided that companies could still
apply the 15 percent discount to the price at the beginning of the
period, which under the law is when the company is considered to
have granted an employee an option to purchase stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for employees and for employee ownership,''
said Karen Frey, communications director at the American
Electronics Association, a trade association of technology
companies. The association, located in Silicon Valley, had sent a
letter to the accounting board in June, calling the proposed
changes ``unnecessary'' and ``confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's proposal had been drawing controversy because it was
aimed at stock plans that under federal law must benefit all
employees. In 1994, the accounting board had backed away from a
similar proposal that would have made it more costly for companies
to grant stock options _ a perk that most companies give only to
top executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be feeling a little bit of the political heat,''
said Tim Sparks, a lawyer at the Silicon Valley law firm of Wilson
Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosetti and an expert on employee compensation
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks said it was still not clear what effect the rules would
have on companies' stock purchase programs. For example, it is
unclear whether companies would be able to apply the discount to
the price at the end of the period if the market price falls. And
if companies cannot use that lower price, it is not clear whether
employees would be able to take their money out of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   A steep drop in the company's stock price could result in
employees being forced to pay more for their stock than they could
buy it on the market, if the discount can only be applied to the
price at the period's start.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting board's decisions are still tentative. The board
plans to issue a draft of the new rules early next year. The public
will then have about 90 days to comment on the rules before the
board makes a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Miller, who manages the stock plans at National
Semiconductor in Santa Clara, Calif., said company officials had
worried that fewer employees would participate in their stock
program if they were forced to limit the discount to 15 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
