<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOGUE-MEDIA-ART-700&AMP;A     07-19 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOGUE-MEDIA-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALOTTI WAS `CONSUMMATE SALESMAN' FOR CONDE NAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the midst of all the hoopla over Tina Brown's
decision to leave The New Yorker and link up with Harvey Weinstein
at Miramax, one aspect of the media deal was largely overlooked:
that Ronald Galotti, the brash publisher of Vogue who helped make
the magazine a blockbuster success over the last several years, was
defecting from Conde Nast Publications to join Ms. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   For the last four years, Galotti has been one of Conde Nast's
heaviest hitters, a hard-driving publisher who raked in the ad
pages at the company's most glamorous magazine and helped bolster
its reputation as the bible of the fashion business. His departure
is therefore no routine matter and could seem to signify another
chink in the armor at a time when the publishing company looks
somewhat vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Fortune magazine published a scathing
article asserting that Conde Nast, a unit of Advance Publications,
has been ``a woeful underperformer'' financially and that Steven
Florio, the company's president and chief executive, has
exaggerated the company's business successes and lied about details
in his personal life. Florio and his supporters have dismissed the
article as inaccurate and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Then the company's chairman, S.I. Newhouse Jr., was caught off
guard by losing Ms. Brown. And there have been reports about other
wandering eyes at the company, namely two of Galotti's closest
friends _ Richard Beckman, who has succeeded Galotti at Vogue, and
Thomas Florio, Steven Florio's younger brother, who was moved out
as publisher of The New Yorker in May and returned to his former
post as publisher of Conde Nast Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Before being named as Galotti's replacement at Vogue, Beckman
met with Jann Wenner about the position of group publisher at
Wenner Media, which publishes Rolling Stone, Us and Men's Journal.
And Thomas Florio has had several conversations with David Pecker,
president and chief executive of Hachette Filipacchi Magazines,
about opportunities at his company, which publishes Elle and
Mirabella.
</P>
<P>
   According to one publishing executive, Thomas Florio sought out
Pecker soon after an article appeared in The Wall Street Journal
earlier this year in which Steven Florio announced that Conde Nast
would be folding The New Yorker into its operations and implied
that big brother was taking control. Thomas Florio did not return
calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether all of this makes Steven Florio nervous, the chief
executive said no. ``I'm sure that every good person here gets
phone calls,'' he said. ``Is it my job to continually challenge
them? Of course it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Galotti said he did not decide to leave because of any
discontent with the company; it had to do with getting a better
offer. As part owner of the media company backed by Miramax,
Galotti will run whatever magazine he and Ms. Brown decide to start
_ although many have raised questions about whether the venture to
create synergy between a magazine, books, television and movies is
just a pipe dream.
</P>
<P>
   Galotti, 48, has long been a larger-than-life, occasionally
controversial character at Conde Nast. He was dismissed as
publisher of Vanity Fair in 1993 after clashing with Bernard Leser,
the former president of the company, although the official line was
that he resigned. He has been accused of throwing chairs, something
Galotti said never happened. He kicked an office refrigerator,
according to one account. Last year, Spy magazine called him a
``vulgarian,'' among other things.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also known as the consummate salesman, which is what
counts most at Conde Nast. He delivered thicker and thicker fall
issues of Vogue to the point where the number of ads was promoted
in pounds rather than pages, which rose to nearly 2,800 at the end
of last year, up from 2,400 the year Galotti started. His
slick-haired, perpetually tan, power-suited, back-slapping persona
went over well with ad executives. It also earned him some
notoriety: He was the basis for the character Big in Candace
Bushnell's popular ``Sex in the City'' column in The New York
Observer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, people have often described Galotti as a prime example
of the Steven Florio school of pit bull publishers: brash,
hard-driving, with just the right dose of charm.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman is also described as a Steven Florio protege and is
proud to describe himself that way. Beckman credits Florio with
giving him his first big break at the company _ as an ad salesman
in the London office of The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Florio _ who was publisher of The New Yorker at the
time _ brought Beckman back to New York and made him ad manager of
The New Yorker, then ad director of Conde Nast Traveler, then
publisher of GQ, where Beckman took ad pages to about 2,000 from
1,400.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Beckman's defection would have been a real blow.
But just as rumors about Beckman's being wooed by Wenner Media were
percolating, Conde Nast was able to counter with a plum: Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Conde Nast replaced Beckman at GQ with Jack
Laschever, a corporate vice president at American Express
Publishing, where he served as group publisher for Departures, Your
Company and Sky Guide since 1997. Beckman said he never intended to
leave, though he said he did meet with Wenner.
</P>
<P>
   As for Thomas Florio, he still would seem to have every reason
to send his resume around. Yes, he may have survived the fallout
from leaving The New Yorker without having made it profitable _
although the magazine's losses did decline during his six-year
tenure _ and, yes, he is earning considerably more money with a
package worth about $800,000, up from the $600,000 he earned at The
New Yorker, according to one magazine executive. But he has yet to
get out from under the upstaging presence of his brother, who moved
him from The New Yorker _ with the blessing of Newhouse _ though
Thomas Florio has said it was he who wanted a change.
</P>
<P>
   One magazine executive said Thomas Florio had also met with
Wenner, who declined to comment, in addition to talking to Pecker.
Asked about his brother's meeting with Pecker, Steven Florio said:
``I don't know that to be true. I've asked Tom about it, and he's
pledged his loyalty and hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   For a time earlier this year, when things were first heating up
at The New Yorker, it seemed that the loyalties of Galotti and
Beckman might be divided over whom to side with. But interestingly,
all of these men appear to have emerged good friends. Beckman said
both Florios and Galotti would be present at his wedding in the
fall. And Steven Florio said he was unconcerned about any threat to
company loyalty. ``Ron is the first publisher in five years that
resigned,'' he said. ``He's the only one I've ever lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
