<SLUG> BC-BROADCAST-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BROADCASTING: RISKS AND OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a piece of twine and run it between two empty dog food cans
and you have a sound transmission system with the approximate
quality of many audio broadcasts over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the stage of Carnegie Hall with 10 million $100 bills and
you would see the amount of money that investors have poured into
Broadcast.com Inc., a company devoted to putting radio and
television programs on the Internet. Investors are apparently
willing to overlook the current technical limitations of Internet
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the first day of trading after Broadcast.com's
initial public stock offering, the company's shares opened at $68,
nearly four times higher than its $18 offering price. That was the
biggest initial jump in the history of stock offerings in the
United States. The shares shot up to as high as $74 before closing
at $62.75. At that price, Broadcast.com has a total market value of
$1.06 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in 1995 by Todd Wagner and Mark Cuban,
who began by putting the broadcasts of a Dallas radio station onto
the Internet through a computer in a friend's bedroom. Cuban, 39,
had run a computer consulting firm and a technology investment
fund. Wagner, 37, is a lawyer and a certified public accountant.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Cuban's share of the company stock is worth more than
$350 million. Wagner's stake exceeds $200 million. Broadcast.com
executives were unavailable for comment because the company is in
its government-mandated quiet period.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com, which is based in Dallas and recently changed its
name from Audionet, now offers transmissions of 345 radio stations,
flickery images from 17 television stations, games from 350 sports
teams and other talk and music programs.
</P>
<P>
   In return for helping broadcast stations extend their reach,
Broadcast.com receives some on-air commercial time slots to sell to
advertisers. It also can sell audio advertising that Internet
listeners hear before joining the program of their choice. The
company also sells on-screen ads that the audience members can view
while they are listening.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com also has a second business, broadcasting corporate
presentations, like meetings for analysts, over the Internet,
offering a lower cost alternative to telephone and video conference
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the company say that as the technology for Internet
broadcasting improves, Broadcast.com is in a prime position to
capitalize on a medium that could be far more compelling than the
text-based Internet is today.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts point out that the risk in its plans are at least
as great as the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   To start with, the company is small, and spending nearly twice
as much money as it is taking in. In 1997, it lost $6.5 million on
revenue of $6.9 million. And the company's prospectus filed with
the Securities and Exchange Commission says it expects the losses
to continue indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, there appears to be little the company can do to
defend against competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can do what they're doing,'' said David Simons,
managing director of Digital Video Investments, a research service.
``Net investors are impervious to the notion of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet both ESPN Sportzone and CBS Sportsline have their own
Internet broadcasting service that competes with Broadcast.com's
sports services. And Broadcast.com has exclusive Internet rights to
only some of its programming. Other programs can be carried by its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com does have some programs that it will probably not
have to fight to keep, though. It runs a site called
www.policescanner.com, for example, which transmits the emergency
service radio broadcasts from New York, Los Angeles and Dallas. Not
only is that programming free _ it is supposed to sound like it is
coming in on two dog-food cans and twine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
