<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOODAH-THEATER-REVIEW     07-19 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOODAH-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNZIPPIN' MY DOODAH: EXASPERATINGLY UNEVEN MUSICAL SATIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(jw) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For political satirists, 1998 is turning out to be a
very good year. Washington hasn't produced such an irresistible
array of lampoonable personages since Gary Hart posed with Donna
Rice next to a boat called ``Monkey Business.''
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is where the Capitol Steps come in. The gang of
singing gunslingers from Washington is back in New York with a
(mostly) new comedy revue, ``Unzippin' My Doodah,'' that is
front-loaded with jabs at the newest members of the ``usual
suspects'' club _ Monica and Linda and Kenneth _ as well as at such
venerable targets as Bill and Hillary and Boris and Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the juiciest takeoffs and songs in this
exasperatingly uneven, 90-minute show have nothing to do with any
of the above. A Monica Lewinsky number, sung by Elaina Newport
(``Why are there so many/ Songs about bimbos?'') and another
spoofing the woman who taped her _ ``That's 'cause the Linda Is a
Tripp,'' sung to ``The Lady Is a Tramp'' _ pack all the wallop of a
powder puff. They don't snap with the crispness of the group's
assaults on less obvious subjects, like the clothier Sy Syms,
overaggressive telemarketers and the entry of India and Pakistan
into the nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   What? You don't find underground atomic bomb tests funny? That's
exactly why the troupe's pairing of silly songs on the subject, to
the tunes of ``Lydia, the Tattooed Lady'' (``India, oh India ...
.'') and ``Chitty Chitty Bang Bang'' (``Pakistani Bang Bang''),
makes you laugh: It's a topic that comes at you completely under
the radar, and one that doesn't yet feel overmilked.
</P>
<P>
   The show's loony opening number, ``Circle of Lies,'' is another
unexpected success. It does double duty as a parody of the
animal-parade opening of the Broadway version of ``The Lion King''
and as a sendup of the jungle on the Potomac. In the staging by
Mark Waldrop, though, you detect a strong whiff of ``Forbidden
Broadway,'' Gerard Alessandrini's long-running Broadway parody
revue.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Unzippin' My Doodah'' could take another lesson or
two from Mr. Alessandrini, because most of the Capitol Steps show
is not up to the tickling level of the opening or nuclear-test
numbers. Much more typically, a song begins as a sharp notion and
rapidly fizzles out, as when a certain New York senator is parodied
in ``He's delightful, he's de-lovely, he's D'Amato.'' The group
fails to develop its own idea of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato as the star
of a Cole Porter musical, and the number falls flat. (It's amazing
how often this pattern is repeated; the audience expresses its
frustration with a peculiarly energyless kind of applause.)
</P>
<P>
   Five members of the 14-person troupe rotate into the cast at
each performance. On a recent evening, the players were Ms.
Newport, Bill Strauss, Dolores King, Mike Tilford and Jamie
Zemarel, all of whom are pleasant if unexciting. Perfectly
painless, in fact. Like their show.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   UNZIPPIN' MY DOODAH AND OTHER NATIONAL PRIORITIES
</P>
<P>
   Conceived, written and directed by Bill Strauss and Elaina
Newport. Staged by Mark Waldrop. Performed by the troupe Capitol
Steps. Sets by R.J. Matson; lighting by Marina Bridges; props and
costumes by Robyn Scott; sound by Jill DuBoff; technical director,
Brad Van Grack; general manager, Jonathan Shulman. Presented by
Eric Krebs, in association with Capitol Steps. At the John Houseman
Theater, 450 West 42nd St.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mike Carruthers, Andy Clemence, Janet Davidson Gordon,
Mike Loomis, Elaina Newport, Ann Margaret Schmitt, Bill Strauss,
Mike Thornton, Mike Tilford, Brad Van Grack, Delores King Williams
and Jamie Zemarel.
</P>
</TEXT>
