<HEADER>
A2239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      07-19 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winds gusted to 58 miles per hour at Chicago's Midway airport at
daybreak on Sunday as a cluster of thunderstorms blew through the
city. A similar group of thunderstorms, marking the leading edge of
sultry air, will likely buffet the central Appalachians in the
predawn hours on Monday before dissipating in the Middle Atlantic
states. The leftover clouds may keep afternoon readings from
reaching much above 90 degrees in parts of Virginia, Maryland and
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure in Quebec will direct a weak cold front eastward
from the St. Lawrence Valley. Humid air streaming into the
Northeast will be lifted by the approaching front triggering
thunderstorms in the northern Appalachians. One or two storms may
reach the coast late in the day. Offshore winds will allow the
hotter air to reach most of the beaches of the Northeast despite
only partial hazy sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   A new disturbance, which came onshore in British Columbia on
Sunday, will strengthen as it crosses the prairies of southern
Canada. Its circulation will draw torrid air into the northern
Plains with record maximums possible. As hot air moves into the
western Great Lakes, a few storms will erupt.
</P>
<P>
   A ribbon of very humid air stretching through the Ohio Valley
will be the focus of scattered thunderstorms. Afternoon
thundershowers will develop along the Southeast and Gulf coasts as
well as in the southern Rockies and the mountains of southern
California. The hot weather in the interior Northwest will be
tempered, but more record highs are anticipated in the central
Rockies and California's Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: The Heat Crest
</P>
<P>
   The towns of Ely, Nev., Rawlins, Wyo., and Milford, Utah, each
established new all-time maximums on Saturday with readings of 101,
99 and 107 respectively. Another dozen new daily records also
occurred on Sunday. Despite the extreme heat during the daylight
hours, most sections saw readings fall into the 60s and upper 50s
at night. The arid climate of the Great Basin allows for 40 degree
day-to-night variations, even during a record heat wave. As the
heat moves east this week, it will combine with humid air to
produce oppressive conditions from the Plains to the Atlantic
seaboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
