A2240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      07-19 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proposal to Curb Discounts on Stock Plans Is Dropped
</P>
<P>
   Faced with opposition from the technology industry and other
companies, accounting rule makers have stepped away from a proposal
that had threatened to end certain lucrative employee-stock plans.
The rules relate to stock-purchase plans in which employees can buy
company stock at a discount of more than 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board had proposed that if
companies wanted to give employees what is effectively more than a
15 percent discount, they would have to treat the discount as an
expense. To avoid that expense, many companies were expected to
limit their stock programs. But the board has decided to drop the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt's Chief Is Leaving
</P>
<P>
   Michael Naumann, the mercurial and blunt-spoken chief executive
of Henry Holt &AMP; Co., will leave the literary publishing house that
he has headed for two years to pursue a chance to become Germany's
minister of culture for the Social Democrats. In his typical
maverick fashion, Naumann, 56, revealed his plans early on Friday
afternoon, when most publishers had retreated for long summer
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Test of `Spam' Buster to Begin
</P>
<P>
   Bright Light Technologies Inc., a company with perhaps the most
ambitious commercial attempt yet to combat junk e-mail _
unaffectionately known as spam _ plans to announce Monday that it
has begun distributing a test version of its system.
</P>
<P>
   Assessing the Latest Hot IPO
</P>
<P>
   Investors are apparently willing to overlook the current
technical limitations of Internet broadcasting. On Friday, shares
of Broadcast.com had the biggest first-day gain ever for the
initial public offering of an American stock, leaving one of the
founders, Mark Cuban, with a paper stake worth more than $350
million. Fans say the company will be well positioned as the
technology for Internet broadcasting improves. But some analysts
say the risk is at least as great as the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Debate Over Internet Access Taxes
</P>
<P>
   Taxing Internet users' access to cyberspace may become a
contentious political issue this fall in eight states if Congress
passes the Internet Tax Freedom Act. The legislation would
effectively ban taxes on Internet access, but it includes a
grandfather clause that would allow eight states to continue
imposing an existing tax.
</P>
<P>
   Galotti Leaves a Void at Vogue
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the hoopla over Tina Brown's decision to leave The New
Yorker, one aspect of the media deal was largely overlooked: that
Ronald Galotti, the brash publisher of Vogue who helped make the
magazine a success over the last several years, was defecting from
Conde Nast to join Ms. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   States Drop Part of Microsoft Suit
</P>
<P>
   Twenty states suing Microsoft for antitrust violations have
dropped an allegation that the software giant gives computer makers
illegal financial incentives to install its Windows Office software
instead of competing business applications.
</P>
<P>
   Picture a Tuna, Not a Duck
</P>
<P>
   A 32-year-old scuba-diving entrepreneur has patented a new type
of swim fin that he says will require a lot less exertion on the
part of divers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
