<DOCNO> NYT19980719.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TITAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-19 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITAN': FLUENT, COMPELLING ROCKEFELLER BIOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(jw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What may well be this summer's ideal book for vacation reading
is not a novel but a biography that has many of the best attributes
of a novel, Ron Chernow's ``Titan: The Life of John D. Rockefeller
Sr.'' Its narrative is wonderfully fluent and irresistibly
compelling. It is filled with outsize characters involved in
actions of great magnitude, as Aristotle might have said.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart is a great mystery, which is how one person could
have contained two such contradictory characters as John D.
Rockefeller Sr. did: on the one hand, the rapacious robber baron
who destroyed everything that stood in the path of making both
Standard Oil the ultimate industrial monopoly and himself the
world's richest man; on the other hand, the infinitely good-hearted
philanthropist who loved to make gifts of dimes and universities.
</P>
<P>
   How ``Titan'' addresses this mystery is perhaps its most
fascinating aspect. As Chernow (``The House of Morgan,'' ``The
Warburgs'') explains in his foreword, the deeper he dug into the
rich trove of material only partly tapped by the many previous
biographers of Rockefeller, the more he discovered that it was not
absolutely necessary to view Rockefeller as being either a devil or
an angel. Yet, he writes, ``like many moguls of the Gilded Age,
Rockefeller was either glorified by partisan biographers, who could
see no wrong, or vilified by vitriolic critics, who could see no
right.'' He adds, ``This one-sidedness has been especially harmful
in the case of Rockefeller, who was such an implausible blend of
sin and sanctity.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernow's approach to these contradictions in Rockefeller is to
record both views in all their extremes and then attempt to resolve
them. The key for him lies in Rockefeller's deep and abiding
involvement in evangelical Baptism, which committed him to good
works, obviously enough, but also justified his accumulation of
wealth as a sign God's favor.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty with this view is that presented in such simple
terms it makes Rockefeller's Bible thumping look like what Chernow
calls ``a cunning facade for the corporate pirate.'' So he takes
the further step of examining both the good and the bad sides of
Rockefeller more closely.
</P>
<P>
   The good had much more dimension to it, he concludes, than the
act of giving away millions implied. This can be seen in
Rockefeller's behavior outside of business, where he conducted
himself unostentatiously (unlike other 19th-century moguls) and
where he was apparently a quite lovable husband and father. It can
be seen in Chernow's portrait of the last four decades of
Rockefeller's nearly 10-decade life, when he lived in retirement,
seemed to grow mentally younger and more playful and, by mastering
the art of public relations, transformed himself into America's
most famous codger.
</P>
<P>
   And it can be seen in his approach to philanthropy, where he
sought above all not to publicize his generosity but to find the
most effective ways that his millions could benefit humanity. In
fact, to judge from Chernow's account, Rockefeller put almost as
much genius into giving his fortune away as he did into acquiring
it.
</P>
<P>
   And the bad was really not quite so bad, Chernow tries to show.
First, as he argues at length, Rockefeller's most eloquent critics,
Henry Demarest Lloyd and Ida Tarbell, exaggerated the record and
got many things wrong. Second, Rockefeller erred in thinking that
silence was the best answer to his critics and in not defending
himself against their attacks. Third, because his retirement from
Standard Oil in the mid-1890s was not made public, he was blamed
for the excesses of his overcombative successor, John D. Archbold.
Fourth, Standard Oil's pursuit of monopoly was done as much to
stabilize the market for oil products as it was to put the
competition out of business. And finally, in an age defined by
muckraking journalism, Rockefeller's sins were bound to be thrown
into too bold relief.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all Chernow excuses his subject's excesses, he also
makes it clear that Rockefeller, despite his tendency to sidestep
blame, was both aware of and often responsible for many things that
Standard Oil did wrong. And while ``Titan'' goes light on
psychobiography, it leaves the distinct impression that to the
extent that Rockefeller was exceeding God's command in storing up
his wealth, he was acting out of a complicated rage against his
pathologically ne'er-do-well father, who far too early in his son's
life undertook to victimize him financially.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chernow is impressively successful in reconciling
Rockefeller's contradictions _ as well as in showing how they
played themselves out in his children and grandchildren _ something
of the mystery remains. One would have liked to get a clearer sense
of how Rockefeller operated financially. For instance, at the
turning point in his early career when he successfully outbid his
former partners, the Clark brothers, for ownership of his first
refinery, one would have liked to learn how he got the financial
backing for his bid and what it meant to him and his backers when
the price far exceeded his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rockefeller is vividly present in these pages with all
the uncanny power that enabled him to build his great empire while
still a young man. You can feel the force of his mind and will, the
ferocious calculation that helped to shape an entire industrial
age.
</P>
<P>
   As Chernow writes in a typical passage: ``Beyond the size of his
stake, Rockefeller also possessed an unlikely charisma. He never
backslapped, roughhoused or skylarked with his colleagues, and his
statesmanlike calm evoked feelings of awe. As one reporter said in
1905, `No man, however unimpressionable he may be, can stand in the
presence of Mr. Rockefeller without feeling the repressed power of
the man.' He seemed to possess oracular powers. As Archbold
conceded, `Rockefeller always sees a little further than the rest
of us _ and then he sees around the corner.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's a character, in short, worthy of an epic novel. Which is
why ``Titan'' is a book to take to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TITAN'
</P>
<P>
   The Life of John D. Rockefeller Sr.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Chernow
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 774 pages. Random House. $30.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
