<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRODUCERS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST TRACK TO ANXIETY IN TV NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steven Goldstein's business is public relations and
television his medium, but when he encounters a reporter it is
usually only as a face on a television screen.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a press secretary in the Bush administration, he had
direct contact with television reporters instead of remote control
glimpses. Now, with the growth of news magazine shows, he said,
they rarely call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one time I was on a broadcast and my mother asked
me, `What's the reporter like?' And I said, `Mother, I never really
met the reporter,''' said Goldstein, now a spokesman for the trade
group of the Insurance Information Institute in New York who has
observed that ``you have the `faces' and you have the producers who
are doing all the work.''
</P>
<P>
   The evolving roles of television correspondents and producers
have come under an uncommon level of scrutiny with CNN's &UR;  &LR; decision
to retract a report that the U.S. military used nerve gas during
the war in Vietnam. The report was broadcast on the premier of a
news magazine show, ``Newsstand,'' a joint venture with Time
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent dismissals of two CNN producers and the awkward
claim by the correspondent involved, Peter Arnett, that he was a
``face'' with minimal participation in the sensitive project has
rattled many television producers who argue that accomplished
correspondents preside over stories like tough editors, although
they concede such involvement varies.
</P>
<P>
   The territory of television producers is a changing, highly
competitive world, with prime-time news programs like CBS' ``60
Minutes'' and NBC's &UR;  &LR; ``Dateline NBC'' making up half of the
country's top 10 shows during the doldrums of July and summer
reruns. Earlier last week, CBS announced that it would expand ``60
Minutes'' into a second edition, underscoring the importance of
prime-time news magazines as a reliable profit center for networks.
</P>
<P>
   The general expansion of prime-time news magazine shows has
created new opportunity for producers, but raised some concerns
among them that the competitive environment has increased their
responsibilities and intensified potential journalistic hazards _
from accelerating the careers of less experienced producers to
raising the volume of news stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that very many correspondents just come in and read
scripts _ I think that's most uncommon,'' said Tom Bettag, the
executive producer of ABC's ``Nightline.'' ``There are many more
dangers now in a much more pressured budget environment where the
news divisions are expected to make larger profits.''
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of news magazine programs, he said, ``is making
everybody work faster,'' adding: ``There isn't enough talent.
Everybody is ratcheting up the speed with which they work and
that's totally wrong. There are times that people are saying this
is an inefficient use of resources and that's perfectly
appropriate. There are other times when you can work too fast and
make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But other producers see benefits in the competition and see no
decline in quality, arguing, for example, that with enhanced
technology like satellite transmissions, it is easier to work
quickly. ``Competition sometimes makes it harder to do a job, but
that in no way means you can be any less diligent in terms of
checking out a story,'' said an ABC producer, Bret Marcus, who is
leaving the network for CNBC to take charge of Geraldo Rivera's
coming news show.
</P>
<P>
   Producers are the journalists who track down impossible facts
with the cunning of hunters _ booking the camera crew, searching
for sources, finding the location, writing the script, editing the
material _ and all for salaries that are usually 10 times less than
what correspondents make.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many times when producers write 95 percent of what
is read, but it's not as if it's not done in consultation with the
reporter,'' said one veteran network producer. ``But in order for
the star system to function _ where you have news magazines
becoming vehicles for high-priced talent _ you need them on the
air. It's a star system, which requires that correspondents get
maximum air time, and by doing that it assigns more stories than
they can possibly report in full.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the standard career path of a producer is a
journalism school graduate who starts as a $20,000-a-year desk or
production assistant for one of the networks, answering telephones
and scanning wire reports, and then, with on-the-job training,
rises through various ranks to a producer earning from $70,000 to
$275,000 a year. In some ways it is an insecure profession, since
most producers work on multiyear contracts with benefits, and in
some cases travel from 30 to 80 percent of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And, as producers colorfully describe it, their relationships
with the more visible correspondents are usually symbiotic
connections _ the bonds of a boxer and a manager, the earned trust
of a married couple, the spiritual connection between a composer
and a lyricist. The correspondent, according to producers, is
expected to challenge material and to play, in some respects, the
role of a demanding editor, who is checking facts and questioning
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The producer and the correspondent are a team,'' said Neal
Shapiro, the executive producer of ``Dateline NBC,'' a news
magazine that is expanding to five nights a week of programming in
August and employs 75 producers and 19 correspondents. ``The
producers do a lot of the initial reporting and they may gather a
lot of the material, but the two of them collaborate and the
correspondents have to do the interviews that are vital to the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the CNN episode, Shapiro said he met with
the Dateline staff to urge them to be more vigilant and careful,
but he added that Arnett's detached relationship with his CNN
producers could not exist under his program's news-gathering
system.
</P>
<P>
   But other producers are less confident that the industry's
built-in safeguards provide sufficient checks and balances against
mistakes in a fast and fiercely competitive situation, in which a
higher volume of stories are being produced; some said that a
similar episode could happen anywhere.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
