<DOCNO> NYT19980719.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PRODUCERS-MEDIA-2N     07-19 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRODUCERS-MEDIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: happen anywhere. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Go by the arithmetic,'' said Martin Koughan, an Emmy-winning
free-lance producer in Sonoma, Calif., who spent much of his career
working on network television and CNN's investigative unit. ``Now
there's five times as much news on the air and there's much more
pressure on the correspondents and much more reliance on the
producers.''
</P>
<P>
   Koughan, 49, said that many of his contemporaries were part of a
flight of network veterans who had pulled out of the industry
because of misgivings about the commercialization of news to seek
occupations as free-lancers, university teachers and even a dairy
farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simplest reason why I left is that quality has gone
down,'' he said, ``Everyone is trying to figure out what people
want to see and then feed it to them. If the only thing that you're
trying to do is titillate, then the point of a story is not even
relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lewis, a former network producer and now the executive
director of the Center for Public Integrity, a watchdog group that
studies ethics and public service, divides the television
industry's producers into two culturally distinct categories, those
who cover breaking stories for the nightly news whose reporting
workloads usually equal the correspondents', and those who are
developing longer feature stories for the news magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the news magazine mode, where the correspondent is handling
25 stories a year and the producer is handling about five, the
editorial load is more substantially handled by the producer and
the correspondent finds himself or herself less and less engaged in
each piece,'' he said. ``So the burden ends up being on the
correspondent to fight the impulse to be on autopilot.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some producers are worrying that the expansion
of news programming is speeding along the careers of younger
producers who have learned more about production techniques than
conventional journalistic skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do get a lot of young assistant producers who are really
smart and really want to learn and just pick it up along the way,''
said a senior producer with ABC, who added, though, that, ``I don't
see enough of a degree of skepticism.''
</P>
<P>
   At ``60 Minutes,'' the dean of news magazine programming,
several producers said that show and ABC's ``Nightline'' maintained
newsrooms where producers and correspondents devised their own
story ideas and maintained close working relationships, in contrast
with Arnett's description of his detached relationship with his
producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship is one of earned trust and you're in this
together,'' but there's always a tension because the correspondent
knows that the producer has the most information, said David
Gelber, an executive producer at CBS News.
</P>
</TEXT>
