<HEADER>
A2248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN20-COX     07-19 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Memories get in way when I map directions
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some friends from the coast are paying their first
visit to Sweet Apple. They called the other day and suggested that
I fax them a map.
</P>
<P>
   I love to make maps, and I was all ready to sit down and turn
artist, until I remembered my son-in-law next door, a man of
technical and artistic turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever made a map for out here?'' I asked him. He said
he had, and, furthermore, he and his computer would transmit a copy
to my friends on the coast. It was too good an offer to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   He brought a copy of the map over after I had gone to bed,
leaving it on the kitchen table. It is spare, clean and concise.
The Department of Transportation would approve.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not my kind of map. I have a favorite approach to Sweet
Apple that may not be as direct, but that lifts my heart and
enlivens my spirit when I travel that way. He notes highway numbers
and traffic lights. I would put in pretty country churches and
graveyards.
</P>
<P>
   And, unfortunately, I put in memories. I would want to note that
that shopping center messed up the spot where the Hawkinses, of the
seed-and-feed store, lived. I loved their old yard and once climbed
their magnolia tree to get branches to decorate the cabin for my
husband Jack's nephew's wedding. I fell out of the tree (magnolia
is so brittle), landing in a patch of poison ivy, and scratched all
during the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the Hawkinses' house was gone, the old cellar hole
was there, framed by all manner of flowers. Now a chicken
restaurant, a bank and a branch of Radio Shack occupy that ground.
The temptation to include what was, instead of what is, is my
failing as a map maker.
</P>
<P>
   My son-in-law left off graveyards. I count them irreplaceable
landmarks. I would try to work in the tombstones of Dessie and Lum
Crow, dear departed neighbors. Mr. Crow found a bargain in
tombstones and bought a handsome one well before it was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want to see our tomb rock?'' he asked me one day. ``But you're
a long way from dying!'' I protested. He laughed. ``You never know
what your young'uns will do after you're dead,'' he joked. And he's
so right.
</P>
<P>
   That ``tomb rock'' is in Ebenezer Methodist Church cemetery.
There's another one I like to point out a bit down the road, beside
Union Primitive Baptist Church. Our good friends Quinton and Nellie
Johnson are buried there, and I never pass that way without a pang
of regret for their going. Quinton helped us shore up the cabin, a
slow-moving, amiable carpenter who was always accompanied by a
swirl of puppies and who was the source of many good stories. A map
to Sweet Apple is a barren document without Quinton.
</P>
<P>
   The big square white house where the Dangars lived is not there.
The space was usurped by a subdivision, but I remember well where
the barn stood, notable to my Jack and to our friend Doc Smellie
because it held all kinds of parts needed for work on a log cabin.
And somewhere near the bottom of the barrel, there was a bottle of
homemade brandy, which refreshed borrowers in their labors.
</P>
<P>
   No use to put on the map that the Denver Coxes lived up on that
hill, and Mrs. Cox made the best butter you ever put on a biscuit.
There's a vast white mansion in the place where Olivia and Clarence
Johnson lived in a cozy, hospitable tar-papered house.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that memories do not a map make. So I'll just go
along with my son-in-law's computerized effort, and to be safe,
I'll walk down the road to meet my friends.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Mondays, Wednesdays, Fridays and Sundays .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
