<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK20-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Braves Notebook
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Stinson
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Before you ask, John Schuerholz wants you to know there is no
bullpen contingency plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no Plan A or Plan B. It's just Plan Reality,'' the
Braves general manager said. ''I would bet every call that somebody
who is a rotisserie league general manager would be expected to
make, I've made.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves decline to place a deadline on Mark Wohlers' return
to form, beyond the July 31 trading deadline. Schuerholz has
plumbed the market for closers but has a history of waiting until
the final hours the deadline. He dealt Mike Stanton an hour before
the deadline in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to offer (Wohlers) as much of an opportunity as
possible,'' Schuerholz said. ''At the same time, we're not going to
compromise and can't compromise and wouldn't compromise the
integrity of our approach to each game, which is to win. If Mark is
pitching well enough to come into situations to preserve wins,
he'll be given that opportunity. If he's not, he won't. A lot of
that is determined from work on the side, work in the bullpen, his
work in games.''
</P>
<P>
   But at what point does Wohlers have to prove his ability to
retain his old job?
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can't do something before July 31, it's very unlikely to
me and to most people that we're going to be able to do anything of
any substantial nature to reorganize (the closer) situation,''
Schuerholz said. '' So the reality is that in two weeks, whatever
moves we make _ whether to support Mark in his role or to alter the
construct with respect to the closer especially _ is going to have
to be done prior to that.''
</P>
<P>
   False alarm
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz came straight out of his chair in the ninth inning
when, with one out, Milwaukee's Fernando Vina sent a line drive
right back at pitcher Kerry Ligtenberg, striking him on the right
hand. He was able to finish the inning, post-game X-rays were
negative and Ligtenberg said he expects to be available tonight.
But the Braves came that close to losing their closer. Had the ball
not hit him on the meatiest part of the hand, it might have been
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a second, I thought it was going to hit me in the face,''
Lightenberg said. ''I didn't see it right away. The only thing you
can do is just stick your hand up. That's your first reaction. The
things is, I thought I could have thrown him out too but I couldn't
feel my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker sits again
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Tucker's slump stretching to 5-for-38 this month,
manager Bobby Cox gave his right fielder his second day off within
five games, granting Curtis Pride another start. That Pride had two
RBI and a home run hardly went unnoticed by management. This is
Tucker's deepest slump since he joined the Braves, his average down
to .258. His average last year never fell below .269 and that was
even after a .237 July.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been hitting so much, it might be too much,'' said
manager Bobby Cox. ''He's got to get back to one or two keys.''
</P>
<P>
   July has not been kind to Cox's left-handed platoon. Besides
Tucker, second baseman Keith Lockhart (who was also given the day
off against right-handed Jeff Juden) is in a 2-for-23 slide since
the All-Star break. Between them, Tucker and Lockhart are hitting
.165 (13-for-79) this month.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Plate umpire Harry Wendelstedt lasted into the eighth before
yielding to dehydration from the oppressive heat. He retired to the
umpires dressing room three batters into the eighth, when he was
replaced by Jerry Layne. . . . Andruw Jones' batting streak ended
at eight games. . . . John Rocker has a growing constituency. When
Cox went out to remove him after Rocker struck out Jeromy Burnitz
in the eighth, Cox was booed. . . . Walt Weiss, nursing a sore
right quadricep, led off the Braves first with one of the slowest
triples in memory, forced to jog on to third base when Jeromy
Burnitz lost his ball in the right field corner. ''I was kind of
hoping he'd pick the ball up,'' Weiss said. ''I didn't want to keep
running.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
