<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISHOPEN-BISHER20-     07-19 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-BISHER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Meara takes his breaks
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ They will be talking of it for years, the
finishing round of the 1998 British Open at Royal Birkdale. A
weekend of frontrunners from off the continent, featuring a
tenacious American faintly known in his own land, had been
embellished only by the rise of a fresh star off the amateur bush,
another Justin _ in this case, a 17-year-old Rose from Hampshire.
So what began as a field of 2,336 aspirants who paid a fee of 80
pound sterling for the chance, boiled down to two, and then to one,
the champion, Mark O'Meara of Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the middle 36 holes, Brian Watts, the 32-year-old
Oklahoman whose tournament office is Japan, held the lead, and even
into the gloaming of Sunday he still had a piece of it. It was
shared with O'Meara, the Masters champion, who never wins the easy
way. He never led the Masters until his final putt. Here, he had to
go four extra holes to beat Watts and win a bookend major to go
with the green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara took the lead with a birdie on the par-5 17th hole, then
Watts matched that, but it was a bunker shot from greenside on the
18th that sent the championship into overtime. ''That bunker shot
on the 72nd hole was as great as any shot I've ever seen,'' even
O'Meara was moved to say. From an awkward stance and everything on
the line, Watts' blast wound up eight inches from the cup. It was a
classic clutch shot, necessary to keep the championship alive. The
marvel of the last two days was that Watts' perfectly honed swing
never bent under the strain of such a pursuit of glory.
</P>
<P>
   The weather calmed after a morning rain. The wind lowered, and
generally the improved conditions were reflected in the scores. For
instance, Justin Leonard, the defending champion who had suffered
through a round of 82 Saturday, recovered with a 69 and was joyful.
''Now I don't feel so bad as a defending champion.''
</P>
<P>
   The move of the day, though, and the creator of mass excitement
was none other than Tiger Woods, who had led the first day, then
shot himself in the foot with a round of 77 Saturday. He was one
under par on the front nine, then turned on the juice and birdied
three of the last four holes. But there was a wall of players in
front of him, consisting of:
</P>
<P>
   Watts _ they still can't believe he's for real over here, and
British papers have done a job of ignoring him, even after leading
two rounds. Canadian? American? Japanese? What a strange career.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk _ the guy with the swing not yet approved by Good
Housekeeping, or David Leadbetter. Poor fellow, he couldn't make a
putt and hung in around two over par until the end.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik _ the eccentric Swede with the upturn capbill,
volcanic dust in his diet, and runnerup the past two years at
Turnberry and Troon.
</P>
<P>
   And, O'Meara _ very nice but uninspiring personality, round
face, body contours of an insurance salesman, 41-year-old
latter-day copy of Bill Casper. And who would become the oldest
player to win two majors championships the same year.
</P>
<P>
   His Orlando neighbor Woods, however, kept shooting at him. With
eight holes to play, the 22-year-old had four strokes to make up.
He got three off them, chipping in on the 17th hole and sinking a
cross-country putt on the 18th. He could only sit and wait, and
when O'Meara and Watts closed him out, he took the stand.
</P>
<P>
   ''Finishing third is not something to be upset about,'' he said.
''My goal was to hit 14 fairways and 18 greens. It didn't work out
that way. I had to scramble a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club's sensible playoff style, the
matter is resolved before moonrise. Four holes between the
combatants, then sudden death only if the issued isn't resolved by
then. O'Meara took the advantage on the 15th hole with a birdie to
Watts' par, and in the end, that was the margin. They matched pars
on the 16th and 17th, but Watts put his approach in another
greenside bunker at 18 again, and this time there was no miracle
left in his bag.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully, I've moved up a notch,'' Watts said, a striking
fellow with a manner you had to like. ''If you'd told me a week ago
that I'd be in a playoff in the greatest championship in the world,
I wouldn't have believed you. I'm proud of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara was in the final pairing in The Open last played here in
1991, tied with Ian Baker-Finch for the lead. The Australian blew
him out with a final round of 66, including a 29 on th frontside.
''Later, I dropped into his home to congratulate him again, and he
invited me to have a sip out of the claret jug,'' O'Meara said. ''I
knew then I wanted one of these for my own, and now I have it. It
is an incredible feeling to have won two majors in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Twilight was falling. Victory was a balm to the nerves frayed by
four days of warfare on the most demanding of courses where The
Open is contested. You think back now to an incident that could
have been calamitous, when a tee shot was lost Saturday afternoon.
After a search of legal length, O'Meara was headed back to hit a
second tee shot when the ball was found. By the time O'Meara could
return to the spot, some nervy spectator had pocketed the ball.
O'Meara was allowed a drop, and after further review by officials,
no penalty was assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Of such, said the champion, are the breaks of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
