<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-WRAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBAF weathers problems, wraps first decade
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Atlanta's major public arts festivals weather difficult
transition phases, the actual presence of the National Black Arts
Festival is a statement. This year's 10th anniversary event _ the
biennenial NBAF's fifth season overall _ often felt more like a
consolidation of festivals past than a leap forward toward the
millennium. And yet, there's nothing else like it anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which concluded its 10-day run Sunday, lived up to
its theme of ``Art Beyond Borders,'' linking artists from the
African diaspora whether they were a Nigerian Nobel Prize-winner or
a Southside Chicago saxophonist, whether they weaved baskets or
produced cutting-edge hip-hop videos. Major flaws persisted _
ticketing problems, scheduling glitches, information flow among
them. So did the major talent.
</P>
<P>
   Though an official attendance estimate was not available Sunday
_ the festival had been looking for 1.5 million people to buy
tickets for shows or visit one of the many artists' panels _ many
venues were consistently full. Sometimes, though, attendance varied
wildly. Star attractions _ such as poet Maya Angelou and vocalist
Abbey Lincoln _ played to packed, or close enough, houses. But the
same night Angelou read for 2,600 fans, festival regulars Olu Dara
and Dianne McIntyre drew less than 100 to their dance-theater
collaboration. Meanwhile, a fringe-minded program, the three-day
jazz festival ''(Re)soundings,'' drew an SRO audience of 250 to
Hill Auditorium that, an NBAF rarity, was predominantly white.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people that I've never had the opportunity to see
perform live,'' said Rob Cambre, a 29-year-old DJ from New Orleans,
about the jazz summit and its international roster. ``It's
aamazing...there are so many of them here in a three-day period.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad response for a festival starting its second decade.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
