</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'NewsRadio' to address death of Hartman
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The late Phil Hartman's character, Bill
McNeil, will be given a funeral on the season opener of
''NewsRadio'' Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The cast ''coudn't go back to work without a formal process on
the stage for dealing with the loss of Phil,'' NBC Entertanment
president Warren Littlefield said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Phil was not just an ensemble character,'' Littlefield said.
''He was the dad on the set to a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Littlefield said ''NewsRadio'' executive producer Paul Simms is
working on the script, in which the cast will be told that McNeil
has died suddenly of a heart attack. Hartman was shot and killed by
his wife, who then committed suicide, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   ''Knowing this group, it will be entertaining, irreverent and
full of love,'' Littlefield said.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Lovitz, a friend of Hartman's since their days together on
''Saturday Night Live,'' will be introduced in the second episode
as a new character who will be taking McNeil's job as news anchor.
''He'll be filled with insecurities,'' Littlefield said, referring
to the character, not Lovitz.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to the Television Critics Association, Littlefield
also:
</P>
<P>
   _ Said that NBC is looking into ''partners and affiliations''
with other media companies, but it's too soon to tell if anything
will happen, let alone what will happen. There have been reports of
discussions with Barry Diller, head of USA Network, as well as
rumors of possible deals with Sony or Viacom. ''It seems today that
size does matter,'' he said. ''But a few years back we were in
discussions with Turner. Didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Acknowledged that ''Veronica's Closet,'' despite its key time
slot before ''ER'' on Thursdays, has not lived up to its potential.
He quoted Marta Kaufmann, one of the show's producers, as saying
''We have to do a better show. We let you down this year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Said that the decision to move ''Frasier'' to 9 p.m. Thursdays
this coming season basically came down to economics. ''Friends''
and ''Just Shoot Me'' were both strong finalists for what has
traditionally been the most-watched spot in prime time, but NBC
felt advertisers would pay the highest rates for ''Frasier'' in
that position.
</P>
<P>
   _ Announced a new prime-time animated show, ''Stressed Eric,''
that wil be given a summer tryout starting Aug. 12. The show
originally aired on the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   She thinks you're swell too, Garry
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Garry Shandling used the occasion of winning the
Television Critics Association award for best comedy for ''The
Larry Sanders Show'' to hit on ''Ally McBeal'' star Calista
Flockhart. Taking the podium, Shandling declared: '' 'Ally McBeal'
deserves this award. Calista Flockhart is the most talented
actress. You're single, right?'' he asked, looking at Flockhart in
the audience. Later, Flockhart went to the same podium to accept
the TCA award for Best New Program for ''Ally,'' and cooed to
Shandling, ''I want Garry to come up.'' After the awards ceremony,
Shandling and Flockhart went to the bar at the Ritz-Carlton
Pasadena (where the awards were held) to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Roone Arledge, chairman of ABC News and former head of ABC
Sports, was given the Career Achievement Award. ''As someone who
dealt with Howard Cosell and Sam Donaldson, I think I do richly
deserve this award,'' Arledge said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks accepted two awards for his HBO miniseries ''From the
Earth to the Moon:'' Best Movie or Miniseries and Program of the
Year. ''Homicide: Life on the Street'' won Best Drama for the third
straight year. It usually is not even nominated for an Emmy for
Best Drama, and executive producer Tom Fontana said of the Emmy
nominations (due out this week), ''As far as I'm concerned, the big
awards are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Also winning: David Hyde Pierce (''Frasier'') for Best
Individual in a Comedy, Andre Braugher (''Homicide'') for Best
Individual in a Drama; ''The American Experience'' for Best
News/Information Program, and ''Blue's Clues'' for Best Children's
Program.
</P>
<P>
   'Homicidal' explorations
</P>
<P>
   ''Homicide'' may have lost Braugher at the end of last season,
but it gets fresh blood when it returns Sept. 25. Michael Michelle
(''New York Undercover'') plays Det. Rene Sheppard, a former beauty
pageant queen turned homicide detective, and Giancarlo Esposito
(''Do the Right Thing'') will pay Mike Giardello, estranged son of
the show's Lt. Al Giardello (Yaphet Kotto). Producer Fontana said
the confused bisexuality of Det. Bayliss (Kyle Secor) will continue
to be explored next season, even though ''the network (NBC) hates
it, the network wants it to go away.'' Not so, said Littlefield.
''What we did ask was how long are you going to keep this
ambiguous?''
</P>
<P>
   Sex, plugs, rock n' roll... .
</P>
<P>
   Scary thought for the day: Drew Carey and Mimi (Kathy Kinney),
his cosmetically challenged nemesis on ''The Drew Carey Show,''
will have sex this coming season. ''Well, they have a kind of
sex,'' Carey added, and then wouldn't divulge any more details
about that episode. Carey also says that he and his friends wil
form a rock band this year with him as lead singer, and they'll
cram an episode with guest-star rockers ''auditioning'' for the
band. Signed so far: former Guns N Roses guitarist Slash and singer
Lisa Loeb.
</P>
<P>
   Will it sell in Kansas?
</P>
<P>
   Jenna Elfman, the first half of ''Dharma and Greg,'' is sporting
alarmingly dyed platinum hair these days. She dyed it for the movie
she's currently filming, ''Town and Country,'' with Warren Beatty.
''I don't know if I'll keep it when we go back into production'' on
the TV show, she says. ''It may be a little extreme for Middle
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'll practice in Fargo
</P>
<P>
   William Macy doubts that he'll return to ''ER.'' In one of this
past season's more memorable story lines, his character, Dr.
Morgenstern, had a kind of professional breakdown, botched a
surgery and resigned. Although it would be just like ''ER'' to
bring him back, he say he's heard nothing from producers and is
planning his movie career (which included the sleazebag husband in
''Fargo'') as if he won't do any more ''ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
