<HEADER>
A2255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-NOTEBOOK20-COX     07-19 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-NOTEBOOK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sights and sounds of the festival: a critics' notebook
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This much is certain: It's not every 10 days in
Atlanta when such a diverse, intensely focused and historic array
of musicians, poets, novelists, critics, filmmakers, dancers,
painters, photographers, actors, directors, political figures, and
deeply engaged audiences troupe through the city.
</P>
<P>
   Enough to make the National Black Arts Festival's
much-publicized struggles seem secondary to its triumphs. This
year, there were scary budget woes (as usual), scary infrastructure
woes (as usual), and an incoming artistic director, former NBAF
music curator and Emory University professor Dwight Andrews, who
had a lot of non-artistic tangles to tame.
</P>
<P>
   If the festival roster was often a ``greatest hits'' scenario,
reprising high points of previous gatherings, then it was
undeniably consistent. Programs that worked before worked again
(and difficulties that beset the fest continued to beset it). There
also, however, were promising introductions of new creative
concepts, which underscored the NBAF's mission to display ``Art
Beyond Borders.''
</P>
<P>
   The following notes, observations and comments are from the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution critics Steve Dollar, Sonia Murray and
Wendell Brock:
</P>
<P>
   _ Poet and literary titan Maya Angelou sold out Symphony Hall on
Thursday. ``There is no hiding place down here,'' she sang, opening
what would be a two-hour show of poetry, song, story-telling and
personal observations centered around that theme. ``That this arts
festival has remained here and remained vital says a lot of people
know there is no hiding place down here,'' Angelou noted. ``We have
to come out and come together and celebrate. Art, poetry, courtesy,
civility, grace, that's really how we've survived down here.'' (SM)
</P>
<P>
   _ Phyllis Yvonne Stickney's one-woman show may now be considered
a staple at the festival, but that does not render it any less
significant. Her searing take on the world left many in the
capacity crowd walking out of the show.The topics of her
``edu-tainment,'' as she calls it, ranged from the self-hatred
within the black community, to how important it is to be computer
savvy, to how some in Atlanta, ``the supposed black mecca'', are
oblivious to how racist the society is. ``My heart don't pump no
Kool-Aid,'' Stickney said. ``I ain't scared.'' (SM)
</P>
<P>
   _ Harry Allen's insightful ``Hip-Hop Music Video Giga-Film
Festival'' spent two hours Tuesday helping the capacity crowd
rethink rap video. ``If there is any problem that hip-hop, and as
an extension hip-hop video, has, it's coming up with a correct,
true and just depiction of black femininity,'' he said as he
introduced videos from the rigid Queen Latifah, an unabashedly
sexual Lil' Kim and Apache. It was a jarring presentation. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the more inspired segments of the festival,
``(Re)soundings'' illustrated with vigor and imagination how an
African-American creative form _ jazz improvisation _ has swept the
world. The three-evening event reflected a key period in NBAF
artistic director Dwight Andrews' own musical life, and his abiding
personal connections to visionaries such as Chicago-born trumpeter
Wadada Leo Smith and British saxophonist Evan Parker created
warmth.The music was a kaleidoscope, shifting through colors and
perspectives, always tilting. One set, by Chicago's DKV Trio with
tenor saxophonist Fred Anderson, was fervent and uplifting;
another, by a German trio that featured trombonist Conrad Bauer and
bassist Peter Kowald, became a thoroughly entertaining showcase for
drummer Gunter ``Baby'' Sommer, who makes percussion a nimble form
of performance art. Even the dry, more studiously ``avant-garde''
pieces got standing ovations, and the rare Southern appearances by
folks such as Parker and reedsman Roscoe Mitchell drew attendees
from across the region. (SD)
</P>
<P>
   _ Olu Dara strums his guitar, and Dianne McIntyre flutters about
as if her body is being plucked. The Urban Bush Women's
butt-shaking antics provoke audience members to stand and shout:
``Go, girls!''
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted art beyond boundaries, this was it. But if the
NBAF's three concert dance programs were meant to reflect the
diaspora _ with African, Caribbean, Latin and urban influences _
they did not succeed. Instead, what was on the program appeared to
be more a measure of who was available at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NBAF audiences _ unlike the Atlanta populace at large _
are a faithful crowd. For an unadvertised Monday night performance
of ``Diverse Duets,'' the 900-seat Rialto was nearly two-thirds
full. Too bad that two of the pieces weren't quite ready to be
shown _ or that two of the ``duets'' turned out to be full-ensemble
performances.
</P>
<P>
   The NBAF should understand that really good artists are really
busy. If it wants to sign Garth Fagan, Bill T. Jones, Rennie Harris
or the Alvin Ailey American DanceTheater _ to import acts from
outside the country or commission new work _ it would do well to
plan ahead. Otherwise, it may find that its audience isn't as
forgiving, or as hungry, as it was this year. (WB)
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roots and Branches Folk Art and Vendors Market at Piedmont
Park, a daily affair that also featured live music, seemed lost to
much of its potential crowd. Africa Fete, a lively package tour
boasting some of the most entertaining names in African pop music,
attracted a few hundred listeners on the festival's first Sunday.
Withering heat and a rain delay were obvious discouragements, but
the outdoor events could have used a promotional boost equal to
some of the considerable talent booked. This aspect of the NBAF
needs rethinking. (SD)
</P>
<P>
   _ An expanded approach to late-night jam sessions, site of the
NBAF's popular social scene, was a cool notion. But late Saturday
an unexpectedly scaled back version of the fest-closing spectacle
``The Big Dance'' meant that instead of an African-American history
lesson in dance, there was ... a jam session. Or close enough.
``Everyone was waiting around for something to happen but nothing
happened,'' said George King, an Atlanta filmmaker and music
enthusiast. ``The last one (in 1996) was so good, I remember it
vividly.'' Still, King noted, ``Olu (Dara) was jamming and people
were dancing.'' (SD)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
