<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RETOOLING' PROVIDES PERSONAL EXPERIENCE WITH WONDERS OF HEALTH
CARE 
</HEADLINE>
 _ COLUMN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ](begin itals)In a series of columns ending next Sunday, C.W.
Gusewelle tells of his recent ``retooling.'' He doesn't imagine his
personal medical adventures are of any special interest or
importance. But nearly everyone, as the years turn, requires an
occasional repair. And when the need arises, it's comforting to be
reminded what wonders U.S. health-care professionals can
deliver.(end itals)
</P>
<P>
   Old sins and misdemeanors have to be paid for.
</P>
<P>
   The thousand visits to the doughnut shop...the incomparable,
companionable weed (was there ever anyone, for Pete's sake, who
didn't (begin itals)know(end itals) tobacco was addictive?)...the
sausage gravy over biscuits, and the cream pies in country cafes...
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later they'll come back to haunt you. So the past week
was spent settling accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Actually it began last month in an offhand way, during an
otherwise uneventful medical exam. Our family physician also is a
friend. We have skied together and followed the growing up of one
another's children. He genuinely cares.
</P>
<P>
   And he's a careful man. During the course of the physical _
toward the last, as I recall _ he put his stethoscope to the side
of my neck.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent days I've mentioned this to any number of folks I
know, people who are mindful of their health. Very few could
remember a doctor ever listening in that area. To the chest and
back, yes, but not the neck.
</P>
<P>
   His brow furrowed just the least bit. He moved the instrument to
the other side, then back to the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you had any dizzy spells?'' he wanted to know. ``Any bad
headaches or trouble speaking? Or numbness or tingling in your
hands?''
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't. There'd been no symptoms whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I hear something there in the carotid I don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   The carotid arteries, one on each side of the neck, are the
vessels through which the heart supplies oxygenated blood to the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get you in for a sonogram,'' he said. ``It's
called a Doppler, and they do it right downstairs here.''
</P>
<P>
   The next week I was on an examining table in a darkened room.
Sound impulses, bouncing off red corpuscles as they passed through
the artery, translated into images on a monitor. Meantime, in the
next room, a doctor was analyzing the pictures in greater detail.
</P>
<P>
   An hour the test took, or a bit longer. Then the doctor came in
to report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right side's clear,'' he said. ``But there's a problem on
the left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The left carotid is 80 to 99 percent blocked. It can be
corrected surgically, but until that's done you could be at serious
risk for a stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   The news was dismaying for more reasons than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going with my family to Alaska the last half of August,''
I told him. ``Everything's set, and I don't want to cancel. I don't
have any symptoms. So is there any reason I can't deal with this in
September, after we get back?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You might be lucky,'' he said. ``But if it were me, with
blockage like that, I wouldn't wait two months.''
</P>
<P>
   The test results were forwarded to my physician, who also
counseled against delay.
</P>
<P>
   He gave me the name and phone number of the surgeon he would
recommend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call him right away, and get on his schedule. I'd say you
could have the operation and be fully recovered in time for the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``But since we're thinking about surgery, it would be a good
idea to check out your heart on the treadmill.'' He leafed through
my records. ``Your last stress test was, what, seven years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   So yet another referral was made, this one to a cardiology
group.
</P>
<P>
   And the treadmill was trod upon.
</P>
<P>
   A radioactive substance, thallium, was injected and computer
images rendered.
</P>
<P>
   From those, certain conclusions could be drawn. But those
conclusions would be in some degree subjective. Because medicine,
although it's a science, also remains very much an art.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing surely known was that 10 days later I would
report as an outpatient to St. Luke's Hospital for a
catheter-and-dye test to confirm the blockage of the carotid
artery.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on those results, what else might be done to me, and
when, remained to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   I felt hemmed round by a confounding array of uncertainties _ an
odd predicament for someone who'd walked into his doctor's office
the previous month imagining himself perfectly fit.
</P>
</TEXT>
