<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-DENIM-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE DEEP DARK BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ These are dark days for denim.
</P>
<P>
   Rich, deep, dense indigo is moving onto the mainstream fashion
charts. After almost two decades, stone and acid washes are being
nudged out of the spotlight. Ditto for the torn, hole-ridden jeans
and faded finishes that reflect years of wear and many tumbles in
the bleach cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The look began in Europe a few seasons ago. Influential designer
Helmet Lang set it on the runway about four years ago. Names such
as Gucci and Versace followed up to help give it the must-have
status.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese, for one, have had very significant roles in the
development of the textiles, says Sarah Clancy, product manager in
new product development for the Lee Co. in Merriam, Kan. And the
look emerged early on the streets of Tokyo, London and Paris. A
European company called G Star was among the first to push it
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as the Gap and Levi Strauss have been taking it
mainstream for the spring season. And now fashion magazines feature
the darks in ads and editorials from the likes of Gucci, DKNY and
Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of some Versace pieces delivered to us in
error, we would not carry anything but dark,'' says Todd Dean, the
owner of Loma Vista Hardware in Kansas City, Mo., which carries
men's designer sportswear from Lang, Dolce &AMP; Gabanna and Versace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely red hot,'' says David Wolfe, the fashion
director for Doneger Inc., a retail consulting service in New York.
``It's given new life to denim. In fact, we're calling it the
born-again denim.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason the darker color has found such an audience in part
is that it is a fresh approach at a time when old faded denim is
widespread. ``It's another option, especially for the kids who live
in jeans,'' says Cassie Ederer, a spokeswoman for Levi Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the appeal is nostalgia. Among the young, to
whom the look is totally new, there is a quest for something real,
Clancy says. ``There is a real interest in an authentic heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend also was spawned by the increasing popularity in the
past decade of vintage blue jeans and the lucrative market for them
in the United States and around the world, says Levi's Ederer. ``We
just looked back to the original denim we were making 125 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The look was first adapted by the fashion-forward who started
wearing stiff _ what the industry calls raw or hard _ dark denim
that they wore, broke in to their own proportions and then washed.
</P>
<P>
   ``About two years ago, we started getting requests from
forward-trendy cities for the look of the original unwashed
denim,'' Ederer says.
</P>
<P>
   There are now a variety of options in dark denim finishes,
styles and textile weights. Some colors are more intense than
others, depending on the number of dips in the dye, Clancy says.
</P>
<P>
   You can find Lee Dungarees, for instance, with the raw finish in
the stiff-break-in-your-own denim or original straight leg in a
rinsed softer fabric. Choose from bib overalls in a rinse finish or
prance around in dark, stiffer wide legs. For fall 1999, Lee is
developing a dark denim with the look of the raw and feel of the
soft.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's current advertising campaign is headlined ``Hard Jeans''
and runs with captions such as ``You Break These in, You've Got
Something'' and ``You Want Something Soft, Call a Man.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the mainstream appeal now is that dark denim is a
more versatile look that can be dressed up and down with anything
from leather jackets and tank tops to blazers and beading. It
emerges at a time in which young people, especially, are seeking
ways to set themselves apart with their own individualistic style.
You can also pick from a broad array of Levi's dark styles
including jackets, hipsters, boot cuts, 501s and 569s.
</P>
<P>
   While it is targeted for now to the young teen and college set,
darker denim is definitely moving into the real fashion arena in
coming months. A few weeks ago at Saint-Tropez, where hot trends
are often nurtured, everyone was wearing it, Wolfe says.
</P>
<P>
   One style note, thanks to the influence of Helmet Lang: The hip
way to wear your denims is turned up into a wide cuff, another sign
of the old that looks new again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
