<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: FASTER FINS FOR DIVERS; SWIM GOGGLES WITH EAR PROTECTORS;
EXERCISING WHILE BABY-SITTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last big innovation in swimming fins _ those rubber
appendages that give scuba divers and snorkelers more leg power _
came in 1965, with the introduction of vents. The vents, by
allowing water to pass through the fin, reduced drag and made
kicking less laborious.
</P>
<P>
   Pete McCarthy, a 32-year-old scuba-diving entrepreneur, had not
even been born when the vented fins first appeared. But McCarthy
has just patented a new type of fin that he says will require a lot
less exertion on the part of divers.
</P>
<P>
   In anthropomorphic terms, McCarthy's fin resembles the tail of a
tuna more than the webbed foot of a duck. ``It's split into two
slender wings that are kind of V-shaped,'' McCarthy said. ``It acts
like a fish tail.''
</P>
<P>
   The fins rotate somewhat like the propeller blades on a boat, he
said. ``Only they don't go all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy _ who said he came up with the design through trial and
error after experimenting with about 200 handmade prototypes _ quit
his job as a software salesman in 1996 to work full time on his
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The fins allow a diver to go faster than he would wearing
conventional fins, McCarthy contends. Using an underwater
speedometer that he also invented, McCarthy said he had clocked
divers going about 30 percent faster with his fins.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a bit like claiming that a new car can go 150 miles
an hour. Impressive, but not particularly relevant if it is used
for commuting and running errands.
</P>
<P>
   A more meaningful measurement, said Jon Hardy, who runs a
scuba-products testing company called Scuba Lab on Catalina Island,
Calif., is the consumption of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, whom McCarthy paid to test his fins, said the split fins
did reduce divers' air consumption. ``The fins are from 20 to 40
percent more efficient than conventional fins,'' Hardy said.
McCarthy said divers wearing his fins just perform a small flutter
kick, rather than the big bent-knee kick that is most effective
with traditional fins. ``No knees at all,'' he said. ``You just
roll your ankles.''
</P>
<P>
   Apollo Sports, a Japanese company that distributes diving
equipment in the United States, has licensed McCarthy's patent and
will be coming out with its version of the split fin this summer.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, who has a company called Nature's Wing, in Newport
Beach, Calif., said he had also licensed patent 5,746,631 to other
companies that will be developing their own versions of the fin.
</P>
<P>
   Swim Goggles With Ear Protectors
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Marie DeAngelis' daughter is grown now. But she remembers
how difficult it can be to coax a child who is prone to ear
infections to put in earplugs before swimming.
</P>
<P>
   So she has invented a pair of goggles with built-in ear
protectors.
</P>
<P>
   The ear protectors are not inserted. Instead, they are
essentially wide bands made of a rubberized waterproof material
that molds tightly around the outside of the ears. The bands, which
attach at the back with a Velcro-type fastener, also serve to hold
the goggles in place.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeAngelis, an administrative assistant at a brokerage firm
in New York, said she was hoping to license her patent, No.
5,713,078.
</P>
<P>
   An Exercise in Baby-Sitting
</P>
<P>
   Since small children must constantly be supervised around the
pool, parents of young families often find it impossible to squeeze
in a few laps for exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Metro and Naomi Fine, of Oakland, Calif., have come up
with a way for parents to watch their children while doing the
backstroke.
</P>
<P>
   It is a flotation device that a child sits inside. The baby
float features a canopy to keep the sun out and a bar in front with
small toys attached.
</P>
<P>
   To use it as a kick board, a parent grasps it at one end. To use
it as an arm strengthener, the parent does the backstroke while
squeezing the sides of the chair between his or her thighs.
</P>
<P>
   Metro and Ms. Fine received patent No. 5,766,052.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
