A2262 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-19 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR; THE INTERN WHO BECAME AN ICON &LR;
<P>
   Waging a ``War Against Waifs,'' the public relations team
representing the woman's large-size store Lane Bryant concocted a
list of 12 women of achievement, ``accomplished, fashionable and
beautiful without fitting into the size-four stereotype,'' said the
draft of the press release. One of the star names on the list was
 &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; , whose inclusion was questioned by the Washington
Post. ``When did alleged adultery and imperiling the presidency
become admirable?'' asked the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think rather than accomplishment, it has to do with
confidence,'' Lane Bryant's  &UR; Chris Hansen &LR;  said. ``One of the
things Lane Bryant is trying to do is enhance their self-esteem.''
Monica ``obviously thinks she's sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the list was officially issued, Lewinsky's name had
been deleted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CURRENT EVENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - CNN's  &UR; Peter Arnett  &LR; received a mere slap on the wrist over
the ``Valley of Death'' documentary on American use of nerve gas,
but apparently recuperation was in order. A spy saw the newsman at
the Benbow Inn in Garberville last weekend, accompanied by a ``much
younger female'' who stalked out after a little tiff in the dining
room. When she returned, after most of the other guests had
finished dinner and left, said the spy, they appeared (very much)
to make up.
</P>
<P>
   - If the president's bodyguards can be forced to testify in the
Lewinsky case, asks  &UR; Sally Jarrett &LR; , isn't it time to remove the
``Secret'' from the ``Secret Service''?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jack Nicholson &LR; , who had returned from Cuba and was on his
way to Scotland to play golf, told Daily Variety that in his
opinion,  &UR; Fidel Castro &LR;  is ``a genius. We spoke about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TANGIBLE EVIDENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  - In an Austin (Texas) American-Statesman story about
marketing to Christians,  &UR; Mark Pritchard &LR;  was dazzled to learn of
the availability of infants' bibs that read ``Perky Lil'
Presbyterian.'' And proving that sometimes the apple does fall far
from the tree,  &UR; Judy Wolf  &LR; was eating in a Sacramento cafe when she
saw a father wearing a T-shirt that said ``Jesus'' accompanied by
his son wearing a T-shirt that said ``Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Paddy Morrissey  &LR; spotted the bumper of a Berkeley driver
who's definitely taken sides: One sticker said ``American Waterfowl
Association,'' the second said, ``If you're looking for your cat,
check under my wheels.''
</P>
<P>
   - Hispanic Business, a Santa Barbara-based publication, has
filed suit against Hispanic, an Austin, Texas-based publication,
claiming trademark rights to the word ``Hispanic,'' reports the
Hispanic Business Journal, which has an obvious interest in the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   - The New York Daily News reports that a day after after
shopping at a boutique in Manhattan,  &UR; Danielle Steel &LR;  called to
order 16 pairs of socks embroidered with the word ``bitch.''
Comedian  &UR; Alan King &LR;  has gone into the kosher pickle business. And
 &UR; Lucy Lawless &LR; , who plays ``Xena the Warrior Princess'' and is said
to be worth $10 million, has made it to the list of New Zealand's
richest citizens.
</P>
<P>
   - A careful listener heard KCBS radio's &UR; Al Hart  &LR; proclaim last
week that  &UR; Albert Schweitzer  &LR; had discovered the theory of
relativity, but it took only a few minutes for the station to
de-credit the organist and credit the fiddler,  &UR; Albert Einstein &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HYGIENE AND HIGH CUISINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A recently enacted L.A. county ordinance requires restaurants to
post letter grades for ratings they receive from the Department of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   The highest grade is 100; points are deducted for violations. As
in high school, an A designates that the grade was between 90 and
100. C is the lowest grade. A restaurant that falls below 70 may be
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   According to Los Angeles magazine, one inspection of the House
of Blues resulted in a 45 rating (violations were fixed the
following month) but several Burger Kings scored 100s on their
initial inspections.
</P>
