<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-HUMIDITY-KANS     07-19 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-HUMIDITY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT THE HEAT, IT'S THE RELATIVE HUMIDITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Try to think of it as nature's moisturizer.
</P>
<P>
   When you step outside and _ WHAM! _ you feel that sudden, soggy
embrace that so epitomizes summertime in the lower Midwest, try to
think of the good it's doing you _ and it is doing you a little bit
of good.
</P>
<P>
   Because heaven knows, it feels gruesome indeed.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough that the temperature reaches 90-plus degrees
here in the summer months; the relative humidity has to shoot up to
such heights as well.
</P>
<P>
   At 90 percent or 92 percent relative humidity, mornings of late
have been sufficiently sodden to run through a wringer washer. Even
our lowest daily humidity readings, which generally occur around
sunset, have rarely dropped below 70 percent, according to Jim
Allen, a forecaster with the National Weather Service in Pleasant
Hill, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   And a temperature of 90 degrees with a humidity of 90 percent
makes it feel like 122 degrees. (See accompanying box.) Yikes!
</P>
<P>
   But hey, wet-blanket syndrome is nothing new around here in the
summertime. And there are specific reasons for that.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulf of Mexico is one. When you're talking ocean air, you're
talking sog-gy. In fact, the Gulf Coast has some of the wettest air
in the United States, according to George Amis, a meteorologist for
the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   And here in the Midwest, most of our air supply comes from the
Gulf. Although it drops a bit of its moisture load on Alabama and
Texas and Arkansas on its way north, there's usually plenty left by
the time it sweeps over the plains.
</P>
<P>
   Heat is another factor. How much water the air can hold is a
function of temperature. Warmer air can hold more water than cooler
air.
</P>
<P>
   And why would that be? In two words, Brownian motion. Molecules
of water and other substances are always moving, and in higher
temperatures they move faster, said Curtis Hall, an instructor in
meteorology at the University of Kansas in Lawrence. The more they
move, the more likely water molecules are to escape from a river or
farm pond or glass of water into the surrounding atmosphere, making
the leap from a liquid to a gas.
</P>
<P>
   In cooler places, say, Portland, Ore., the summer air doesn't
generally heat up enough to get the molecules moving enough to turn
into large quantities of water vapor.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the relative humidity in comfortable places _ such as
the Pacific Northwest _ can be every bit as high as the relative
humidity in steamy regions. Halfway up the western front of the
Cascade Mountains in Washington state, you'll find perpetual cloud
cover and one of the most humid regions on Earth, according to
Allen. But people don't object nearly as much as they do in some
places with lower relative humidity readings.
</P>
<P>
   That's because relative humidity is defined as the ratio of the
amount of water vapor in the air to the amount of water vapor the
air is capable of holding. And in cooler places the air cannot hold
onto as much water. Therefore it doesn't take as much water in the
air to bring the relative humidity to 80 percent or 90 percent. But
although the ratio might be high, the total amount of water vapor
in the air is much lower than in a warmer place.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure of water vapor is known as the dew point. This
is the temperature below which water in the air will condense,
turning into dew or fog or clouds. As the temperature increases,
the dew point often does the same. However, the dew point never
exceeds the temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem with soggy air, from the standpoint of human
comfort, is that it interferes with our cooling system. We are a
species that mostly keeps from overheating by sweating. In theory,
sweating cools us because as the sweat beads up on our skin, the
atmosphere absorbs it, using heat from our bodies to turn the
liquid water into vapor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's humid, there's nowhere for the sweat to go,'' said
Jeffrey Potteiger, who directs the exercise physiology lab at the
University of Kansas in Lawrence. ``It can't evaporate. It doesn't
provide that cooling effect. Anytime you're doing any kind of work,
you're going to generate body heat. In a humid condition, you can't
dissipate that heat to the environment as easily. So we sweat more
and more, it runs off of us, it seems we're not getting any cooler,
and in fact, we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Drinking lots of water is critical during hot, humid weather,
especially for people who are working or playing hard outside.
Because caffeine and alcohol are diuretics, it's wise to keep them
to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, spending time in an air-conditioned building
isn't a bad idea either.
</P>
<P>
   So relative humidity levels of 70, 80, 90 percent feel bad. And
they tend to make for bad hair days.
</P>
<P>
   And for a few people, a heavy load of water vapor can cause
annoying irritations, fungal infections such as athlete's foot and
jock itch. High humidity also can promote certain bacterial
infections, according to David Kaplan, a dermatologist in Overland
Park, Kan. People troubled by excema sometimes suffer flare-ups
during hot humid conditions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of us, according to Kaplan, a little humidity
is a good thing, keeps our skin hydrated. A little humidity, we
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
