<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR; THE INTERN WHO BECAME AN ICON &LR;
<P>
   Waging a ``War Against Waifs,'' the public relations team
representing the woman's large-size store Lane Bryant concocted a
list of 12 women of achievement, ``accomplished, fashionable and
beautiful without fitting into the size-four stereotype,'' said the
draft of the press release. One of the star names on the list was
 &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; , whose inclusion was questioned by the Washington
Post. ``When did alleged adultery and imperiling the presidency
become admirable?'' asked the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think rather than accomplishment, it has to do with
confidence,'' Lane Bryant's  &UR; Chris Hansen &LR;  said. ``One of the
things Lane Bryant is trying to do is enhance their self-esteem.''
Monica ``obviously thinks she's sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the list was officially issued, Lewinsky's name had
been deleted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CURRENT EVENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - CNN's  &UR; Peter Arnett  &LR; received a mere slap on the wrist over
the ``Valley of Death'' documentary on American use of nerve gas,
but apparently recuperation was in order. A spy saw the newsman at
the Benbow Inn in Garberville last weekend, accompanied by a ``much
younger female'' who stalked out after a little tiff in the dining
room. When she returned, after most of the other guests had
finished dinner and left, said the spy, they appeared (very much)
to make up.
</P>
<P>
   - If the president's bodyguards can be forced to testify in the
Lewinsky case, asks  &UR; Sally Jarrett &LR; , isn't it time to remove the
``Secret'' from the ``Secret Service''?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jack Nicholson &LR; , who had returned from Cuba and was on his
way to Scotland to play golf, told Daily Variety that in his
opinion,  &UR; Fidel Castro &LR;  is ``a genius. We spoke about everything.''
</P>
