<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-     07-19 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earth to Girbaud
</P>
<P>
   When you wanted hip-hop denim in the early '90s, who was a good
bet to call? Girbaud.
</P>
<P>
   The Greensboro, N.C., based jeans maker was the center of a
young fashion-edgy cult among the young who considered the label
oh-so-cool. It was an easy fit. Before the company was part of the
VF Corp, in the 1970s, the Paris-based Girbauds were pioneers in
stone-washing denim. And they were part of the drive behind torn
and distressed denim in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But fashion pundits know well that Marithe and Francois Girbaud
_ middle-aged, French intellectual, avant-gardists _ have long been
looking well beyond denim. Their quest is for modern clothes
appropriate to urban life in a new century.
</P>
<P>
   Shiny high-tech fabrics, protective armor, active stretch
textiles and clothes that leave arms free to move are their
priorities. They have introduced light laser-cut fabrics that leave
no need for traditional seams and hems.
</P>
<P>
   In their fall fashion show in New York last spring, they brought
you heat-fused fabrics and city street styling that blends day into
night and casual into active. They crossbred ski and skateboard
pants and put knee pouches into military pants. They provided ways
to travel light without bags and baggage.
</P>
<P>
   The key word here is pockets, deep cargo pockets (inset) and
roomy hidden satchels. And for those who have toted handbags over
sore shoulders or run through a storm with a bag bouncing against
the ribs, the idea not only fits the cargo fashion of the moment
but also offers comfort as an attainable dream.
</P>
<P>
   The Girbauds, along with Donna Karan and Calvin Klein, are
working on a new century. Maybe it's time to think about going
forward and not back.
</P>
<P>
   Deep pockets required
</P>
<P>
   About those pockets, anyone who has traipsed through a mall or
schoolyard recently knows cargo pants and shorts with deep leg
level pockets are the uniform with the young.
</P>
<P>
   What you may not know, the pants originated with the British
army in 1938 and were worn in the 1940s by American paratroopers
who packed ammunition in the side pockets, the Wall Street Journal
noted recently.
</P>
<P>
   Today they are not just for kids and club types who stuff their
pockets with beepers and credit cards. Moving into fall, the pants
are slated for hautier fashion ground. Ralph Lauren's suede
version, for instance, priced well over $2,000, makes deep pockets
more than a fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cargo fashions are bringing in pocketfuls of cash,'' noted the
Journal, which predicted sales in cargo styles at $2.3 billion in
1998, as estimated by a market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   For your own wallet, check out Army-Navy stores for the
originals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
