<DOCNO> NYT19980719.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2267 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-CLINIC-KAN &LR;      07-19 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CLINIC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS DOCTOR PERFORMING LATE-TERM ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Kansas' most well-known abortion doctor has begun
performing ``partial-birth'' abortions at his clinic in Wichita,
raising further questions about a new state law.
</P>
<P>
   George Tiller, owner of Women's Health Care Services, began
doing the late-term abortion procedure on fetuses with severe
abnormalities this month, said the clinic's administrative
director, Dena Vogler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are performing so-called partial-birth abortions as defined
by Kansas law,'' Vogler said Thursday. ``We have found a
satisfactory method so that we can legally do these procedures and
honor the desires of the women and families that require these
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogler said Tiller so far has performed ``a couple'' of the
abortions since the beginning of the month. Tiller, one of a
handful of doctors in the nation who perform late-term abortions,
now is thought to be the only doctor in Kansas performing
``partial-birth'' abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes said Tiller's actions circumvent the intent of the
law, which went into effect July 1. But Tiller's clinic _ which the
new law is directed at _ maintains that the new procedure is legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're absolutely not skirting the law,'' Vogler said. ``The
lawmakers wrote a bill which was difficult to interpret in many
respects, and we are playing the hand that has been dealt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law, passed in the final days of the legislative
session, prohibits late-term abortions unless the woman's life is
in danger or if the pregnancy would cause irreversible impairment
``of a major bodily function'' of the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Graves signed the bill into law in April, but there
has been confusion ever since over what it really means. Some said
the law banned virtually all late-term abortions, with no
exceptions for severe fetal abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Graves, insisted that the ``major bodily
function'' clause meant either ``mental or physical'' bodily
function, which would allow women with severely deformed fetuses to
get post-viability abortions. ``Viability'' is defined in the law
as the point at which the fetus can survive indefinitely outside
the womb.
</P>
<P>
   While attention was focused on the viability section of the law,
another twist emerged: A separate section in the law banning
``partial-birth'' abortions contained a ``mental health''
exception.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes were taken aback at the news about Tiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's simply proving the point that the pro-life people have
made for years: He's the Dr. Kevorkian of abortion,'' said Rep. Tim
Carmody, an Overland Park, Kan., Republican who helped write the
new law. ``He will push the envelope as far as he possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmody said that if Tiller had found a loophole, legislators
would address it next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently the definition we have is not strong enough to stop
it,'' he said. ``So it's just a matter of a few months until we get
a stronger partial-birth abortion ban on the books.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Gittrich, director of Kansans for Life, said Graves is
partly to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just shows how much the governor prevented partial-birth
abortions, doesn't it?'' Gittrich said. ``Bill Graves worked on the
passage of a partial-birth ban that doesn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves' spokesman referred calls on the issue to the attorney
general's office. Mary Horsch, spokeswoman for Kansas Attorney
General Carla Stovall, expressed surprise at the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had not known about it, but we'll certainly take a look at
it to see what's going on,'' Horsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Vogler said that Tiller's ``partial-birth'' method is different
from the one used by other doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not doing the procedure that the public normally
envisions when they hear about this term,'' she said. ``We are
providing full cranial anesthesia, which causes fetal death, and we
are in fact aspirating a portion of the cranial contents in order
to comply with the Kansas law.''
</P>
<P>
   In most states with bans on ``partial-birth'' abortion _ the
medical term is ``intact dilation and evacuation'' _ the procedure
is defined as one in which the fetus is partly extracted legs
first, then the base of the skull is punctured and the contents
drained so it can pass more easily through the birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas' new law, however, defines ``partial-birth'' abortion as
a procedure that ``includes the deliberate and intentional
evacuation of all or a part of the intracranial contents of a
viable fetus prior to removal of such otherwise intact fetus from
the body of the pregnant woman.''
</P>
<P>
   That means Tiller doesn't have to partly extract the fetus
before draining the contents of the skull. He can kill the fetus
and drain the skull in the womb, then induce the woman into labor
so she delivers a stillborn baby.
</P>
<P>
   The method varies only slightly from the late-term ``induction
method'' that Tiller has performed for years, in which he killed
the fetus by injecting its heart with a chemical, then induced the
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essentially the same procedure,'' Vogler said. ``We have
simply changed the location of the injection of the agent that
causes fetal demise, and we are also aspirating a portion of the
cranial contents in order to be doing what the law defines as a
partial-birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she did not think the ``partial-birth'' procedure posed
any more risk to the patients than the previous late-term method
used by Tiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very little to go on, but we would not employ this
method if we didn't feel that it was a sound procedure that was
safe for our patients,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tiller has filed a lawsuit in the Kansas Supreme
Court challenging the new law. He did not, however, challenge the
``partial-birth'' abortion section.
</P>
<P>
   Vogler said she did not know whether Tiller would continue to
perform the procedures if he wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer that question, because we have done so few of
these procedures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
