<SLUG> BC-GIRAFFE-DIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GIRAFFE DIES AT KC ZOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ For the second time in less than six months a
Masai giraffe has died of a mystery illness at the Kansas City Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old female, named Jeanerry, collapsed about 3:45 p.m.
Wednesday. More than 100 visitors watched as officials attempted to
treat her below the boardwalk between the lion and rhino exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her legs absolutely went out from under her,'' said zoo
spokeswoman Denise Rendina. ``Her neck went limp.''
</P>
<P>
   The other giraffe stood still watching as the veterinary staff
administered an IV and oxygen. The animal got up once but collapsed
again. It was given a lethal injection about 6 p.m. Test results
are pending.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Suedmeyer, zoo veterinarian, said he does not yet know
whether Jeanerry's ailment was the same one that killed her mother,
Damita, in January. That was a mystery syndrome that has afflicted
28 giraffes in North America in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials said they are not concerned about contagion
spreading to other animals. Five other Masai giraffe remain at the
zoo, including Tsavo, a male offspring of Jeanerry. They are among
47 in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Zoo officials hope to meet in Tulsa, Okla., in
September with officials from other zoos holding Masai giraffe to
discuss importing more of the animals to increase genetic
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The death Wednesday was the most public of six apparently
unrelated deaths of high-profile animals at the zoo since December.
A lion had cancer, a gorilla had an aneurysm, a puma had muscle
spasms, and a snow leopard had cancer and a nervous-system problem.
</P>
<P>
   All but the gorilla were euthanized by the zoo's veterinary
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have you got, Dr. Kevorkian out there?'' Ollie Gates,
chairman of the city's Board of Parks and Recreation Commissioners,
asked zoo Director Mark Wourms in jest this spring, referring to
the Michigan assisted-suicide advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of them has been because of an illness and not because of
any professional error,'' Rendina said of the deaths. ``Certainly
we are always concerned about the care of our animals. Regretfully,
death is part of what we do here.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service last
visited the zoo May 13 and found no problems directly affecting the
welfare of animals.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors have not found any such problems in seven inspections
since August 1996. In June of that year, inspectors ordered repairs
to a pump that circulates water in the baboon area and to a door in
the rhino area.
</P>
<P>
   But clean inspection reports reflect conditions on the day they
are made and would not deter the federal agency _ part of the U.S.
Department of Agriculture _ from investigating further if officials
thought something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Jamie Ambrosi said the agency would look into the
deaths and decide whether a formal investigation is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   But Conrad Schmitt, zoo curator, said, ``People need to
understand that this is not an exact science.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're constantly learning new things about all the animals we
take care of. Animals, like people, are born and some of them get
old and die, and some die when they're young. Unlike with people,
we don't get a lot of money for research into unknown causes of
(animal) death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
