</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEVEN GATES OF JERUSALEM': BRAWN OVER BRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Krzysztof Penderecki's ``Seven Gates of Jerusalem''
at the Lincoln Center Festival on Friday night made us wonder about
bigness as a source of beauty and power. It is an immense piece,
not in length nor, I am afraid, in depth but in the almost
intimidating number of singers and orchestra players it directs
toward its listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Two choirs occupied the side balconies of Avery Fisher Hall and
a larger one the back of the stage. The New York Philharmonic not
only faced its audience in the customary position but also sent
squadrons of players to the back of the hall. Indeed, this was the
concert experience in the form of a siege. People even
contemplating escape soon realized that great waves of music had
sealed off every route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven Gates of Jerusalem'' sets biblical fragments from
Psalms, Isaiah, Jeremiah and Daniel and commemorates that city's
3,000 years of history. It had its first performance in Jerusalem a
year and a half ago and tries hard, desperately hard, to impress us
with its import.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is overscale, lest our minds be allowed to wander.
Choruses boom from every side; brass choirs and claps of percussion
sound at both front and rear. Penderecki's fondness for ominous,
droning pedal points and portentous ostinato figures are manifest
in both the orchestra and voice parts. The sheer size of this piece
cannot help but make its effect, just as two sticks of dynamite
make a bigger hole than one, but how quickly the effect fades once
our ears stop ringing. ``Seven Gates of Jerusalem'' is theater
without drama. Its grandiloquent gestures seek to cover up an
underlying poverty of invention. The melodic lines fade in and out
of tonality and churchlike modality; their movement is incessantly
stepwise and often chromatic.
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, Penderecki has sought to discover what a
halfway cultured yet excitement-seeking listener wishes a solemn
and religious piece to sound like and then has assiduously obliged.
We should be able to rejoice when a 20th-century composer cares so
deeply about his listeners, but there is a difference between
reaching into someone else's soul and winning favors through
flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Masur's conducting job was like that of a dispatcher at a
railroad yard: making sure that everyone got on the right track at
the right time and that collisions were avoided. Musicians
stationed far from one another always pose coordination problems,
and there were small ones here; television monitors seemed to help.
The Philadelphia Singers Chorale sang lustily. Christine Goerke's
soprano was the vivid presence in a quintet of soloists that
included Wendy Nielsen, Florence Quivar, Jon Villars and William
Stone. The truly valid moments of the evening came in Boris
Carmeli's richly passionate Hebrew declamations from Ezekiel.
</P>
<P>
   There is an entrepreneurial air to Penderecki's highly
successful composing career. He has a knack for large issues,
weighty subjects and timely events. The novelty of his early music
_ with its swimming textures and designed chaos __ was truly
exciting. But its novelty has worn off, leaving the composer to
pick fastidiously through a supermarket of received ideas. One
wishes they were more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   It is rarely a good idea, nor is it very fair, to compare a new
piece with an established one, but at home, after Friday's
performance, I couldn't help thinking of another seven-part piece
equally solemn and religious. Haydn's ``Seven Last Words of
Christ'' for string quartet is barely audible next to the
thunderings of ``Seven Gates of Jerusalem,'' but its music is
freestanding: filled with invention, devoid of slick tricks and
calculated melodrama, appealing to the listener's highest
instincts. After writing this, I spent the rest of the weekend with
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 1832EDT &QL; 
