A2272 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-19 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUZZ IS ON FOR BONDS. HERE'S WHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The emerging buzz on Wall Street is how the bond
market promises the next big investment bonanza as factors coalesce
over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   These factors include continued low inflation, a federal budget
surplus, a stronger dollar, Japanese financial deregulation and the
launching of a single European currency to be known as the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Analyses from a variety of observers point to a scenario that
will unfold as follows:
</P>
<P>
   Rising concerns about the stock market being overvalued will
create more interest among U.S. investors for alternatives such as
bonds, particularly if inflation remains as well-behaved as most
economists expect. While this in and of itself would be a
substantial spur to bonds, there will be much more fueling demand.
This means as investors bid prices up, interest rates can be
expected to decline because they move inversely. Some are
predicting the 30-year bellwether Treasury bond yield will go well
below 5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   The critical key will be a stronger dollar, particularly in
relation to the Japanese yen and the German mark.
</P>
<P>
   The next signal event during deregulation of Japan's financial
markets comes as 1999 dawns, when Japanese pension funds will be
freed to diversify portfolios. Pension fund investments have been
limited to Japanese bonds, which have painfully meager yields. Fund
managers will be looking for the higher yields available in
America, and Treasuries will be especially attractive as the
dollar's value continues to rise against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times analysis noted that Japanese pension funds are
sitting on $9 trillion and quoted one economic advisory firm's
estimate that as much as 15 percent of this total will be put into
play in the U.S. bond market next year.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the world, anticipation of the launching of
the euro has led German investors to conclude that their D-mark
holdings will be devalued because the mark is Europe's strongest
currency. The euro, it is reasoned, can't be brought to market at
the high end of Europe's currency value range. It would put
countries with currencies of less value at too much of a
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   This has led Germans to hedge by moving into dollar-denominated
investments, which already has provided a lift for the Treasuries
market. As confusion mounts during the period of adjusting to the
euro currency, the hedging trend into dollar investments is
expected to accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all this will be happening as the U.S. budget comes
into balance for the first time in nearly three decades. This means
the supply of Treasuries relative to demand will be less than has
been the case during the years when huge deficits had to be
financed with large issues of Treasury debt.
</P>
<P>
   This will tend not only to make Treasuries more dear than
otherwise would be the case, but to force investors to look beyond
governments for their credit market investment opportunities, which
bodes well for corporate bonds as well.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say the strengthening dollar will hurt stocks,
and this is certainly true for companies with earnings heavily
dependent on export trade as U.S. goods become more expensive for
foreign buyers. On the other hand, a bull market in bonds implies
low interest rates and low inflation, both of which imply good
things for the economy and corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the smart money's right, 1999 might be a lot better year
than most investors dared hope for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
