<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORGIA-OPERA-REVIEW-A     07-19 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORGIA-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCRETIA BORGIA': BRINGING OUT BEST IN DONIZETTI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATONAH, N.Y. _ There are many opera conductors who bring more
podium experience and technical ability to the job than Will
Crutchfield, who led his first opera in 1991. But Crutchfield has a
special understanding of the bel canto opera repertory, which he
demonstrated again Saturday at the Caramoor Festival here,
presiding over an affecting performance of Donizetti's ``Lucrezia
Borgia.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast he had assembled and coached clearly benefited from his
knowledge of the style. The players of the splendid Orchestra of
St. Luke's responded sensitively. But it was Crutchfield's palpable
belief in this work as a compelling musical drama that made the
performance so satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   For many opera buffs, it's hard to distinguish ``Lucrezia
Borgia'' among the nearly 70 operas Donizetti churned out during
his 20 working years. For sure, there are formulaic aspects to the
score, and it takes a leap to accept Lucrezia as a sympathetic
heroine. In the face of ruthless rivalries among 16th-century
Italian aristocrats, Lucrezia has schemed her way through four
marriages, leaving a trail of poisoned victims behind.
</P>
<P>
   But, in opera, music often reveals a subtext that works on a
deeper level than the plot, and that is the case here. Seen another
way, the opera centers on a young man, Gennaro, who was abandoned
by his parents, raised by poor a fisherman, made his way as a
soldier of fortune and was under the mysterious protection of an
anonymous powerful family. As Crutchfield, a former music critic of
The New York Times, explains in his program notes, Gennaro is torn
between his circle of privileged friends _ especially his best
friend, Orsini _ who tempt him into ``decadent dissipation,'' and
his longing for his lost mother, who, it turns out, is Lucrezia.
So, musically, the opera becomes a battle between a dramatic
coloratura soprano, Lucrezia, and a hearty coloratura
mezzo-soprano, the trouser role of Orsini, over a young tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Crutchfield was sometimes so concerned with revealing the
lyrical flow and dignity of this music that his spacious shaping of
the long-lined arias lost rhythmic continuity. But it was better to
err on the side of elegance, for too often Donizetti's profusion of
bel canto melody can sound generic, and here it seemed inspired.
And Crutchfield brought a sense of compositional coherence to the
score overall, with its mix of arias, dramatic ensembles and
spirited crowd scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The fiery soprano Lauren Flanigan, who has a devoted following,
had been scheduled to sing Lucrezia, and many in the sold-out house
had probably come expecting her. She had to withdraw, however,
because some performances in Japan detained her longer than
expected, and she said she had not adequately learned the role of
Lucrezia. Her replacement, Melanie Helton, sang with confidence.
She is an intelligent, expressive soprano who has an essentially
big-sized voice, yet sings soft, high phrases with care. Her sound
is sometimes grainy and hard-edged, but her performance was
involving.
</P>
<P>
   Tenor Bruce Fowler made a sweet-voiced, youthful Gennaro. And if
he seemed a bit fresh and malleable, it fit the character
perfectly. As Orsini, the remarkable mezzo-soprano Vivica Genaux,
who scored a triumph last season at Caramoor in Rossini's ``Donna
del Lago'' was remarkable again. Her voice is vibrant, flexible and
interesting. She sings with technical ease and dramatic
incisiveness. Her scintillating and sensual performance of the
drinking song in the final scene made this music seem a clear model
for Eboli's ``Song of the Veil'' in Verdi's ``Don Carlo.'' The
stentorian bass Hao Jiang Tian as the Duke of Ferrara, Lucrezia's
husband, and tenor Steven Tharp as his agent, also did solid work.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor Venetian Theater has a popular new innovation:
supertitles, employing a digital screen system, much like those
road signs that flash advisories on the highways. But it was a good
solution for an outdoor theater. The grounds of the estate remain a
lovely place to enjoy a pre-performance picnic. But it is what
Crutchfield has to share with us about a misunderstood repertory
that has made the yearly ``Bel Canto at Caramoor'' opera an
essential contribution to a respected festival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
