<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLASTIC-MUSIC-REVIEW-     07-19 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLASTIC-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLASTIC PEOPLE: ECHOES OF 1968 CZECHOSLOVAK ROCK AND STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Plastic People of the Universe, formed in 1968 in
Prague, are one of the few rock bands that can claim to have
changed history. The group's somberly propulsive music and
sardonic, surreal lyrics, along with its English name, were taken
as subversive provocations by the Czechoslovak government that was
installed after the Soviet Union invaded Czechoslovakia in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'70s, rock that had considered itself transgressive
in the West had been absorbed into the entertainment business. But
in Eastern Europe, unofficial artistic expression was seen as a
threat to order. When the members of the Plastic People were jailed
in 1976 for ``organized disturbance of the peace,'' Czech artists,
students and intellectuals formed a human-rights movement, Charter
77, that eventually helped to overturn the government. In 1989,
Charter 77's leader, Vaclav Havel, became the president of
independent Czechoslovakia. But in the meantime, the band broke up;
its core members formed Pulnoc (Midnight), which toured the United
States in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Plastic People reunited last year for the 20th anniversary
of Charter 77, and on Saturday night they performed at Irving Plaza
as part of the Intel New York Music Festival. The concert was a
benefit for Tamizdat, a nonprofit organization that makes
connections among artists in the United States, Western Europe and
the former Eastern bloc. And the music, though no longer considered
seditious, retains a good part of its dour intensity.
</P>
<P>
   The band reached back to its earliest repertory, when it was
enamored of the Velvet Underground and the Doors, groups that built
songs on steady, inexorable vamps. Its music is by its bassist,
Milan Hlavsa, and the songs center on repeating bass riffs that
crimp blues-based Western rock into dissonant minor keys that are
unmistakably Eastern European. Jan Brabec, on drums, made those
riffs pushy and explosive; he could settle into one brawny,
relentless beat or snap the music to attention with bursts of
syncopation.
</P>
<P>
   The music's late-'60s roots showed clearly, recapturing a time
when rudimentary rock opened up to exploratory, chaotic solos. When
Josef Janicek's plinking keyboards were in the foreground, the
music evoked the Doors; Jiri Kabes, on viola, linked the group to
both the Velvet Underground and to Eastern European fiddle
traditions. A younger guitarist, Joe Karafiat, has joined the
longtime Plastic People; he wailed above the riffs with psychedelic
squiggles, and occasionally added quick-scrubbing '70s funk chords.
Vratislav Brabanec, on alto saxophone, played scurrying, free-jazz
solos or joined in on the bass lines to make the group sound
something like early King Crimson.
</P>
<P>
   Hlavsa sang and intoned most of the lyrics, in Czech, with a
low, haunted growl that sometimes reached up to a bitter shout.
Brabanec announced song titles in English, among them
``Intoxication,'' ``Constipation,'' ``Elegy,'' ``Magic Nights,''
``Nobody'' and ``Little Canary,'' which he said was about the
canary dying. ``A very sad song,'' he said, with a droll
half-smile; the strife was over, but not forgotten.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
