   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ JERUSALEM _ Police arrested a badly burned man
they said had been trying to set off a car bomb Sunday in downtown
Jerusalem just hours before Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
were opening a new round of peace talks. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GLICKMAN _ The secretary of Agriculture says he is now free to
address new and old cases of discrimination against black farmers
now that the senate has approved the removal of the stattue of
limitation stumbling block and he hopes it will heal wounds.
(Atlanta Journal-Constiution)
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ Short update on the continued search for Eric Rudolph.
(Brett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA-DELIVERERS _ Depending on how you slice it, pizza delivery
drivers pay a high price for the privilege of delivering those
pepperoni pies. Many young drivers hop in the their cars not
thinking who would foot the bill should they cause an accident
while on a run. (Drummond, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-WRAP _ ATLANTA _ A short wrap on the final weekend of the
National Black Arts Festival that includes updated numbers and
final weekend observations of note. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-NOTEBOOK _ A critic's notebook looking at events through
the final weekend of the National Black Arts Festival. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ LOS ANGELES _ More from the TV press tour, including
ABC and NBC. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   PUZZLERS _ They are people who've never met a polysylabbic they
couldn't turn into a three day weekend. They play more games with
the English language than Shakespeare, e.e. cummings and Johnnie
Cochran combined. National meeting of the National Puzzlers League
in Atlanta this weekend. A hapless hack covers it. (Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ Some friends from the coast are paying their
first visit to Sweet Apple. They called the other day and suggested
that I fax them a map. I love to make maps, and I was all ready to
sit down and turn artist, until I remembered my son-in-law next
door, a man of technical and artistic turn. He said he and his
computer would transmit a copy to my friends on the coast. He
brought a copy of the map over after I had gone to bed. It is
spare, clean and concise. The Department of Transportation would
approve. But it's not my kind of map. (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
