<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-COUPLES _ TEHRAN, Iran _ Cupid might not have to sneak
around Iran anymore. Young Iranians say they now encounter fewer
problems when they step out together in public. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   USAFRICA-TRADE-3rdLEDE _ WASHINGTON _ With an appealing name,
the ``African Growth and Opportunity Act'' seems to break new, and
positive ground. Proponents say it shifts the U.S. relationship
with Africa from aid to trade. But the Africa trade bill before
Congress, sponsored by U.S. Rep. Philip M. Crane, R-Ill., has
generated contoversy. Opponents of the bill, prominent African
Americans among them, have been growing. (Abulhassan, Cox News
Service.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   USAFRICA-TRADE-BOX _ WASHINGTON _ The split in the African
American community over the bill. (Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MXFACTORY _ MEXICO-FACTORIES _ TIJUANA, Mexico _ One of
Tijuana's maquiladoras, the Korean-owned Han Young auto parts
factory, is making history that could affect Mexico's entire
maquiladora industry. Han Young factory workers are the first to
vote to join an independent labor union _ defying the traditional
government-controlled labor movement. With some American labor
activists backing them up, the workers are trying to use NAFTA to
impose sanctions on Han Young for alleged attempts to destroy the
independent union. (Ferriss, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   w/MXENVIR _ MEXICO-ENVIRONMENT _ MEXICO CITY, Mexico _ When
NAFTA was passed, Mexico and the United States agreed banks would
be established to finance environmental projects along the polluted
border. But environmentalists have complained these banks have been
mismanaged and have failed to live up to expectations. A hard look
at what the banks have done and haven't done. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TURTLES _ XCACEL, Mexico _ She struggles ashore in
darkness, illuminated only by a milky spray of stars in the
Caribbean sky. The sole sounds on the beach are the splash of
waves, the wind and the steady crunching of flippers scooping sand.
Half an hour later, the massive sea turtle begins to deposit more
than a hundred pearly-white eggs inside a nest. Today, biologists
camp on this beach _ called Xcacel and considered one of most
important turtle nesting grounds in the Caribbean _ to protect the
endangered turtles and their eggs from poachers. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS _ WASHINGTON _ Last September the League of Women Voters
in Athens, Ga., staged an issues forum on children's health in the
bustling college town there, home to the University of Georgia. Ten
people showed up. Local community leaders are seeing firsThand what
is crossing the radar screens of pollsters, civics experts and
university professors around the country with alarming consistency:
In the great public square of American democracy, the voting public
has gone home. (Foskett, Cox News Service 1000&AMP;add). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV _ WASHINGTON _ High-definition television may prove to be a
boon for the entire industry, but right now broadcasters and cable
firms are battling each other over a rule saying cable ``must
carry'' local stations that broadcast HDTV. (Glass, Cox News
Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-2ndLEDE _ WASHINGTON _ America may be waiting for Sen.
John Glenn's return to glory in October, but Glenn himself is not.
For Glenn, who turned 77 on Saturday (July 18) the glory is already
back. (Montgomery, Cox News Service). Eds: With timeline and
photos. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH-SCENE _ ANDREWS, N.C. _ A piece that captures the
atmosphere, the color, the people, etc. How the locals feel about
the feds vs. their feelings about Rudolph? What is the spotlight
doing to the community? How is the level of fear, especially among
the summertime visitors? (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT _ The South's long dry spell has been a killer in Texas
and has had a regionwide impact on crops, especially cotton and
corn. The drought also has fostered some odd politics. Farmers in
south Alabama, for instance, may not have to pay the full price of
experimental cotton if they can get an official declaration of
disaster. An analysis of the present and future situatiion.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-FLORIDA _ Floods in winter. Fire in summer. What next
for the Sunshine State? Locusts? A look at Florida's hottest,
driest summer ever and what it has meant for food crops, timber and
tourism. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT-LOUISIANA _ While much of the rest of the South seems
likely to recover soon from the drought, Louisiana may not. Feeling
the heat from drought-plagued neighbor Texas, Louisiana continues
to suffer major crop damage and ecology upsets: Houses are sinking
in New Orleans and gators are swimming out of game preserves into
the Gulf. (Rochell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERGROUND-ATLANTA _ After struggling for nearly a decade, the
owners of Underground Atlanta are putting the much-touted downtown
redevelopment up for sale. Envisioned as a model for urban
public-private redevelopment, the festival marketplace never caught
on and now tenants and sales are dropping fast. (Turner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO-MURDER _ LUDOWICI, Ga. _ Thurman Martin's death,
authorities say, was a family affair. They say the retired
trucker's grandson, Billy Crowder, and son-in-law, Joseph John
Stanton, crept into his bedroom and shot him in his sleep with a
.22-caliber rifle. His daughter and granddaughter cleaned up after
them. Crowder's sister, Katie, pleaded guilty to hindering the
apprehension of a criminal. A friend of Crowder was convicted and
sent to prison for life for helping bury the old man and plant
tomatos over him. Crowder and Stanton are on trial this week for
murder in one of the most bizarre of South Georgia killings.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
