<SLUG> BC-BRITISH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First, the Masters; Now, the British for calm O'Meara
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ His 4-iron to the green on the final
playoff hole having just settled into two-putt range Sunday evening
at Royal Birkdale, Mark O'Meara turned to his caddie, Jerry
Higginbotham, and declared, ''I can't believe how calm I am.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's OK,'' said Higginbotham, ''cause I'm nervous enough for
both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   On a British Open Sunday jammed with enough dramatic moments to
fill a Royal &AMP; Ancient highlight reel, the 41-year-old O'Meara
calmly added another chapter to his amazing year, securing the
Claret Jug in a playoff over Brian Watts after both finished at
even-par 280. The Jug will assume a spot in the trophy case of
O'Meara's Orlando home, next to the hardware earned at Augusta
National two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, to match the glistening trophy there is silver in
the champion's hair. O'Meara became the oldest player in the modern
era to capture two majors in the same season (Jack Nicklaus was 40
in 1980, Ben Hogan 40 in 1953). O'Meara also is the first American
to win two majors in a season since Tom Watson took both the U.S.
Open and British Open in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ''To win an event such as this is just an incredible feeling,''
O'Meara said. ''Let alone what happened at Augusta this year, and
now to win two major championships in one year, if I could put my
finger on it, I would have done it earlier in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Higginbotham was the least surprised. He put down 100 pounds on
his man early in the week at 40-1.
</P>
<P>
   ''This guy's been winning golf tournaments the last five years
pretty steadily,'' noted his ecstatic employee. ''This year he wins
two majors. Who knows? Now maybe he goes crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering her husband's methodical march at the Masters, where
he hung around patiently and then sprinted home with closing
birdies, Alicia O'Meara said, ''He had that same sort of relaxed
state this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone remaining relaxed Sunday deserve to win a major
championship One minute amateur Justin Rose, the British Boy
Wonder, was holing out from 45 yards out for birdie on the 72nd
hole, tying for fourth. The next minute, a fist-pumping Tiger Woods
was birdieing the final three holes for 66, placing third at 281,
to nearly secure a playoff spot against Watts and his Orlando
neighbor from Isleworth Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   And while O'Meara had the cash ($520,000) and the cup, Watts had
the shot of the tournament. Stuck with a downhill lie and one foot
out of the bunker near the 18th green, and needing a par to push
O'Meara to a four-hole playoff, Watts blasted the low shot to a
foot.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, if you had told me I would have been in a playoff
at the Open Championship at the beginning of the week, I wouldn't
have believed you,'' said the 32-year-old Watts, who gave the Japan
Tour new credibility. ''I'm happy to be here, but also I'm
disappointed that I didn't win because I had the opportunity to do
it today.''
</P>
<P>
   After his closing 68 caught Watts at 70, O'Meara basically won
the playoff on the first extra hole, the 15th, sinking a 5-footer
for birdie as Watts lipped out from four feet. The British Open
format is an aggregate score for the four holes. O'Meara was
1-under, Watts 1-over.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt it I went out there today (two shots behind Watts) and
played well and kept my composure, coming down the stretch,
hopefully I would have a shots,'' O'Meara said. ''That's all I
think you can ask for in the game of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
