<HEADER>
A2278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-AVERY-CO     07-19 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-AVERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins hope Avery can make the big plays
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ This isn't the first time someone gambled on John
Avery. When Avery was 5, an uncle took bets that his little nephew
could outrun all the older boys in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The uncle cashed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he didn't give me a dime,'' Avery said at the practice
facility of the Miami Dolphins, for whom size is important as
training camp starts, and yet is not at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins' offense has been a small-time operation lately,
plodding down the field little by little. Last season, Dan Marino
did not complete a 30-yard pass in 10-of-16 starts. Karim
Abdul-Jabbar's longest rush was 22 yards. Miami has not returned a
punt for a touchdown since 1993, or a kickoff for a score since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Big plays? Big zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody to account for,'' said one NFL personnel director.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in April, Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson handed a large task
to a small man _ the 5-foot-9, 186-pound Avery, a halfback from
Mississippi who had runs of 97 and 74 yards last season, and a
kickoff return of 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's plenty big enough to do what we need him to do,'' said
new offensive coordinator Kippy Brown, who lobbied for Johnson to
take Avery with the 29th pick. ``It makes all the difference when,
in one play, a guy can take it all the way down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do things like Houdini,'' Avery said. ``Make them miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Pity he can't magically make himself bigger, so the doubters
would disappear. The perception is that small backs are not as
durable, that they cannot play every down, that they are doomed to
such limited duties as catching dump-off passes and returning
kicks. Johnson, upon taking Avery higher than most teams slotted
him, conceded he ``may be more than a specialty player.''
</P>
<P>
   Even teams that liked him as a second-round pick questioned if
he could handle the pounding as a ballcarrier. ``We thought he was
as quick and fast a player as there was in the draft,'' said
Cincinnati Bengals director of pro and college personnel Jim
Lippincott. Yet the Bengals, who start 230-pound Corey Dillon at
halfback, worked Avery out as a cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a player of that size to carry the load for 16 games would
be unusual,'' said Scott Studwell, the Minnesota Vikings player
personnel coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smaller backs go down too easy,'' Lippincott said. ``And
sometimes their legs go like hell, but they don't go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 backs who ran for at least 1,000 yards last season,
nine are under 6-feet, including Detroit's Barry Sanders, who led
the league with 2,053 yards. Yet only Napoleon Kaufman is under 200
pounds. Warrick Dunn, at 180 pounds, rushed for 978 yards as a
Tampa Bay Buccaneers rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were shocked about what kind of inside runner Dunn
was,'' said Terry Bradway, the Kansas City Chiefs director of
player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Avery will surprise skeptics, too. Little would surprise
those who coached him, or against him, in college. Ole Miss head
coach Tommy Tuberville, who tutored some burners as a University of
Miami assistant, calls him the quickest player he's coached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great quicks,'' said Jeff Rouzie, linebackers coach at
Alabama, which was scorched for a touchdown return. ``You try to
gang tackle him as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   As a high school senior in Asheville, N.C., Avery rushed for
1,871 yards and 32 scores. He was headed for the University of
Tennessee until he failed an SAT test and spent two seasons at
Northwest (Miss.) Community College before moving to Ole Miss.
</P>
<P>
   In two years as a Rebel, he rushed for 1,650 yards on 247
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Avery must grow as a blocker and receiver. He could bench-press
385 pounds before dislocating his elbow, and Ole Miss coaches say
he was often too aggressive as a blocker. But many teams refrained
from blitzing the Rebels, fearing overpursuit would allow Avery to
bust a long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He embarrasses people when they miss him,'' Studwell said.
``Every time he touches the ball, he's a threat to take it to the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery hasn't been asked to do much receiving _ 35 catches in two
Div.I seasons _ but that skill may determine his initial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can put him in the slot, or split him out, then you
really have a weapon,'' Bradway said. ``Teams will be forced to put
an extra defensive back in the game, or cover him with a
linebacker, and that's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery as Miami's feature back _ will that happen? Many around
the league don't think so, at least not yet, even if they
acknowledge that bigger backs aren't always more durable. Taller
backs certainly aren't. Buffalo's Thurman Thomas, at 5-foot-10, has
missed six games in 11 years. Minnesota's Robert Smith, at 6-feet,
has missed 28 in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taller guys tend to run high, and present a bigger target,''
said Rich Snead, director of player personnel for the Tennessee
Oilers, who have the rare big back (Eddie George) with a little
wiggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big backs dish out punishment, but also absorb a lot,''
Studwell said. ``They wear out faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery, like Sanders, has learned to contort his body, avoiding
contact. The two games he missed at Ole Miss were after he hurt his
elbow, stretching for yardage.
</P>
<P>
   ``John was going against the best in the SEC, and he didn't take
a solid hit,'' said Eddie Gran, running backs coach at Ole Miss.
``You don't get a perfect-form tackle on him. You're just grabbing
at his ankles.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough to catch, as the fish were when he would go on excursions
with his grandfather. ``Not deep sea,'' Avery said. ``I was pretty
sure a marlin would drag me through the water.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Bears, and Lions, and Colts? Big ones?
</P>
<P>
   ``When fear sets in, it doesn't matter who is chasing you,''
Avery said. ``You just run. The lion wakes up every day knowing he
must outrun the fastest gazelle to eat and survive. The gazelle
knows he must outrun the fastest lion.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this little gazelle can wake up a snoozing offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan J. Skolnick writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
