A2279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-JONES20-COX     07-19 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-JONES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones runs into 21st century
 &HT;    By Dani Davies
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sylvia Hatchell thinks of the hundreds of pre-game speeches
she has delivered in 23 years coaching basketball, there is one
moment that stands out.
</P>
<P>
   As she talked to her players before a game during North
Carolina's national championship run in 1994, her eyes met those of
freshman point guard Marion Jones ... and the coach became inspired
by the player.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked at me with so much intensity in her eyes that she
was on the verge of tears, and we hadn't even played the game
yet,'' Hatchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, that intensity has propelled Jones to the edge
of a new conquest. She has emerged on the international track and
field scene as a phenomenon, a just-in-time miracle in a sport of
retiring stars.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackie Joyner-Kersee hangs up her spikes after next
weekend's U.S. Open, Jones will fall into position to be crowned
America's newest speed queen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some observers may have jumped the starting gun on
that coronation. Jones' coach, Trevor Graham, calls Jones ``one of
the greatest female athletes to ever walk on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, that's a swooshing sound you hear in Jones' jet
stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think that if the world doesn't know who Marion
Jones is now, it's only a matter of time before they do,'' said
Dave Mingey, the corporate communications manager for Nike, which
has signed Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 22, combines Joyner-Kersee's athleticism, Dan O'Brien's
charm, Carl Lewis' showmanship, and Wilma Rudolph's history-making
ability, giving track and field fans a hybrid of the best they've
seen.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, she will supplant world records in the
100 and 200 meters, and long jump and win five golds, including
relays, at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney. When that's done, the WNBA
will Marion Jones won the 100 meters in 10.84 seconds in an
Austrian meet this month. Her 10.71 finish in China made her the
world's second-fastest woman after Florence Griffith Joyner, who
holds the record at 10.49.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who will face Joyner-Kersee in this week's Goodwill
Games, is pursuing her many goals with a Lewis-like attitude _ get
out of my way. She's used to critics and skeptics ... those who
questioned her decision to skip track and field for a basketball
scholarship, then leave North Carolina after her junior season to
chase world records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I'm 50, there will be those people talking about
what I should and shouldn't do, but they don't pay my bills,'' she
said. ``To hell with everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 USA Track &AMP; Field News Female Athlete of the Year may
be confident, but she's also smart enough to pace her pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can run faster than a 10.49 (in the 100), faster
than a 21.34 (in the 200) and jump longer than 24-8 1/4 before my
career is over,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Patricia Rico, the president of USA Track &AMP; Field,
everyone is waiting to see whether Jones can follow through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's human nature to want to see records made and records
broken,'' she said. ``We have in our midst one of the greatest
athletes of the future and maybe the greatest of our time, so why
not?''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving UNC last spring, Jones won the world and U.S.
100-meter titles. Then she stunned fans with a 10.71 finish in
Chengdu, China, becoming the world's second-fastest woman after
Florence Griffith Joyner. Last month, she became the first woman in
50 years to win three individual events at the national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner's 100 and 200 world records, which most athletes have
viewed with reverence for 10 years, suddenly seem vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Five gold medals in a single Olympics would be unprecedented.
Jesse Owens and Carl Lewis each won four in 1936 and '84,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Hatchell, when Jones sets a goal for herself
``you can pretty much write it in the books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As an athlete,'' Hatchell said, ``there are no flaws in Marion
Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   When UNC track coach Dennis Craddock first watched her run as a
10th-grader, he saw ``a woman among girls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has that little thing inside her that you can't quite put
your finger on,'' Craddock said. ``It's a fierceness that comes out
in everything she does that makes her a great, great competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jones accepted the basketball scholarship to UNC, track
fans shook their heads. Why would the top sprinter in the nation
trade track for basketball? But when the Tar Heels won the title,
the debate quieted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the championship was kind of a see-I-told-you-so type
of thing for me,'' said Jones, who led ACC freshman in points (494)
and steals (111) that season.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels beat Louisiana Tech 60-59 for the title on
Charlotte Smith's game-winning basket. Jones said it ``felt like
hours'' for the shot to fall. The journalism major said she still
can't find the words to describe the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a feeling that can never be matched,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Games might come close.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones, after 1,716 career points, three ACC titles and one
national championship, passed up her senior season to dedicate
herself to track. UNC fans were confused and crushed and the WNBA
also was left behind _ the league gave Jones an oen invitation to
play that still stands.
</P>
<P>
   But even Hatchell knows Jones made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think track is Marion's future, at least for now,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is intent on achieving her goals on the track, but her
most important objectives go beyond the record books.
</P>
<P>
   She said the best thing about her life is that she's happy, and
that has less to do with sports than it does her health _ she broke
her left foot twice at UNC _ and ``her wonderful fiance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and C.J. Hunter, one of the world's elite shot-putters,
plan to marry in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wouldn't be inspired by her?'' Hunter said from the
couple's home in North Carolina. ``She won't stop until she's
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dani Davies writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
