<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2280 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIZZA-DELIVERERS-COX     07-19 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIZZA-DELIVERERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pizza delivery more costly than you think
 &HT;    By Mike Drummond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Depending on how you slice it, pizza delivery
drivers pay a high price for the privilege of delivering those
pepperoni pies.
</P>
<P>
   Many young drivers hop in the their cars not thinking who would
foot the bill should they cause an accident while on a run.
</P>
<P>
   Many personal insurance carriers will deny the claim, most will
not renew the driver's insurance, and some may do all of the above,
say industry experts.
</P>
<P>
   Domino's Pizza has one of the most unforgiving policies in the
industry when it comes to delivery drivers. This stems in no small
part from the wave of multi-million dollar personal-injury lawsuits
the company settled in the early '90s, after its ``30-minutes or
free'' guarantee triggered a rash of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Like most in the industry, Domino's insurance policies cover
only damage and injury to the other party. If Domino's employees
caused the accident, they have to find some other means to repair
their own cars. They also have to look for other work. ``Our
drivers are fired when they're in accidents,'' said Ann Roth,
director of administration for Western Ohio Pizza Inc., the
franchisee that operates 51 Domino's stores in Ohio and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The company conducts quarterly driving-record checks. It fires
employees who receive three or more moving violations, on or off
the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Like many pizza chains, Domino's carries a standard commercial
non-owned vehicle insurance policy. Unlike many other parlors and
chains, however, Domino's often relies on the personal policies of
its employees to settle claims.
</P>
<P>
   Domino's doesn't like to say that it carries commercial
liability insurance, even to its employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost hate to let them know that we have insurance,'' Roth
conceded. ``That's not something we tell prospective employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for them to know about it until they get
into an accident, and then their insurance is responsible,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Some insurance carriers disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're an employee of a company making deliveries, it
would be logical that the company would cover that employee,'' said
Jim Horvath, a spokesman for Allstate Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to be up front with (delivery drivers),'' said Jan
Ward, director of insurance at the Automobile Club of America's
Dayton office. ``It's not worth it for a lot of these kids to be
working for them (Domino's).''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, the employees' insurance will cover that
accident. Because Domino's automatically fires the employee in an
at-fault accident, the company doesn't have to worry about a
recurring incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be a second time,'' Roth said. ``Our
policy is they carry their own insurance that's primary in any
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The strict policy has helped drive down the Ann Arbor, Mich.,
company's insurance costs by 25 percent over the last decade, Roth
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Hut Inc. also requires its drivers to carry personal auto
insurance and conducts driving-record inspections twice a year. But
the company relies on its own liability insurance when one of its
employees causes an accident and the employee isn't necessarily
fired automatically, said company spokesman Jay Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our insurance company takes care of it,'' he said. ``If we
thought the employees' insurance company would cover it, we
wouldn't need to carry liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies require policy holders to list their
occupations. But many times, young people who are covered in one
job subsequently take a delivery position and fail to tell their
insurance companies. Many parents also fall into this trap.
</P>
<P>
   One Domino's delivery man, who declined to have his name used,
said the job is worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if my insurance company knows I deliver for
Domino's,'' he said. ``But I had a friend whose insurance tripled
when he informed his company he'd be delivering.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, smaller pizza stores struggle whether to pay the high
premiums for commercial insurance, or risk the exposure by not
getting coverage at all. One Dayton pizza shop owner said he didn't
buy insurance for drivers when he first started 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small business owners say, `We don't have anything to lose,'
'' said the owner, who wished to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza drivers typically are 18-24 and put more miles on their
cars than most, too risky a demographic to be covered under a
personal policy. They can choose to get a commercial policy, which
boosts the premiums out of range for most.
</P>
<P>
   That's life in America, said Alan Rubin, president of Carnegie
Insurance Service Corp. in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Domino's has a responsibility to tell employees
(it has its own liability insurance),'' Rubin said. ``Hey, you
don't have to take the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Drummond writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
