<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-2TAKES-NYT     07-19 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS WITH USA SHOW NBC'S EXPANSION GOAL  
 NETWORKS FIND OLD NEWS CAN BECOME NEW HITS  
 FILM STUDIOS COUNTING MORE ON FOREIGN SALES  
 COVERAGE OF COLUMNIST PROVOKES COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The reports that emerged this week about NBC
talking with USA Networks Inc. about a possible joint venture
revived longstanding speculation that NBC's parent, General
Electric, is looking to pull out of the volatile and increasingly
problematic television network business.
</P>
<P>
   But senior executives associated with NBC and GE's management
strategy dismissed the notions that a deal with USA Networks was
ever close to happening or that GE and NBC would soon part.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening, said the executives, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, is the result of focus on a goal long articulated by
Robert Wright, NBC's president: finding an entertainment cable
channel that could provide a secondary revenue source for
programming owned by the network. USA Networks would be an ideal
partner, as would a cable channel owned by Viacom, like
Nickelodeon, or one owned by Time Warner, like TNT, both of whom
NBC has talked to.
</P>
<P>
   What made the USA rumor generate more heat, the executives said,
were two factors: the recent decision by Rupert Murdoch to sell 20
percent of his film, television and sports businesses in an initial
stock offering _ a move many investment bankers would like GE to
emulate with NBC _ and the prospect that NBC's profits, which
peaked last year at about $500 million, are certain to fall in the
coming season.
</P>
<P>
   One senior NBC executive said flatly that John Welch, the
chairman of GE, ``does not want to get rid of NBC'' but pointed out
that Wright, who pursues deals avidly, would continue to look for
an arrangement with the right company, preferably a Hollywood
studio with program production operations. But he added that GE
``would have to retain control for tax reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of control is why previous discussions have broken
down. ``Talks will continue to go on,'' the senior NBC executive
said. ``But I'd put the odds on something happening at one in
five.''
</P>
<P>
   And while NBC executives are aware that they face a downturn in
profits in the coming year, Wright has disputed predictions that
the drop will approach $250 million. The senior executive said NBC
had already instituted a series of cost-cutting measures _ quietly,
for example, imposing a freeze on most hiring.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   NETWORKS FIND OLD NEWS CAN BECOME NEW HITS
</P>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Old news is apparently good news.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest trend in television news programming is something
network executives are calling ``repurposing.'' Specifically, it
means taking previously reported stories, adding some updated
material and perhaps a new title and putting them back on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CBS announced its long-awaited second edition of ``60
Minutes,'' and one of its big elements will be updates of
``classic'' reports from the archives of the original edition.
</P>
<P>
   That came after ABC's announcement that it would repackage
reports from ``Nightline'' as a prime-time entity with some new
reporting. Accompanying those shows, ABC will create a program that
will take some past reports from its news magazines, ``20/20'' and
``Primetime Live,'' link them by theme, such as consumer or nature
stories, and give them an hour in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, CBS decided to use old editions of its ``48
Hours'' program under the title ``48 Hours Mysteries.'' That show
has been one of the biggest network success stories of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   David Westin, the president of ABC News, said in an interview
here that as the networks looked to find ways to generate more
revenue, news was increasingly the logical place to go. Not only do
the networks own the shows, he noted but, ``There was a reason a
lot of big successful news pieces were done in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Nightline,'' Westin said Ted Koppel, the
anchor, had been looking for an outlet to showcase some of the
show's best work and had first thought of going to cable's A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we looked at it and said, `Why not do it for us?' I think
`Nightline' can do a lot more. They have such a backlog of great
material.''
</P>
<P>
   The summer is the ideal place to trot out these repackaged news
shows, Westin said, because of the alarmingly low ratings that
repeats of entertainment programs have been getting.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FILM STUDIOS COUNTING MORE ON FOREIGN SALES
</P>
<P>
   In its first week, Warner Brothers' ``Lethal Weapon 4'' took in
$34 million at U.S. movie theaters. And if its performance matches
that of ``Lethal Weapon 3,'' it could generate $150 million
domestically.
</P>
<P>
   But it could take in even more overseas. ``Lethal Weapon 3''
made $175 million at foreign box offices when it opened in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. films, particularly hits, are doing more business abroad
than ever. Consider that ``Titanic,'' the joint production of
Viacom's Paramount Pictures and News Corp.'s 20th Century Fox, took
in $1.1 billion at foreign box offices. That is almost twice as
much as Steven Spielberg's ``Jurassic Park,'' the second most
successful U.S. film overseas, which had $556 million in foreign
ticket sales in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time _ 20 years ago _ U.S. film companies received
just 40 percent of their ticket sales outside the United States.
Last year, for the first time, film studios made more from movie
theaters overseas than they did from those in the United States,
and with more and more countries adding screens, the lead will most
likely widen, film executives say.
</P>
<P>
   Just as U.S. companies raced to build movie theaters in Great
Britain about five years ago, they are starting to build in South
America and some European countries. And with the expansion of
cable and free television abroad, marketing movies has become
easier.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Warner Brothers can count more certainly on a
built-in market for ``Lethal Weapon 4.'' Over the last six years,
the studio has had plenty of time to build brand awareness as
``Lethal Weapon 3'' played on TV worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Does every American film benefit? Certainly not. The ``small''
American film still does not travel well, and comedy may be king at
home, but generally it is not a great export. Each country's humor
depends on the issues and idiosyncrasies of its own culture.
</P>
<P>
   _ GERALDINE FABRIKANT
</P>
<P>
   COVERAGE OF COLUMNIST PROVOKES COMPLAINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe's own coverage of Patricia Smith, the columnist
who resigned after acknowledging that she fabricated characters in
four columns, has provoked complaints by a group of 20 black women
that the coverage was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter written to The Globe on July 1, the women, including
a civil rights lawyer and a professor at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, made it clear that they condoned neither
what they called ``Smith's misdeed'' nor the paper's decision to
seek her resignation.
</P>
<P>
   But, citing pieces by the Globe columnists David Warsh and
Eileen McNamara on the case, a report by the paper's ombudsman,
Jack Thomas, and an editor's note about the investigation into Ms.
Smith's columns, the women wrote that they ``object strenuously to
the ugly, vindictive campaign the paper is now waging to obliterate
the columnist's otherwise stellar record of achievement as a
journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The paper's approach has not been worthy of a major civic
institution,'' Margaret A. Burnham, the civil rights lawyer who
helped draft the letter, said in an interview last week. ``They've
taken the approach that I, as an employment lawyer, see a lot: What
can we do to control the damage, to circle the wagons, to protect
the people on our staff?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the volume of the paper's coverage was unfair to
Ms. Smith, The Globe's editor, Matthew V. Storin, said, ``I don't
agree with that, although I understand that it looks that way to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the coverage, which included a report about the
withdrawal of a writing award given to Ms. Smith by the American
Society of Newspaper Editors, he added, ``We had certain
obligations to our readers and to the journalism profession to make
public both the follow-up research on her columns and the fact that
the ASNE writing award was being withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe, which is owned by The New York Times Co., is planning
to publish one more article on the matter Monday when the
ombudsman, Thomas, gives his accounting of the extent of Ms.
Smith's fabrications. The paper had earlier reported that it had
identified 52 columns, 28 of them published in 1995, that included
the names of people whose existence could not be immediately
verified.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1996, when Storin, suspecting earlier
fabrications, set down what he later called ``rules of the road''
for three Globe columnists _including Ms. Smith, Eileen McNamara
and Mike Barnicle _ Ms. Smith wrote 196 columns, Thomas said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   In that group, he said, are 20 with unverified information,
including a total of 36 people whose existence could not be
authenticated. But, he said, there was no clear pattern to the
presumed fabrications, ``no persistent political agenda,'' as he
put it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith resigned after admitting to fabricating four
characters in recent columns. Her lawyer, John T. Williams, could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
</TEXT>
