A2289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-48     07-19 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-POLITICS-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ARGENTINA, RURAL TOWN WELCOMES SHELTER FROM WINDS OF CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCUMAN, Argentina _ Antonio Domingo Bussi, the barrel-chested,
cigar-chomping governor here in this tiny northwestern province,
has been getting a lot of bad press lately.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, government investigators discovered that
Bussi, a retired general, had a fat Swiss bank account that he
never disclosed on his tax returns. A court reprimanded him, and he
was suspended from office for several months. But he was not
impeached, thanks to rock-solid support in the provincial
legislature and his popularity among voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not legal problems, they are political problems,''
Bussi said in an interview. He called his enemies ``tricksters and
liars'' who could not fool the people of Tucuman.
</P>
<P>
   While Bussi, 72, is a national icon for a hated past of military
repression, he remains Tucuman's favorite politician. He is banned
by the state constitution from seeking re-election next year, but
his son, congressman Ricardo Bussi, is favored to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   The winds of change rushing through the big cities and most of
the provinces of Argentina somehow don't seem to reach Tucuman,
where churches are still filled on Sunday and everything stops for
the daily three-hour siesta.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only province in Argentina still led by a former
official of the military junta era of the 1970s and 1980s but it is
also one of the only places where the political left has influence.
</P>
<P>
   While labor and university activism has died down almost
everywhere else in the country, here in Tucuman students and union
members still throw debris at policemen in regular and near riotous
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Tucuman economics also follow their own rules. Just beginning to
emerge from virtual bankruptcy, the provincial government still
pays its employees with locally printed money, currency as
worthless as Monopoly bills as soon as it is taken across the
provincial borders.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization has swept Argentina as the government continues to
dismantle Gen. Juan Domingo Peron's statist legacy, but here
privatization has run into big problems with 80 percent of the
households refusing to pay the bills sent by the water utility
taken over by a French company three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bussi, whose party is called the Republican Force, was elected
three years ago on a platform in which he vowed to clean up the
mess left from a series of Peronist governors, and he has succeeded
in cutting the local government's deficit while improving many
services such as paving roads and providing street lighting. A new
lemon boom is lifting the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The propaganda against the military that has confused people
elsewhere in Argentina has not confused people in Tucuman because
the people here felt the horrors of the guerrilla war,'' he said,
adding, ``I am and always will be a military man.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Tucuman has certain aspects of Macondo,'' said Eduardo Gallo,
a sociologist at the University of Tucuman, referring to the
imaginary town in Gabriel Garcia Marquez's novel ``One Hundred
Years of Solitude,'' a place where people levitate and the skies
rain yellow blossoms. ``The place has its peculiarities..''
</P>
<P>
   This impoverished, tropical province of 1.3 million people looks
and feels far more like Central America than the rest of rural
Argentina, which is dominated by the sprawling plains of the pampas
and Patagonia. Here, orange trees line the avenues of this
provincial capital, bearing fruit as fat as melons and flowers that
envelop the city with a sweet fragrance all spring and summer.
Immense sugar cane fields flow to the very edge of the local
airport's landing strip. The province even has its own cuisine;
while meat pies known as empanadas elsewhere in Argentina contain
chopped meat, here it is shredded.
</P>
<P>
   Tucuman has always been a little bit different. Its sugar
economy created a particularly stratified and traditional society,
one in which the plantation barons controlled every aspect of the
lives of their peon workers and ran their own armies as recently as
100 years ago. Tucuman even briefly declared its independence as a
republic in the 1830s, and once waged war against a neighboring
province.
</P>
<P>
   Political turmoil climaxed in the 1970s, when a Cuban-inspired
guerrilla movement grew in the mountains and carried out bombing
campaigns in the towns and cities. The local military government at
the time, led by Bussi, put down the guerrillas, but the civilians
that took power in the 1980s were more efficient at stealing from
the local treasury than running the government.
</P>
<P>
   Bussi's current popularity probably stems from his tough stance
toward Compania de Aguas del Aconquija, the French water company,
as much as anything. He has condoned the public's widespread
refusal to pay its water bills, and from time to time has suggested
he might not pay either.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an irrational cannibalism in Tucuman,'' said Jose
Manuel Garcia Gonzalez, vice president of the embattled water
company. Francois de Rochambeau, the general manager of the
company, said, ``Corruption has no obstacles here because the
people are not bothered by it. Why? Only a sociologist can say.''
</P>
<P>
   The sharply negative views of the two executives is
understandable given that their company is losing $2 million every
month and is seeking to either renegotiate the contract it signed
with a previous governor or leave the province altogether. Bussi
predicted that a resolution would come soon, but at the moment his
constituents were upset with the company because ``we're paying
higher water prices than in France, but with lower quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Such populism is music to the ears of many of Tucuman's
residents, including Daniel Palacios, 22, a worker at a local
strawberry farm. ``The people don't care about what Bussi did
before as long as he helps the people now,'' Palacios said. ``Tough
governors are good for keeping the peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
