<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2293 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLICKMAN-COX     07-19 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLICKMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secretary ready to end Georgia discrimination suit
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman says he is ready to
seek closure to a $2.5 billion race discrimination suit filed by
hundreds of the nation's 18,000 black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has joined the House of Representatives in approving
legislation that removes the two-year statute of limitation in
federal discrimination cases. This measure clears a major hurdle
facing about 600 black farmers in 14 states seeking monetary
damages for proven acts of discrimination in lending and
foreclosures.
</P>
<P>
   A conference committee is expected to act on the measure in the
next couple of weeks , and then it will go to President Clinton for
his signature.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's signature, Alexander Pires, the lead attorney for
the black farmers, says that he expects an estimated 2,500 black
farmers will be impacted immediately by the decision. Twenty-six
farmers from Georgia are involved in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The USDA finally will be able to address these older cases,
seek closure, and where appropriate, properly resolve complaints of
individuals who have been discriminated against,'' Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The provision included in the agriculture appropriations bill
will allow USDA to settle effectively very old discrimination cases
by waiving the statue of limitation in certain instances.
Individuals whose cases fall into this category should not be
punished for USDA's prior failure to investigate their claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of agriculture publicly acknowledges his
department has treated black farmers differently as a matter of
policy in granting farm loans and foreclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Race discrimination complaints from black farmers go back as far
as 1983, when then-President Ronald Regan dismantled the civil
rights section of the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the government to go on now and settle the suit. Their
defense was statute of limitation and you don't have that no more,
now let's settle it,'' said North Carolina farmer Tim Pigford, lead
plaintiff in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see that both the Democrats and Republicans are
comfortable in addressing a long-standing problem,'' said Pires.
House Speaker Newt Gingrich led an effort to remove the statute of
limitations provisions and the mantle was carried in the senate by
senators Charles Robb, D-Va., Thad Cochran, R-Miss., and Dale
Bumpers, D-Ark.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen Georgia farmers are among those suing USDA.
Alvin Walker, 49, once a thriving Putnam County dairy farmer, hopes
that the decision to help black farmers is not too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might just get us out of their face, but I don't know if
it will stop what is going on in the USDA. Racism in that
department is to the bone and the justice system is not moving
against them,'' said Wallker.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is in bankruptcy court trying to keep some of the 150
acres he has owned since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
