</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz's arm good enough for great stats
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Without even throwing his hardest stuff Sunday
afternoon, John Smoltz battled through 90-degree weather and brief
stints of boredom to notch his third straight win. Yet he swears
that his elbow, which has seen him bounce in and out of the
disabled list this season, has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   His numbers tell a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Since coming off the disabled list June 20, Smoltz is 4-1 in six
starts, with a 2.92 ERA. Overall, he's 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an amazing year, a great year for me,'' said Smoltz,
who started the season on the disabled list after arthroscopic
surgery on his elbow in December. ``I'm sneaking up on people
considering what I've been through. But this is still a
reconstruction period for me to get ready for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Things could change real quick for me. The last three or four
starts were tough.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last outing, a 4-2 victory over the New York Mets, Smoltz
threw a season-high 114 pitches. His pitch counts had gone over 100
pitches the last four starts. The National League leader in innings
pitched in 1997 showed no sign of wear Sunday, as he threw only 86
in the 11-6 laugher (opposing pitcher Jeff Juden threw 87 in three
innings).
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoltz was great,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``In a game
like that, there was no sense in leaving him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   He had certainly made his point. Smoltz left the game leading
11-3 after the seventh inning. Before exiting, he retired the side
in order three times and sent six to the bench victims of the
strikeout. He also displayed great control, walking no one. Smoltz
lowered his ERA for the year to 2.53, despite giving up his first
homerun since June 26 to Jeromy Burnitz in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The offense provided plenty of rest for him, scoring in each
inning. Atlanta has provided a lot of run support for Smoltz this
season. In his 14 starts, the Braves have scored 72 runs, an
average of more than five a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat for a long time. Sometimes I felt like I needed a
few warm ups.'' said Smoltz, who helped his cause with a single in
the fifth. ``But I'll take it. This one was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
