<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORE ISSUE: WHOSE APPLES TASTE BETTER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind that the Mariners trail the Texas Rangers in the
American League West standings. There is a more significant issue.
</P>
<P>
   How would the Wenatchee Red Delicious fare in a head-to-head
match with Granny Smith from Texas?
</P>
<P>
   I hate to be the one to break the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Our apples aren't bad apples. But at this stage of the summer
they are T-ball rookies trying to compete against seasoned Texas
Leaguers. Thus the results from the International Apple Festival
are ordained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always hold the International Apple Festival the last
weekend in July,'' explained Baxter Adams. ``We invite 24 different
countries to bring their apples to be judged against Texas
apples.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas never loses, possibly because they grow about the only
apples on the globe that mature the last week of July.
</P>
<P>
   A former petroleum geologist, Baxter is now skipper of the Love
Creek Ranch and apple orchards. When he retired from the oil
business, he bought some land in the Texas hill country, intending
to run a few cattle and live the good life.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the land wouldn't even support a few cattle. This had been
a sheep and goat ranch and it had been grazed to the rock,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Then he met a horticulturist who wondered out loud whether Texas
hill country land might support dwarf apples developed in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That was 15 years ago. Baxter took a gamble and there are now
350,000 apple trees within a 50-mile radius of Medina, Texas. There
are 200 residents in that community. The apple festival draws
20,000 visitors, prepared to sample ``the best apples in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Granny Smiths are 40 percent sweeter than Washington's,''
Baxter insists.
</P>
<P>
   We visited his ranch last spring. It looks more like a vineyard.
The dwarfs are tied to wire trellises and can be picked without the
aid of ladders.
</P>
<P>
   As good as his Granny Smiths may be, Baxter confided that the
best apple he has tasted is the Pink Lady from western Australia.
He is now growing Pink Ladies in Texas. But he has heard the rumors
from out of the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blows my mind,'' he admitted. ``With their short growing
season, I don't know how they can grow Pink Ladies in Yakima. But
they know a lot about apples.''
</P>
<P>
   They will be eating a lot of pie at Adam's Apples produce stand,
gift shop and restaurant outside Medina this month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the Yakima Valley residents are biding their time,
waiting for their apple crop to come in, when they'll be able to
produce desserts like apple cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime we can all enjoy:
</P>
<P>
   Alice's Blackberry Crisp
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh blackberries
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Spread blackberries in a 9-by-13-inch oven dish. Sprinkle with
lemon juice and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Combine remaining ingredients and spread over berries. Bake 30
to 35 minutes at 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm with vanilla ice cream or vanilla yogurt. Feeds four
to six.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene's Apple Cheesecake
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cube butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large Golden Delicious apples
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup plus 2 tablespoons granulated sugar (divided)
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup currants
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce packet cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Let the cream cheese come to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Combine in a bowl the flour and powdered sugar. With a pastry
blender cut in the butter until the mixture resembles cornmeal.
With your fingers (or those of a very close friend), press this
mixture over the bottom and sides of an 11-inch flan pan or a
9-inch regular pie pan. Halve, peel and core the Washington apples
and cut into quarter-inch slices. Arrange them in the pan,
overlapping slightly. Sprinkle with two tablespoons granulated
sugar and the currants.
</P>
<P>
   Next, plop the cream cheese into the bowl of an electric mixer.
Add three-quarters cup sugar, the lemon peel, lemon juice and the
eggs. Beat until smooth, then pour evenly over the apples.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cheesecake about 30 minutes in a 350-degree oven, or
until the cheese mixture is just set and very lightly browned
around the edges. Let cool to room temperature, then refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves eight.
</P>
<P>
   Texans at the Medina International Festival annually crown Miss
Apple Dumpling (ages 4 to 8) and Mrs. Apple Blossom (65 and older).
Marlene Johnson, a Washington resident who contributed this recipe,
is too old for the former award, too young for the latter. Those
Texas poker players really know how to stack the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Aha, but did you know the Washington Apple Commission annually
names a Granny Smith as its representative each year?
</P>
<P>
   After a nationwide search, the commission crowned Joan Phillips
as 1998 spokeswoman for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to second-guess the selection committee. But Mrs.
Phillips just happens to be a resident of Plano, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
