   HOUSEDEBATES-FINANCE (Washington) _ Call it the capital's
rendition of ``Eine Kleine Nachtmusik,'' the sometimes discordant
strains of the campaign finance debate that is relegated to the
post prime-time hours of the House's summer agenda. The vistors'
galleries are empty. The reporters and TV crews that cram the
Capitol in daylight have all but dispersed. But like nightwandering
vampires, a small coven of lawmakers arises in full majesty to take
the floor for a debate that often does come close to drawing blood.
They only come out at night, and they are scheduled to resume
debate after the sun sets on Monday. By Alison Mitchell. (Scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) 1,400 words.
