<DOCNO> NYT19980719.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-HUMMER20-COX     07-19 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-HUMMER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner an unstuffy Goodwill host
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ted Turner's little sports festival won't quite scale
Olympian heights, but he enjoys one advantage over Games more great
and glorious.
</P>
<P>
   He's way more cool than Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is not your father's patriarch. He plays the convivial
host of these Goodwill Games _ now in their fourth incarnation _
rather than overstuffed nabob who rules from untouchable heights.
</P>
<P>
   When a foreign radio correspondent thrusts a microphone in his
face and asks Turner to say a few words to the Russian people, he
takes that as a cue to frolic. A careful, official statement does
not follow.
</P>
<P>
   He seizes the mike and exclaims, ''Hey, we love you Russia, man!
How are things going over there? We love you over there. Hope you
have good luck at the Goodwill Games!''
</P>
<P>
   Big differences can be found in little phrases. ''Pretty
terrific,'' Turner blurted out on stage Saturday night during the
Goodwill opening celebration. ''Most exceptional,'' the other guy
used on Atlanta one summer night. Which one would you rather have
run your track meet?
</P>
<P>
   ''I can afford to be (more relaxed). I don't have as many people
to answer to,'' Turner says. ''Oh, I have some people to answer to
(since the Time-Warner deal), just not as many.''
</P>
<P>
   As he worked the room in a private, VIP party before the opening
celebration, Turner played official greeter, inquiring of each
person he met, ''You having a good time?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Just like any time you throw a party, you're supposed to go
around making sure people are enjoying themselves. And there were a
lot of sponsors there,'' he said. Yes, there remains a business
aspect to his obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and wife Jane Fonda began the Games out front, breathing
as much personality as they can into a project that otherwise has
lacked for one. It works, to see the Italian synchronized swimming
team ignoring the celebration on the stage while trying to get
pictures of the couple. Or the one fan in the VIP area who
persuaded Fonda to sign her thigh.
</P>
<P>
   These next two weeks are highly personal. Turner bought into the
Braves and the Hawks and, lately, the Thrashers. The Goodwill
Games, Turner invented, and he will defend them as blood kin.
</P>
<P>
   If that means perpetuating his claim that mere sport can change
the world, then so be it. ''I have an incredible sense of pride
because I know that they had a lot to do with easing up the
tensions that made the Cold War possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The Goodwill Games) are at least as important to him as any
of his teams,'' said Terry McGuirk, chairman and CEO of Turner
Broadcasting System, Inc., who's been with Turner since 1972. ''He
still sees that there's a world mission to be done. And the other
side is it's an awful lot of good programming.''
</P>
<P>
   They seem to feed a need within Turner, obvious by the way he
has taken in the last two days. We cynics have tried to tell him
the Goodwill Games have outlived their original purpose of bringing
a boycott-crazy world together, and that they are but a
little-noticed money pit. He takes much glee in not listening.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know,'' Turner warns, ''we're still looking hard at the
possibility of Winter Goodwill Games.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's so full of pepper these days,'' said McGuirk. That's
saying much for a man known to be dangerously spicy.
</P>
<P>
   Turner was scheduled to leave for his Montana digs Sunday night,
returning to New York later in the week. Even the itinerary somehow
wound into a punchline. ''I'll watch it every evening. It gives me
a chance to see the production. I'm not hands-on that much. I put
my hands on a knife and fork three times a day. What else I put my
hands on, I can't talk about. No other women, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Before departing, he paid call on Sunday's U.S.-Puerto Rico
basketball game. 'Twas not a highly ceremonial visit.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss of Goodwill would chase down the guys shooting rolled
up T-shirts into the seats to fetch one for his 5-year-old
grandson, John. He would stand and dance during a musical
interlude. Midway through the first half, he leaned back to press
row and get a partial score on the Braves game back home.
</P>
<P>
   While he was there he'd shoot a couple unsolicited comments
toward his new friends in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is great. Nobody thought these Games would happen. What
would the Olympics be worth if you could buy them? I tell you, this
is going to be a big franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ''You see where (IOC member) Dick Pound doesn't like us. He
said we were just a made-for-TV Olympics. Imagine that. He must
think we're competition. Isn't that what life's all about,
competition?''
</P>
<P>
   It has been estimated that the first three Goodwill Games lost
$109 million. This one, too, is expected to bleed, only not as
much. Never have you seen a man more determined to get his money's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
