<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECYCLED-AD-COLUMN-AR     07-19 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECYCLED-AD-COLUMN-ART-615(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ADS ABOUT ADS MAKE A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: CANADA, Calif., Fla., N.Y., Wis. )  (Eds.: Budgeted earlier as ADVERTISING-ADCOL) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Advertising is often described as holding a mirror to
society. Now more than ever, the mirror is reflecting back images
of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising about advertising, once a marketing mainstay, is
again a popular trend along Madison Avenue. Consumers are being
bombarded by sophisticated television and radio commercials, print
ads, billboards and World Wide Web sites that are self-reflexively
devoted to advertising. These are ads that announce they're ads,
parody other ads, describe how agencies create ads, debate how
consumers react to ads _ and even caution against believing
advertising hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, cheeky commercials for the Sprite soft drink
marketed by Coca-Cola Co. assert: ``Image is nothing. Thirst is
everything. Obey your thirst.'' The ads mock ads for products,
including soft drinks _ as well as Coca-Cola's own decision to sign
the basketball star Grant Hill to endorse Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is: `Don't trust the endorser. Just drink what tastes
good,''' said C.J. Waldman, an art director at the Sprite agency,
Lowe &AMP; Partners-SMS in New York, part of the Lowe Group unit of
Interpublic Group of companies. ``The message is more believable
when you take out the baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising about advertising is making a comeback for several
reasons, ranging from an emphasis on ads that entertain to a need
to appeal to younger consumers. Marketers hope that
self-deprecation will soften the hardness of sales pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``By saying you're not taking advertising seriously, it says by
extension that you're not taking yourself seriously either,'' said
Tom Kraemer, a copywriter at Ammirati Puris Lintas in New York, a
unit of Interpublic that has created ads about ads for the Burger
King fast-food chain owned by Diageo PLC.
</P>
<P>
   A recent commercial for the Burger King Chicken Crisp sandwich,
for example, spoofed the familiar series of spots for De Beers in
which shadowy couples celebrate diamond gifts. The tongue-in-cheek
spot, Kraemer said, treated the new menu item ``as if it were
comparable to a $5,000 diamond.''
</P>
<P>
   Though ads about ads may seem novel, they're not new.
</P>
<P>
   Back in radio days, comedians like Jack Benny and Fred Allen
delivered commercials that were devoted to their reluctance to
deliver commercials. The trailer for the 1947 film ``Miracle on
34th Street'' was about the making of the trailer for ``Miracle on
34th Street.'' And in the 1950s and 1960s, such performers as
Arthur Godfrey, Ernie Kovacs, George Burns, Stan Freberg and Henry
Morgan frequently broke the fourth wall to offer wry sendups of
sponsors and ad agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the mirth, the goal is the same as for any
huckster's spiel: to promote a product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to try to create a bond between the advertiser and
the audience that declares `We're all in this together,' '' said
Larry Adelman, a critic of consumer culture who is co-director of
California Newsreel, a documentary center in San Francisco. ``But
we keep buying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hip, ironic way to co-opt a growing public backlash
against advertising's ubiquity,'' he added, ``and undercut any
impulse to think critically about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers may discover that ads about ads do not sneak under
the radar but rather remind consumers how inundated they are by
advertising _ and how much they dislike it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advertising industry will suffer,'' warned Kalle Lasn,
editor of Adbusters, a publication of the Media Foundation in
Vancouver, British Columbia, that attacks consumerism, ``because
once you start to denigrate advertising, you keep cynicism
growing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like biting your own tail,'' he added. ``Eventually, you
bite off the tail.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The resurgence in ads about ads may be traced to 1989, when
Energizer started running commercials in which a pink
battery-powered bunny kept ``going and going and going'' through
make-believe spots for products like coffee, nasal spray and soap.
There were 47 commercials through 1993 and then a brief reprise in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Current examples include a Levi's jeans campaign with a
self-aware attitude about fashion advertising, which proclaims
``Our models can beat up their models''; a Web site for Simple
Shoes Inc. offering an archive of ads carrying such headlines as
``I went through five years of art school and all you get is this
dumb ad''; ads for Miller Lite beer presented as the handiwork of
``Dick,'' an imaginary agency ``creative superstar''; ads for
Diesel apparel that lampoon marketing tactics like linking products
to social causes, and a campaign for Captain Morgan rum in which
the Seagram brand's pirate character parodies various ads and asks
on the Internet ``Is it me, or is this site trying to promote some
product?''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Shapiro, executive vice president for marketing at the
Seagram Americas unit of the Seagram Co. in New York, said: ``We
never set out to use advertising to sell, but the feedback we've
gotten from consumers is outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best-liked ads of all time were self-referential,
from the Bert and Harry Piel campaign for Piels beer, which
featured the voices of Bob Elliott and Ray Goulding, to the ``spicy
meatball'' spot for Alka-Seltzer, which showed an actor developing
heartburn during the shooting of a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, however, the approach faded as agencies played down
showy creative techniques in favor of playing up the features and
benefits of products.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's back, for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One is that advertisers are taking their cues from a flood of
self-referential material in the popular culture: TV series about
TV series like ``Home Improvement'' and ``The Larry Sanders Show'';
movies about movies like ``The Player'' and ``Living in Oblivion,''
and journalists scrutinizing the performance of other journalists
in Brill's Content magazine (with other journalists then
scrutinizing the performance of Brill's Content). There was even a
novel, ``The Bestseller,'' about writing a best-selling novel.
</P>
<P>
   Since imitation is often the sincerest form of advertising,
Madison Avenue has been inspired to turn its gaze inward and devote
a growing part of its output to itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising has become institutionalized as a cultural
reference point,'' said Bill Westbrook, president of Fallon
McElligott in Minneapolis, the Miller Lite agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good or bad, advertising is pervasive,'' he added. ``If I do a
takeoff on an ad campaign, I have some degree of confidence a
significant number of people will know what I'm talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Freeman, chairman and chief creative officer at the Cliff
Freeman &AMP; Partners unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC in New York,
labeled advertising ``the great unifier'' in a consumer culture
fragmented into niche markets and segmented media choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're with a bunch of strangers with nothing to say,''
said Freeman, who often produced humorous ads about ads for the
Little Caesars pizza chain, ``all you have to do is bring up
commercials and everyone has an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly true for a special demographic group, 20-
and 30-somethings. Advertisers' ardor to appeal to those
free-spending but finicky consumers is a big reason why ads about
ads have returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a target audience that is media savvy and cynical,'' said
Bob Kuperman, president and chief executive for the Americas at the
TBWA Chiat/Day unit of Omnicom Group, which created the Energizer
campaign for Ralston-Purina Co. ``You go to focus groups and they
talk in marketing terms; they say, `Before I discuss this, can I
see the creative brief?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know advertising,'' he added, and they ``distrust so much
of it, so you try to break down the barrier and get the
salesmanship out of it. The less you're selling obviously to this
group, the better off you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rooney, vice president for marketing at the Miller
Brewing Company unit of Philip Morris Cos. in Milwaukee, which
sells Miller Lite, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average 25-year-old has a thicker skin for traditional
marketing devices than the average 40-year-old,'' he said. ``So you
have to be a little more clever.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Lite campaign, Rooney said, ``people realize you're
having fun at your own expense, that you're showing some humility.
To a large extent, that has worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney also raised another reason for the popularity of ads
about ads: a shift to entertaining ads that seek to develop
pleasing personalities for brands from ads that recite product
attributes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the beer business talk less about the quality
characteristics of the product like `cold filtered,' `beechwood
aged' or `Tastes great. Less filling,' '' he said, ``because
consumers assume that.''
</P>
<P>
   So ``there needs to be something else about your brand that gets
people motivated,'' he added. ``The personality of the brand is
driving it more so than ever. If you're not as tied to making sure
you talk about the hops, that opens the door for a wider range of
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy has been extended beyond Lite's ads to Lite's
packaging. The brand now ``pokes fun at itself,'' Rooney said, with
such language as this from the sides of cans: ``This beer has your
name on it. Wait. It has our name on it. Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the appeal of ads about ads, pitfalls lurk.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious is that the trend may represent little more
than self-indulgent navel gazing, predicated on a misimpression
that consumers are fascinated by something about which they are
actually indifferent, or worse yet, antagonistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run the risk of no one understanding it except people in
the advertising industry,'' said Kuperman of TBWA Chiat/Day, who
decried ``the self-absorption of advertising about advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that problem, he added, the Energizer bunny campaign
parodied easily recognized genres (soft drink ads, celebrity
endorsements, late-night record offers) rather than specific spots.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dick character now plays only a minor role in the Lite
campaign. ``You don't want to do it for too long,'' Rooney said of
ads about ads, because otherwise ``you become a parody of
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a cheerleader contest Miller sponsored last fall was
promoted so self-reflexively that distributors complained customers
perceived it as a spoof of contests and refrained from entering.
</P>
<P>
   ``If advertising about advertising becomes too popular,''
Freeman of the Freeman agency said, ``it would no longer be
surprising. It would just become boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing a consumer can say is `I've seen that,' '' he
added. ``And advertising is so derivative; as soon as somebody hits
on something, everyone follows.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there have recently been instances when ads about ads
came out at the same time as other ads about the same ads. The De
Beers spoof for Burger King was running simultaneously with a spot
by a Miami agency, Crispin Porter &AMP; Bogusky, for another fast food
chain, Checkers, that also spoofed the diamond commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfortunate, a really bizarre coincidence,'' said
Kraemer at Ammirati Puris, as well as ``a creative's worst
nightmare, because the idea of doing what we do is to come up with
something fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is the possibility that ads about ads _ by attempting
to parry critics who try to subvert advertising through advertising
_ will only spur them on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making it harder for those like us to get back at
them,'' Lasn said, adding that when he saw a recent Diesel
campaign, which mocked ads for Benetton apparel, ``I thought, `They
finally snookered us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Lasn and other advocates of less commercialism may have
discovered a counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we're finding it increasingly hard to `outcool' them
because of this trend,'' he said, ``we're moving more into straight
information ads instead of parodies.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a recent foray against Philip Morris for selling
cigarettes avoided ad spoofs assaulting the Marlboro cowboy or the
Virginia Slims woman. Rather, an ad in Adbusters ``simply asked
people why they're buying food from a tobacco company,'' Lasn said,
referring to brands like Kraft and Minute Rice that are sold by
Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it worked,'' he added. ``People talked about it. I did a
lot of radio talk shows.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be something advertisers want to reflect on the next
time they see themselves in that mirror.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
