<SLUG> BC-HENRYHOLT-CEO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY HOLT CEO TO LEAVE FOR GERMAN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET EMBARGO for
electronic media.) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Naumann, the mercurial and blunt-spoken chief
executive of Henry Holt &AMP; Co., will leave the literary publishing
house, which he has headed for two years, to pursue a chance to
become Germany's minister of culture for the Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In his typical maverick fashion, Naumann, 56, revealed his plans
early on Friday afternoon, at a time when most publishers had
retreated for long summer weekends. Not even John Sargent _ who
manages the service companies for Verlagsgruppe Georg von
Holtzbrinck, the German conglomerate that owns Henry Holt _ knew
until he was told by a reporter that Naumann had made the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has long been driven very much by the politics and culture
of Germany,'' said Sargent, who is also chief executive of St.
Martin's Press, another Holtzbrinck company. ``Knowing Michael's
commitment, I think it's great for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Naumann raised the profile of Henry Holt with generous advances
for prominent authors like Salman Rushdie and with a blend of charm
and candor that sometimes rattled the publishing industry. He
boycotted the National Book Awards when the judges failed to
nominate a Holt book, ``Mason &AMP; Dixon'' by Thomas Pynchon, and he
canceled a contract with the best-selling author Gloria Naylor for
a manuscript he considered unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt, which does business of $45 million a year, is losing
money, according to Sargent. And there had been speculation that
Naumann would leave.
</P>
<P>
   But Naumann said that he had not been pressured to depart. ``I
had no intention of leaving,'' he said. ``I can honestly tell
you,'' he added, ``that the company is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Sargent said that in the last four months, revenue and profits
had started to increase. Two titles have been on the New York Times
best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann, a German citizen who formerly headed Rowohlt Verlag,
which is owned by Holtzbrinck and is one of the largest publishing
companies in Germany, said he was approached last week by a member
of a search committee formed by the German Social Democrats to seek
someone to fill the new position of minister of culture if they win
in national elections in September. The party has a strong chance
of beating Chancellor Helmut Kohl and the Christian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats are led by Gerhard Schroder, the governor
of Lower Saxony. Naumann said he had received a telephone call on
Thursday from Schroder, inviting him to become minister of culture
if the party won.
</P>
<P>
   Although he still had three years remaining on a five-year
contract with Henry Holt, Naumann said, he decided to leave to
pursue the cabinet opportunity to demonstrate his commitment to the
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a country which was savaged by its own history,''
Naumann said. ``And I belong to that generation born during the war
that had numerous questions and tried to redefine the course of our
country. So it sounds rather pathetic, but it's really true _ I've
started to really enjoy the democratic institutions in my
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Naumann said he would remain at Henry Holt until a successor is
found, adding that if the Social Democrats do not gain power, he
would be likely to look for another publishing position. A few
months ago, one of Holtzbrinck's German newspapers approached
Naumann to become its publisher, but he rejected the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, in an article in Vanity Fair about
Holtzbrinck, Thomas McCormack, the former chief executive of St.
Martin's Press, was reported as suggesting that Naumann would
probably leave the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly fits into what I predicted,'' McCormack said on
Friday. ``I do know that he was very much on the skids here, and it
would have been a good face-saving pretext if an offer like this
heaved up, as it did.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormack said that Naumann was ``very much over his head at
Henry Holt, but his head was such that he would take advice from
almost no one at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sargent, however, said that Naumann was striving to improve
Henry Holt and that progress was being made. ``It is a difficult
task to turn around a company like Holt from where it was to a
profitable level,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
