<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Chicago Cubs
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight and Tuesday at 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV: Fox Sports South will broadcast both games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Denny Neagle (10-7,
3.17; 6-4, 3.98 lifetime vs. Cubs) vs. RHP Kevin Tapani (10-6,
4.84; 2-2, 4.67 lifetime vs. Braves). Tuesday, RHP Greg Maddux
(13-3, 1.57; 7-0, 1.51 vs. Cubs) vs. RHP Kerry Woods (8-5, 3.46;
0-0, 3.46 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 200-194 and
has not lost a season series to the Cubs since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves are 3-4 against the Cubs after being
swept in a three-game series at Wrigley Field May 29-31, Chicago
beating John Rocker, Kevin Millwood and Denny Neagle. The Braves
took three of four from the Cubs May 22-25, outscoring them 25-18.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs leaders: Avg.: Mark Grace (.325); HR _ Sammy Sosa (36); RBI
_ Sosa (89); SB _ Sosa (13). W _ Kevin Tapani (10); ERA _ Terry
Mulholland (3.10). Strikeouts _ Kerry Wood (156). Saves _ Rod Beck
(25).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Cubs, who lost five of their first nine out of the
All-Star break, are concluding a 12-game road trip, the club's
longest of the season. . . . With five regulars hitting .300 or
better and the 59 home runs between Sammy Sosa and Henry Rodriguez,
the Cubs get consistent run support, the 5.03 per-game average
ranking fourth in the league. But the club also leaves an average
7.1 men on base each game, fourth most in the league. . . . The
Cubs need all the run support they can find because their starters'
ERA is a ripe 4.43. Braves starters, by comparison, is 2.99. . .
Sosa ranks in the NL top 10 in eight offensive categories. He has
homered twice against Atlanta but both came within three at-bats
May 25 off Mike Cather and Kevin Millwood at Turner Field. . . .
Between Sosa (118 hits) and Mark Grace (117), Chicago has two
players chasing 200-hit seasons. The last Cub to reach 200 was Ryne
Sandberg in 1984. . . . Tapani is facing the Braves for the third
time this year, losing at Atlanta 9-5 in May 25 and defeating the
Braves 4-2 at Wrigley. He is unbeaten in his last four starts and
is coming off a 7-4 win in Pittsburgh last Tuesday. Despite his
record, he has given up 17 earned runs in his last three starts and
his ERA (4.84) is at its highest point in almost 13 weeks. . . . On
the DL: OF Brant Brown (separated left shoulder) and LHP Pedro
Valdes (strained left foot).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: Entering Sunday night, Grace was hitting .341 with 43
RBI in his last 73 games. Tyler Houston is hitting .424 in his last
11 games. Since joining the Cubs July 6, Glenallen Hill is 7-for-20
with four RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: Jeff Blauser went into Sunday night's game with eight
hits in his last 42 at-bats (.190). Since being called up from
Class AAA Iowa June 26, Kevin Orie is hitting .189 (7-for-37).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
