<SLUG> BC-BRITBAR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watts won't quickly be forgotten after inspired British
performance
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ The more pleasant news for Brian Watts:
With $329,000 earned for second place Sunday in the British Open,
that's enough money to gain fully exempt status on the PGA Tour
next year. Maybe with such an opportunity, he'll pull away from his
home base, the Japan Tour, where he has starred for six years and
and piled up enough yen to retire at 32.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe Watts will just tour the world, doing clinics
on bunker play under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless what transpired in the four-hole playoff at Royal
Birkdale, where Mark O'Meara prevailed to win his second major of
the year and his career, Watts' bunker shot at the 18th hole, the
72nd of the tournament, will be remembered as one of golf's
greatest pressure shots ever. With one foot out of the bunker and
peering down at a downhill lie, Watts would have impressed
observing Birkdale members and a worldwide television audience if
the ball had stopped six or eight feet from the hole. Instead,
Watts chopped down on the ball and stiffed it to tap-in range,
parring the hole, matching O'Meara at even-par 280 and heading to
the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to create something in my mind and I visualized a
good shot, and fortunately it came off almost perfect,'' Watts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Was the visualization detailed enough to included a ball
smacking into the flagstick and disappearing, giving Watts the
Claret Jug?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Only that would have prevented what transpired over the next
hour. O'Meara's key shot of the final round evolved as the 4-iron
to three feet at the par-3 14th, creating his first lead. In the
playoff, O'Meara got his edge on the first extra hole, the par-5
15th, making birdie from five feet. Watts lipped out from four
feet, then self-destructed the chance for a recovery birdie at the
17th. He drove right into the hay, popped out with a wedge and was
lucky to make par.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I didn't hit the fairway on 17, that was pretty much a
one-stroke penalty,'' Watts said. ``I was able to advance it about
30 yards to where Mark's drive was and mine should have been. But
after I made par on 17, I still felt I had chance because I was
only a stroke back.''
</P>
<P>
   At 18, with the multitudes climmbing through the seaside
underbrush, Watts found a shallower greenside bunker and this time
blasted long. O'Meara, with a well-struck 4-iron to the green, won
with two putts. After running his first putt three feet by, causing
a groan from the crowd, O'Meara grinned, stroked it in and raised
his arms to the gray sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't feeling any more pressure than I was when I've done
well in Japan before,'' Watts said. ``I tried to hit my shots, go
through my routine. I tried to keep it as simple as I could and not
think about leading the British Open Championship.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, now wasn't the time for Watts to elaborate.
His disappointment with the present tended to dominate. That a
gentleman such as O'Meara had defeated him, offered a bit of
solace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him after he won on the last hole, if it wasn't me,
I'm glad that he won,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
