<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-GOODWILL-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL JOHNSON PUTS HIS INJURIES BEHIND HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also GYM-GOODWILL-GAMES, BKO-GOODWILL-GAMES,
RHODEN-COLUMN-GOODWILL) 
(mk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ To hear his coach talk, Michael Johnson's hips
have been out of alignment, much like the front end of a car. That,
in turn, has left his wheels wobbling, from his tight hamstrings to
his strained Achilles' tendon. But after a frustrating early
season, Johnson said he was again ready to road-test his form at
400 meters, where he is accustomed to reaching the finish line
greeted by a checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   He will run the quarter-mile on Tuesday at the Goodwill Games,
hoping to lower a 44.40-second performance in Rome last week. That
was Johnson's best time of an interrupted season that found him
finishing an unaccustomed third in Oslo in 44.58 to two British
sprinters. But his injury problems appear to be behind him, Johnson
said Sunday at a news conference. He can again think about winning
races instead of only about staying healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective is to end the season ranked No. 1 in the world
and winning the rest of my races,'' Johnson said. ``I feel
confident I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He strung together 58 consecutive victories in the 400 from 1990
until 1997 and won the Olympic gold medal in the 200 and 400 at the
1996 Summer Games in Atlanta. But he strained a quadriceps muscle
in a 150-meter race against Donovan Bailey in June 1997, which
essentially ruined Johnson's season, except for a gutsy performance
at that year's world championships in Athens, where he won the 400
on sheer determination.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics aside, that victory in Athens may have been the
greatest of Johnson's career. It was especially phenomenal, said
his coach, Clyde Hart, considering that Johnson's left leg had
one-third less strength than the right leg and one-third slower
reaction time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like running on a flat tire,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Johnson's hip alignment continued into this
season as he found himself training one or two days a week and then
having to take the rest of the week off. From day to day, he did
not know what his legs would allow him to do. With massage and
special exercises, Hart said, Johnson has corrected the problem in
the last month and now lacks only races to regain complete fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to deal with emotionally, not knowing when
I'm going out to train whether I'm going to get injured,'' Johnson
said. ``It got to the point whether it was day to day. Thankfully
I've got that behind me. I can go out and train hard every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is a month behind in training, Johnson said, which
left him unable to compete effectively at 200 meters. He withdrew
from the event here. But he said that attempts to write off his
career before the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia, were
premature.
</P>
<P>
   Only injuries have slowed him, Johnson said, adding that he
believed he could still run under 43 seconds at 400 meters when
completely healthy, which would shatter Butch Reynolds' world
record of 43.29 seconds. Johnson owns the second-fastest time of
43.39 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   If he starts running 45 and 46 seconds, he said, he won't have
to be pushed out of the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you show vulnerability, people say, `O.K., it's
time,''' Johnson said. ``But they don't take into account what it
is. They don't think about injuries. The day I'm not running fast
and it's not because of injuries, I'll be in retirement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
