<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This Week In Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Sunday's games still out are: Minn-Oakland, KC-Seattle,
Balt-Anaheim, Tampa-Texas)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Orioles 5-1 (47-51), Red Sox 4-3 (56-40), Yankees 3-4
(68-24), Blue Jays 3-5 (50-50), Devil Rays 2-4 (36-60).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Yankees 13-3, Red Sox 9-7, Blue
Jays 9-7, Orioles 5-11, Devil Rays 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Red Sox lead league, Blue Jays 9 games back,
Orioles 10 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Orioles had their nine-game winning streak
broken on Saturday while the Yankees actually had a losing week.
Holy Cow!
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: The Red Sox set a major league record Saturday
with four two-out homers in the fourth inning. The all-time mark is
held by the Giants, who in 1939 hit five two-out homers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Toronto's Roger Clemens is hot with 11 wins,
moving his ERA down to 3.38 and his 140 strikeouts are third in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Blue Jays starter Juan Guzman has a
league-leading 12 losses.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Yankees centerfielder Bernie Williams came off
the disabled list Saturday and went 3-for-5 with a home run.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Yankees announced that Mel Allen, the longtime
voice of the club, will be posthumously honored with a bronze
plaque in Monument Park at Yankee Stadium. The unveiling will come
July 26.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: White Sox 6-2 (43-55), Tigers 4-3 (41-54), Royals 2-4
(42-54), Twins 2-4 (44-52), Indians 2-5 (54-42).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Indians 10-6, Twins 7-9, White Sox
7-9, Tigers 7-9, Royals 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: None.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: It appears now as if the Twins will remain in
Minnesota, the possibility of building a new park now a reality,
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: White Sox outfielder Albert Belle hit the 300th
homer of his career Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The best ERA in the league? It's Cleveland's
Bartolo Colon, at .248 followed by Boston's Pedro Martinez (.272)
and Hideki Irabu (2.79) of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: On Saturday Indians shortstop Omar Vizquel
made his first error in 55 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Form Brave and now White Sox catcher Charlie
O'Brien was put on the DL with a chipped fracture in his right
thumb.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The White Sox are trying to sign Robin Ventura to a
contract extension but several teams continue to call about
acquiring the third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Mariners 6-0 (45-53), A's 3-3 (45-51), Angels 2-4
(53-43), A's 3-3 (45-51), Rangers 2-4 (53-44).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Angels 10-6, Rangers 8-8, A's 8-8,
Mariners 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wild-card hunt: Rangers 2 1/2 back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The division is getting ugly again as both the
Rangers and Angels are in slumps while the Mariners have been the
hottest team since the break but it may be a little too late. The
Mariners went into Sunday's game with an 8-2 mark on the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Former Brave Rico Rossy, now the third baseman
with the Mariners, had a career high four hits Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Since getting in a clubhouse wrestling match
with David Segui, Mariners lefthander Randy Johnson has thrown
back-to-back shutouts, striking out 26.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Over a two-game period against the Royals, the
Mariners scored 26 runs on 35 hits and had 50 baserunners.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Angels righthander Chuck Finley is listed as
day-to-day after suffering a laceration that required stitches in
his right knee in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: It is just a matter of time before Anaheim's Tim
Salmon goes on the DL. The ligament in his left heel is 70 percent
torn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
