<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This week in Review
 &HT;    (EDS: Sunday's games still out are: San Fran-Houston (wild card
mention should be changed once that game is over), Cubs-Fla,
LA-Cards, Rockies-Arizona, Phillies-Mets.)
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Braves 5-1 (65-33), Marlins 2-3 (37-59), Mets 2-4
(48-45), Phillies 3-4 (49-46), Expos 3-4 (39-58).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Mets 9-7, Braves 9-7, Marlins 8-8,
Phillies 7-9, Expos 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Mets 2 1/2 games back, Phillies 3 1/2 games
back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: With Mark Wohlers continuing to struggle, the
Braves are still looking for bullpen help. The Braves have called
the Phillies about Mark Leiter but the club wants prospect George
Lombard in return. That may be too much.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Braves third baseman Chipper Jones is hitting
.471 (24-for-51) this month with seven home runs and 13 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Braves starters are 12-4 with two no decisions
in their last 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: Braves rightfielder Michael Tucker has just
one hit in his last 29 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: After three weeks on the disabled list, Mets
starter Al Leiter came back Saturday and threw six shutout innings
in a 7-0 victory over the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Braves went over the 2 million mark in
attendance for the eighth straight season while Mets manager Bobby
Valentine is using reliever Mel Rojas to throw batting practice
after he refused a minor league assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Pirates 5-2 (45-53), Astros 3-2 (57-39), Reds 3-3
(45-53), Cubs 2-3 (52-44), Brewers 3-4 (48-48), Cardinals 1-5
(44-52).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Astros 10-4, Brewers 8-6, Reds 7-6,
Pirates 6-7, Cubs 5-8, Cardinals 4-9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Cubs 1/2 game back, Brewers 4 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: How have the Astros built their cushion in the
division? Not against clubs from their own division, just 12-11
against teams from the Central while they are 17-6 against the
East. And the Cardinals just keep on falling.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Cardinals first baseman Mark McGwire picked up
his 100th walk Saturday and is now 16 shy of a career high which he
set in Oakland in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: Teams looking for pitching are calling
Cincinnati about Pete Harnisch, who is 7-4 with a 3.06 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: During their recent winning streak, the Reds
players tuned the clubhouse stereo to songs from the 1970s, the
days of the Big Red Machine.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: The Cubs finally got back outfielder Lance
Johnson, who had been on the 60-day with an injured right hand.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: With 41 homers, McGwire is just one homer shy of
matching the team record set by Johnny Mize in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Padres 6-1 (65-34), Dodgers 4-2 (49-48), Giants 1-4
(53-44), Diamondbacks 4-1 (34-62) Rockies 1-4 (41-56).
</P>
<P>
   _ Final interleague records: Dodgers 8-5, Giants 8-5, Padres
6-7, Diamondbacks 5-8, Rockies 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wildcard hunt: Giants lead league, Dodgers 4 games back.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big story: The Giants are falling out of the division
race, having lost seven of their last eight and are now 10 games
behind the Padres but still have the wildcard.
</P>
<P>
   _ The hot bats: Dodgers outfielder Gary Sheffield has reached
base in 30 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big arms: The Padres have two of the top four pitchers in
the league when it comes to ERA. Andy Ashby is third at 2.53 while
Kevin Brown is behind him at 2.59.
</P>
<P>
   _ The unexpected: The Padres are 24 games over .500, which they
have never been at any time in their previous 29 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ The injuries: Arizona placed third baseman Matt Williams on
the disabled list to prevent further damage to a stress fracture in
his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scoop: The Padres are 10-1 against the Reds this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
