<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brewers leave Atlanta on short end of stick as error-filled
series ends
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Milwaukee Brewers got out of town and after a
12-error series and Sunday's interminable 11-6 Atlanta victory,
leaving was a far safer thing to do. Andruw Jones crumpled a fender
running into the center field wall, Kerry Lightenberg's right hand
was nearly detached by a Fernando Vina liner and Dennis Martinez's
ERA continues to hemorrhage after another two-run outing.
</P>
<P>
   But in taking three of four from the Brewers, Atlanta will keep
two items from Sunday's three-hour, 10-minute sweatbath: John
Smoltz (8-2) won again and the far end of the bench made a mess
that the Brewers never did clean up. Second baseman Tony Graffanino
had his first 4-for-4 day in the majors (including a home run) and
Curtis Pride, starting in right for the slumping Michael Tucker,
scored four runs and hit a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   For a team whose bench is seen as a general weakness, the day
deserved some bunting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those guys need to be thrown in the lineup every once in a
while,'' said left fielder Ryan Klesko, ''especially when someone's
not swinging that good, whether it's myself or Tucker or Andruw.
Those guys need some at-bats. Plus, it's the challenge. You want to
try to do well for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride has. In two starts within the last five games, he scored
five times, driven in a pair and stolen a base. But Graffanino's
performance was more significant simply because he was hitting .203
at the All-Star break and had become little more than a lacking
understudy at Keith Lockhart. Making some critical adjustments at
the plate _ hands higher, stance closer to the plate and up further
in the box _ Graffanino is 8-for-13 since the break, bringing his
average to .240, its highest in a month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure, I'd like to play every day,'' Graffanino said, ''but
Keith is huge for this team, he's on base all the time and we need
him to do well too. But I feel I can do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Pride was crossing the plate at a pretty regular pace and
Graff had an outstanding day,'' said manager Bobby Cox. ''It makes
a great day when two guys who haven't played a whole bunch do that
well when they do get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz worked seven hard innings before yielding to the heat,
allowing seven hits while striking out six but yielding just two
earned runs, which dropped his ERA to 3.53. After 14 starts last
year, he was 6-5 and wondering what could go wrong next. Even after
two visits to the DL, this season may actually wind up being one of
his most successful. He won for the fourth time in six starts since
coming off the DL June 20.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to put together a solid year, under the
circumstances,'' he said. ''I think I can do that. It's been very
gratifying to this point but at the same time, I'm also aware
things could change real quick for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
