A2343 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENSMOKER-COURT-ART-     07-19 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENSMOKER-COURT-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA GIVES TEEN-AGE SMOKERS A DAY IN COURT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, Miss., Minn., Calif., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Judge Steven Shutter is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANTATION, Fla. _ Once a month for a couple of hours, Judge
Steven Shutter of Broward County clears his courtroom of lawyers
and defendants to make room for restless teen-agers and their
inconvenienced parents for what is known as Teen Smoking Court.
</P>
<P>
   The judge sometimes has to order quiet more than once, and
sometimes he even removes a few people to emphasize his point, but
the crowd recoils into silence on its own when Earl Mogk stands up
to talk about his larynx cancer, the product, he said, of 40 years
of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was your age, there was nobody out there to tell me
about the dangers of smoking,'' Mogk, 60, said at a recent court
session, talking through an electronic device he has used since his
larynx, or voice box, and vocal cords were surgically removed.
``The reason I'm here today is for a reality check.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers applauded, even though many said later they would
keep on smoking.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida's fight against teen-age smoking, Shutter's courtroom
in Plantation, a suburb just west of Fort Lauderdale, is a new
weapon that combines education, health warnings and parental
nagging with the weight of the law. The Teen Smoking Court is part
of a large-scale campaign against underage smoking that the state
is financing with $200 million of the $11.3 billion settlement it
reached with tobacco companies last year after suing to recover
Medicaid payments for smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is experimenting with advertising, school-based programs
and increased policing of both minors and retail outlets suspected
of selling cigarettes to those under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts are part of a two-year pilot program that includes
``truth ads'' for the printed and electronic press, which are
designed by teen-agers themselves. ``Attention movie industry,''
one advertisement that objects to smoking in films reads. ``We are
your best customers, so why are you trying to kill us?''
</P>
<P>
   Another effort consists of a ``truth train,'' scheduled to stage
rock concerts and beach parties in 10 cities around the state to
spread the anti-smoking message.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, an advocacy
group in Washington, said that states that had sued the tobacco
industry had emphasized the need to protect young people from
smoking and stop cigarette-makers from tailoring advertising
campaigns to entice them.
</P>
<P>
   A push on the national level to reduce teen-age smoking has
stalled with the failure of a $516 billion tobacco bill in the
Senate last month.
</P>
<P>
   But the other states that have reached settlements, Texas,
Mississippi and Minnesota, are all expected to use part of the
money for anti-smoking programs aimed at minors, officials said.
Thirty-seven states have suits pending against the tobacco
companies. Some states, like California and Massachusetts, have
their own public education efforts with money from increased excise
taxes on cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Myers, executive vice president and general counsel for
the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, said that Florida may help
design an effective model for other efforts to reduce smoking by
the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean that everything they're doing will work,''
Myers said. ``It means that we can learn a good deal from these
efforts and do even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Florida made it illegal for those under age 18 to
possess tobacco products. Since then, state agents and local police
have cited thousands of teen-agers for smoking and required them to
pay a fine or do community service. Their offense is an infraction
and does not involve any criminal charges, but repeat violators,
and uncooperative ones, face suspension of their driver's licenses
or a legal block to getting one.
</P>
<P>
   Other states, including Minnesota, North Carolina and Texas,
also punish underage smokers with suspension of driving privileges,
fines or community service. In Idaho, violators face up to six
months in a juvenile detention center. But Myers said Florida was
among the first to enlist the courts.
</P>
<P>
   That effort began here in Broward County Court in April when
Shutter went beyond just handling smoking citations to create the
state's first Teen Smoking Court. Other counties are setting up
their own systems and are expected to use the court here as a
model.
</P>
<P>
   Underage smokers given citations in Broward County must appear
in court with a parent, sit through an anti-smoking video or class
and listen to Mogk ``for dramatic effect,'' Shutter said. About 150
teen-agers appear in court each month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a crime,'' Shutter said jovially at a recent court
session with 175 ethnically diverse teen-agers. ``It's wrong, it's
stupid, it's dangerous, but it's not a crime. You ruin your health,
you ruin your life, but you don't care. So let's talk about the
legal consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the choice of a $53 fine, including court costs, or eight
hours of community service, like washing police cars, most
violators opted for community service. Those under age 16 were
required to watch a one-hour video that graphically depicted the
hazards of smoking while the older teen-agers signed up for a
four-hour class at the local chapter of the American Lung
Association that includes both videos and group discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Then the judge called out individual names for a brief
interaction at the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you what to do,'' Shutter said to one
smoker, Lisa Gottlieb, who turned 18 the day she appeared in court.
``You can make your own decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Ms. Gottlieb said she had no plans to quit her
pack-a-day habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' Ms. Gottlieb, a Plantation High School
graduate who started smoking at 14, said of the law-enforcement
effort. ``The bottom line is, kids are going to smoke. It's my body
and unless I have a desire to quit I'm not going to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
