 CHAMPIONSHIPS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
United States goes deep on Spain
<TEXT>
<P>
   All 15 players score in victory
</P>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL; 
MONTE CARLO, Monaco _ It wasn't exactly the running of the Bulls.
Or even the running of the Clippers or Mavericks, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   But when Spain's national team confronted the U.S. World
Championship of Basketball team Sunday, it was a considerably
better test than the Americans had received a day earlier against
France.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a moderately respected international competitor _
though not expected to be a medal contender this month in Athens,
Greece _ was waiting for the United States. And when Rudy
Tomjanovich's team was locked in a seven-point game at halftime of
its second exhibition, it represented another opportunity for a
growth spurt for the young Americans.
</P>
<P>
   They continued to sprout up the chart.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Sasser scored the first six points of the second half,
point guard Michael Hawkins provided valuable leadership and the
United States wore down Spain for a 95-78 victory at Stade Louis II
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The United States never trailed in the game, but it wasn't until
the second half that the Americans put away the more physical
Spaniards.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive part of the win was a different set
of heroes emerged than those who carried the heaviest weight a
night earlier against France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's going to be a trait of this team,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``We have good players, but the most important thing is that
we have the team concept. All the guys came out in the second half
and really got it going. Hopefully, one of the strengths of this
team is going to be our depth. On different nights, different guys
are going to get the job done for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasser finished with 15 points and Hawkins had 12. They were the
only Americans to score in double digits although all 15 of them
scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good learning experience for us,'' Tomjanovich said.
``I'm pleased with the way we came out in the second half and kept
our intensity up there. And, again, defense was a big key for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain was forced into nine turnovers in the first seven minutes,
when the United States rolled up an 18-8 lead. But when it wasn't
stealing the ball, it was fouling the person who had it.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, no more than a few seconds elapsed on the game
clock without a foul being whistled. The United States had 20 fouls
in the first half, when Spain went to the free-throw line 21 times.
If it could have hit more than 62 percent, Spain might have been
closer than 43-36 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the team from Spain was a lot more physical and we
got in foul trouble early because of it,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We
didn't make the adjustments to how the game was being called.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hawkins began to run the U.S. club smartly after halftime,
when he had three of his four assists and 10 of his points,
including two opportunistic 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think someone for us might have 15 or 20 points on one night
and then the next night, it'll be somebody else, maybe somebody off
the bench, doing that type of scoring,'' Hawkins said. ``In this
game, we kind of got a feel for the way the game was going in the
first half and coach Tomjanovich told us we had to pick it up going
into the second half, so that's what we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980719.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENSMOKER-COURT-ART-     07-19 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENSMOKER-COURT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PLANTATION, Fla.: I'm not going to.''. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other teen-agers interviewed after court said they had no plans
to quit, underscoring the difficulties in changing attitudes. Not
all could fully explain why they smoked, even when they disapproved
themselves. ``It's more of a social thing,'' one boy said. A girl
said, ``It's like biting your nails.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the court, in the parking lot, one teen-ager stole a
last smoke in the car, sitting with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, however, parents who smoked disapproved of their
child's smoking and were appreciative of the court.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the video with his 16-year-old daughter, Cary
Clark, 36, a superintendent at a church, said, ``I'm glad that
here's another piece of information that will help her at some
point say smoking isn't what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, about 35 percent of high school students smoke, a
rate that is similar to the national rate of 36 percent, state
officials said. But the urgency to reach teen-agers for prevention
efforts stems from studies that have also found that people who
have not started smoking by age 21 are unlikely to ever smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Most teen-agers in court were caught smoking near their schools
by undercover agents from the Division of Alcoholic Beverages and
Tobacco within the Florida Department of Business and Professional
Regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Deployed against both underage smokers and the retailers who
sell cigarettes to them illegally, the agents and other local
law-enforcement agencies issued about 2,800 citations to minors
from October 1997 to May 1998. They issued 136 citations to
retailers from July 1997 to May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But some officials do not see the point in punishing smokers.
``It's kind of absurd to hold the kids accountable in that way,''
said Jon Lloyd, a health program specialist with the California
Department of Health Services, whose smoking programs focused on
restricting ``vectors of the disease,'' like advertisers and
retailers. ``We feel it kind of takes attention away from the real
perpetrators of this addiction. That is the tobacco companies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Florida officials say they are aiming at an integrated
effort. ``You have to do everything,'' said Chuck Wolfe, director
of Florida's program. ``You can't just pick one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all pieces of the program, the Teen Smoking Court will be
evaluated. Shutter, 54, said that realistically, he would deem the
court successful if it got 20 percent to 25 percent of the
teen-agers cited to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be some of them who will intellectualize it and say,
`Yes, I don't want this to happen,''' the judge said. ``That isn't
the run-of-the-mill teen-ager.'' But, he added, ``If I get 30 kids
out of this, was that worth half a day? I think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
