u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-DEBATES-FINANCE     07-19 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-DEBATES-FINANCE-915(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS' DEBATE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Texas, Calif., Wis.)  (lb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Call it the capital's rendition of ``Eine Kleine
Nachtmusik,'' the sometimes discordant strains of the
campaign-finance debate relegated to the post-prime-time evening
hours of the House's summer agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors galleries are nearly empty of curious tourists. The
reporters and television crews that cram the Capitol in daylight
have all but disappeared. But like night-wandering vampires, a
small tag team of lawmakers take the floor for a debate that often
does come close to drawing blood.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the daytime votes that the Republican leadership
wants to showcase have been cast, long after news deadlines have
passed, some of the truths of modern politics are told.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Socratic dialogue seeking to define a ``shakedown.'' It
began when Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., seeking limits on money
in politics, clashed with Rep. Tom DeLay, the House majority whip,
over the lessons of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations that huge cash donations were made to the Nixon
White House in satchels and manila envelopes led Congress in 1974
to enact the last sweeping overhaul of the campaign-finance law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the corporations that were being
shaken down by the Nixon administration are telling me now that
they are being shaken down by both political parties in soft
money,'' Shays said. ``Soft money'' is the term for the unlimited,
unregulated donations to political parties that would effectively
be banned by bipartisan legislation sponsored by Shays and Rep.
Martin Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, of Texas, who has sometimes argued himself hoarse in his
fight against Shays' legislation, promptly asked for a definition
of ``shakedown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakedown,'' Shays responded, ``is when leaders from both
parties will call up a corporation president and say, `We would
like $100,000 or $200,000 or $300,000 or half a million,' and make
it very clear to those leaders that they can expect no action on
their legislation unless they get it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Would the gentleman like to name the members that do it?''
asked DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, usually mild-mannered to a fault, warned
uncharacteristically, ``Do not even wonder for a minute about
whether I will be able to document that information.''
</P>
<P>
   So it has gone, once a week, maybe twice a week since late May.
The next roundelay is scheduled for Monday after the sun goes down.
The debate has become an evening marathon dance, an endurance test.
And that is just as it was intended to be.
</P>
<P>
   With most Republicans fiercely opposed to changing a
campaign-finance system that favors incumbents, Speaker Newt
Gingrich first tried to scuttle the overhaul in March by having a
debate but never allowing the Shays-Meehan bill to come to
consideration on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   When that tactic backfired politically, Gingrich shifted gears
to allow a full and fair debate _ so full that 11 separate
proposals are up for consideration along with scores of amendments.
If more than one proposal draws a majority, then the one with the
most votes is the one presented to the House for a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Republicans showed some mercy by striking an
agreement with Democrats that whittled down proposed amendments to
the Shays-Meehan bill to 55. But that is still a formidable
obstacle course when many of the amendments are designed to water
down the bill or push away supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of time has also allowed lobbying against the bill
to intensify. An array of 53 organizations _ including the
Christian Coalition, the National Right to Life Committee and the
Southern Baptist Convention _ are fighting the measure in large
part because it would restrict the use of television and radio
commercials by independent groups in periods close to an election.
</P>
<P>
   In this debate, certain questions return like a coda. Night
after night, Republicans insist that campaign spending is free
speech, protected by the First Amendment, and challenge the notion
that money raising sullies Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is too much money?'' Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., asked
Rep. Ron Kind, D-Wis. ``Too much money compared to what? What kind
of money is appropriate? How much money is too much in politics?''
</P>
<P>
   Kind replied: ``The average person in western Wisconsin believes
that under the current finance system, even though it is legal for
a wealthy individual or group to contribute a million dollars to
either political party, that is too much money. That is
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay often seems to have snack food on his mind as he doggedly
refutes such notions. When asked about the $2.8 billion spent by
the political parties in the last presidential campaign year, DeLay
said ``That is less than the American people spend on potato
chips.''
</P>
<P>
   On another night he toted up the $218 million spent on House
races in 1996. ``That breaks down to about $3.80 per voter who
voted in the election _ $3.80,'' he said. ``That is less money than
we spent on bubble gum in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Meehan asked Doolittle if he was ``not in favor of
any limits at all?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is correct,'' Doolittle answered. ``No limits.'' In fact,
Doolittle is sponsoring his own campaign-finance proposal that
would eliminate the current limits on how much individuals and
political action committees may contribute to candidates. He would
require in their place electronic disclosure of contributions, with
reports filed every 24 hours in the last three months before an
election.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The long nights do give many Republicans one opportunity they
relish _ that of highlighting some of President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore's campaign-finance practices of 1996, which
spurred investigations by the Justice Department and in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first ran in 1992 on a platform that included an
overhaul of the campaign laws. But his re-election campaign was
criticized as the very symbol of fund-raising excess as the
president courted big donors with White House coffees and
sleep-overs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a recent breakfast with reporters if he wanted the
president to use his bully pulpit to help propel the issue forward,
Meehan demurred. ``If he comes out and makes a statement, the
Republicans, they all take to the floor with their photographs,''
Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, DeLay stood last week next to a blow-up poster of
Gore at a Buddhist temple in Los Angeles. Democrats later termed
the event inappropriate because of the temple's tax-exempt status,
and the party returned the donations.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay lambasted the Democratic National Committee for taking
illegal foreign donations in 1996. The party returned the money
after it became an issue in the final days of the 1996 campaign.
Several party fund-raisers have since been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said: ``If you have a friend by the name of Arief and
Soraya, and I cannot even pronounce the last name _ Wiriadinata,
something like that _ who donated $450,000 to the DNC and was
friends with a guy named Johnny Huang, and later returned it
because Wiriadinata could not explain where it came from, then
probably there is a high probability that it's money from foreign
nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing names that emerged in congressional hearings, DeLay said,
``I could go on with John Lee and Cheong Am, Yogesh Gandhi, Ng Lap
Seng, Supreme Master Suma Ching Hai and George Psaltis.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays intervened. ``I know the gentleman did not mean it to
sound this way, but when I listened to it, it sounded this way,''
he said. ``It sounded like if you have a foreign name, there was a
high probability they were foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   After some give and take, DeLay said, ``No, I am not saying
that.'' He followed up with a written statement the next day
saying, ``In no way did I mean to suggest that Asian-Americans
should not participate in our democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
