<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA WINS PLAYOFF AND THE BRITISH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (Eds: See also GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-SCENE) 
(mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Moments after Mark O'Meara captured a
thrilling and memorable British Open on Sunday, his wife, Alicia,
was asked why her husband is having his best year at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's your time, it's your time,'' said Alicia. ``He's a
late bloomer, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   What a way to blossom. Prevailing over a courageous Brian Watts,
a charging Tiger Woods and winning his second major championship of
the year, O'Meara bested Watts in a four-hole playoff by two
strokes, providing a terrific climax to a demanding four-day test
of golf at the Royal Birkdale Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara and Watts, who made a spectacular bunker shot on the
72nd regulation hole to save par and force the playoff, finished
tied after 72 holes at even-par 280. Woods, who shot a
four-under-par 66 Sunday and birdied three of the last four holes,
finished just one stroke out of the playoff and settled for third
place.
</P>
<P>
   Once the playoff began, O'Meara was at his steady best, adding
another major championship to his victory at the Masters in April.
Hitting every fairway in the playoff, which started at the 15th
hole, O'Meara birdied the first playoff hole to take a one-stroke
lead, then clinched the title on the 18th hole, where he made a
three-foot putt for par, after Watts had already bogeyed. As his
final putt settled in the cup, O'Meara raised his arms in triumph
as thunderous applause came from the grandstands and thousands of
fans who had surrounded Royal Birkdale's 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, in his 18th year on the PGA Tour, had reached the
pinnacle of his career. And while he savored the moment, even
O'Meara had difficulty absorbing the magnitude of winning two
majors within five months, after waiting his whole career before
this year to win his first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could put my finger on it, I would have done it
earlier,'' said O'Meara, who shot a two-under-par 68 in regulation
Sunday, while Watts shot a 70. ``It's incredibly gratifying to know
my name is on this trophy. If you look at the names of the players
that have won the Open championship, and the golf courses they've
won on, it's a tremendous honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf ball sitting on the ground doesn't know how old you
are. It doesn't know if you're 41, 50, or 22. Granted, I don't hit
it as long as some of the young players, but once in awhile I wield
a pretty wicked putter. And I make some pretty good putts at some
important times.''
</P>
<P>
   By winning, O'Meara:
</P>
<P>
   _ Became the oldest player ever to win two majors in the same
year. Both Jack Nicklaus (1980) and Ben Hogan (1953) won two majors
in the same year at the age of 40.
</P>
<P>
   _ Became the first man to win two majors in the same year since
1994, when Nick Price won the British Open and the PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Became the first man to win the Masters and the British Open
in the same year since Nick Faldo in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   _ Became the first American to win two majors in the same year
since 1982, when Tom Watson won the U.S. Open and the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   At next month's PGA Championship at Sahalee Golf Club in
Redmond, Wash., O'Meara will have a chance to become the first man
to win three majors in the same year since 1953, when Ben Hogan won
the Masters, the U.S. Open and the British Open.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But despite his achievements, O'Meara refused to call himself a
great golfer. ``Great players are Jack Nicklaus, Byron Nelson, Ben
Hogan, Sam Snead, Arnold Palmer, you can go down the list,'' said
O'Meara. ``I consider myself a consistent player, a player that
tries to do the best I can at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, O'Meara's best was just good enough, as other players
were more spectacular, yet fell short. It was a difficult defeat
for Watts, a 32-year-old American who started the day holding a
two-stroke lead and fell just short of an improbable victory.
Having played primarily on the Japanese tour since 1993, Watts
started the tournament as a long shot, and almost ended it as the
champion. But he missed a costly 4-footer for par on the first
playoff hole, and O'Meara never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if you had told me I would have been in a playoff
at the beginning of the week, I wouldn't have believed you,'' said
Watts, who lives in Edmond, Okla. ``I'm disappointed that I didn't
win, because I had the opportunity. But I'm still proud.''
</P>
<P>
   And Watts will be particularly proud of his brilliant bunker
shot at No. 18, which led to the playoff with O'Meara, who had
already finished his regulation round, and was watching from behind
the 18th green with his wife and two children. When Watts pulled
his second shot at No. 18 into the left-side bunker about 45 feet
from the pin, he was in serious danger of making a bogey that would
have given the title to O'Meara right there.
</P>
<P>
   But with one foot in the bunker, and one foot out, Watts lofted
a soft shot that floated out of the sand, landed on a slope near
the green, then trickled toward the hole and stopped less than two
feet away. The crowd roared, and O'Meara applauded in appreciation,
and when Watts tapped in for par, the playoff was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as good a shot as I've seen, with that kind of
pressure on,'' said O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to create something and visualize a good shot,
and it came off almost perfect,'' said Watts.
</P>
<P>
   The entire day provided memorable moments, as the wind calmed
for the first time all week, and seven players competed on the back
nine with a chance to win. Four players finished tied for fourth
place at 282: Jim Furyk, Jesper Parnevik, Raymond Russell and
Justin Rose, a 17-year-old amateur from England who was the darling
of the crowd and shot a 69 Sunday. But O'Meara left with the claret
jug, the trophy given to the British Open champion for a year.
Playing one group ahead of Watts in regulation, O'Meara took the
lead for the first time when he birdied No. 14, moving to even par,
one stroke ahead of Watts and Furyk.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, meanwhile, was several holes ahead, making his own run.
Standing at four over par as he reached the 15th hole, Woods made a
20-foot putt for birdie at No. 15. Then after making par at No. 16,
Woods made a spectacular birdie at No. 17 by chipping in from 30
feet, then capped his charge by making a 30-foot birdie putt at 18.
</P>
<P>
   Now Woods had to wait. O'Meara made a bogey at No. 16 to fall
into a three-way tie for first place with Watts and Woods at one
over par. But O'Meara made a crucial birdie at No. 17, hitting a
9-iron to within 15 feet, then making the pressure putt to go one
stroke ahead of Watts and Woods. Watts answered with a birdie at
No. 17, making an 18-foot putt to tie O'Meara at even par.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Meara made par at No. 18, Woods could not win. Then Watts
made his phenomenal bunker shot at No. 18, but O'Meara was not
fazed. After all, this has been O'Meara's year, and he knew where
he would put his latest trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will go in my trophy cabinet at home,'' said O'Meara.
``I've got a nice spot for it, right next to the Masters
championship trophy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
