<HEADER>
A2355 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANSION-SALE-TEX     07-19 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANSION-SALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DISHWASHER PLANS AUCTION FOR HIS SOUTH TEXAS SHOWPLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARNES CITY, Texas _ The Veladi Ranch mansion rises like a
lord's castle on these South Texas plains. But the lord has moved
out, and his impressive 30,000-square-foot estate is going on the
auction block Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-story, 34-room mansion will go to the highest bidder. It
will be an absolute auction, meaning that the house, the 240 acres,
the spacious sale barn and auction arena will all be sold
regardless of the price.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no haggling, no offers and counteroffers, no tea
for the local Realtors, no sign in the yard. When the gavel drops,
the sale is done. Bidders must have a $100,000 cashier's check to
qualify. They must be prepared to plop down 10 percent of the
purchase price and will have 30 days to close.
</P>
<P>
   It's clean, quick and simple.
</P>
<P>
   It can also be risky for the seller if the bids are low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there is probably some gamble to it,'' said William
Bone, president of the National Auction Group, the Alabama-based
company handling the sale. ``But people who own mansions like that
like a gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Bone said Arturo Torres, the owner of Veladi Ranch, was told he
could sell his property on a nonabsolute basis, meaning he could
withdraw the property from the sale if the bids were too low, but
he declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't be any fun,'' Bone said.
</P>
<P>
   Torres' Veladi Ranch appears almost out of time and place on the
relatively flat and open range southeast of San Antonio. It is an
antebellum-style home, with massive verandas surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   The main level has a foyer with marble floors and a
``double-flying'' staircase that flanks the 60-foot atrium and huge
crystal chandelier. The first level, or ground level, sports a
disco with deco bar and dance floor, a game area and a ballet room.
</P>
<P>
   Studies, parlors, baths and bedrooms fill the top two floors.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch's 240 acres are immaculately groomed; the entire
acreage is irrigated. There are a 10-acre spring-fed lake, clay
tennis courts, a mammoth swimming pool, stables, kennels, an exotic
bird aviary, a manager's home and a staff dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fancy place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ultimate Texas showplace ranch,'' Bone said.
``It's got to have cost him $15 million to build. He wanted to live
in it, but he couldn't get his family to settle there, so he
decided he was going to sell it, no matter what it brings. He
thought an auction just looked like fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres, a Cuban immigrant, came to the United States after the
Bay of Pigs invasion in the early 1960s. He landed in Miami and
with the help of a church organization made his way to Amarillo,
where he worked for a hardware company during the day and a
drive-in theater at night. He eventually took a $1.25-an-hour job
as a dishwasher at a Pizza Hut.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years later, he had a franchise in Del Rio, and
eventually he came to own nearly 250 Pizza Huts and Taco Bells. In
1991, he sold out to PepsiCo for $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   He owns Play-By-Play Toys &AMP; Novelties, a worldwide
multimillion-dollar company that manufactures stuffed toys. He
opened a chain of Veladi Ranch Steak Houses and intended to raise
certified Hereford beef at his ranch to supply the restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Gilda Cisneros, Torres' personal executive assistant, said those
plans faded when Torres, 61, suffered a stroke in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``He decided he wanted to simplify his life,'' she said. ``He
has closed most of his restaurants and is selling off the ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Veladi Ranch, she explained, is named for Torres' three
daughters, using the first two letters of each name _ Ve for
Veronica, La for Laura, and Di for Diane.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Witherspoon, a representative for the National Auction
Group, said the ranch has generated quite a bit of interest in the
Texas market. The company took control of the property after the
July Fourth holiday, and within the first week nearly 50
prospective buyers had toured the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had calls for more than 1,000 brochures,'' he said. ``We
sent out 10,000 to 15,000 brochures prior to that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the national advertising that makes these auctions
appealing, Witherspoon said. Ads are placed in all the essential
national magazines and newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Auction Group has handled the sale of the Lloyd
Bentsen ranch in McAllen, the Squaw Mountain ranch in Jacksboro,
and the CF Ranch in Aledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has been our bread and butter for the last 10 years,''
Bone said. ``The absolute auction sales started in Texas, and they
are catching on around the country. Texas is really a wonderful
place, where they literally still have a frontier mentality. People
in Texas don't mind taking a chance. They personify the
entrepreneurial spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres, Bone said, isn't worried about the sale outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more excited about what kind of food is going to be
served, what band is playing. He is bringing in friends from Puerto
Rico, Mexico and Miami. He has never expressed any concern over the
money it's going to bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a big going-away party for him. It could
be a chance for someone to get a bargain. We're just going to throw
it open and see what happens. We'll keep going until we have a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres and his family have moved to San Antonio. Bone said he
expects the new ranch owners to be from either the Fort
Worth/Dallas area or Houston. It will probably be a weekend home,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Registration for the auction begins at 1 p.m. Monday. The
auction is at 4. Information is available from the National Auction
Group by calling (800) 473-2292.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
