<HEADLINE>
U.S. HOOPSTERS STUNNED BY PUERTO RICO, 84-76 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also GYM-GOODWILL-GAMES, RUN-GOODWILL-GAMES) 
(mk) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Already wearing their road uniforms, the U.S.
basketball players felt even less at home Sunday with many of the
8,617 fans at Madison Square Garden waving Puerto Rican flags and
filling the arena with pro-Puerto Rican chants. After losing their
Goodwill Games duel, they felt even worse.
</P>
<P>
   After a torrid first half by U.S. forward Elton Brand, Puerto
Rico figured him out just in time. Brand scored 16 first-half
points, but only eight in the second half, and Puerto Rico rallied
from a 19-point second-half deficit to stun the Americans, 84-76.
It was the first game of the competition for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the comeback was guard Eddie Casiano, who scored 26 of
his game-high 31 points in the second half. It was his two free
throws with 6 minutes 11 seconds left that tied the score at 69-69.
A 3-pointer by forward Javier Colon gave Puerto Rico a lead it
never relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   Brand's inside play helped offset the crowd early on. His
emphatic dunk gave the United States a 31-19 lead before he topped
his seven-of-nine first-half shooting with a 15-foot baseline
jumper and a tip-in to stake the Americans to a 42-30 halftime
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have a lot of experience, and they have a lot of
moves in the post that are very hard to defend,'' Brand, a standout
as a freshman last season at Duke University, said of playing
international competition. ``This is a greater level than what I'm
used to in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico was unable to capitalize on its chances in the first
half, shooting 18 free throws, 10 more than the United States shot,
but missing seven of them. It was worse from the floor. Puerto Rico
shot eight of 26 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Puerto Rico was just warming up. The U.S. lead was
55-36 before Puerto Rico made a furious run, outscoring the
Americans by 48-21 over the final 15:07. Puerto Rico never led
until Colon's 3-pointer with 5:42 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt very at home with the crowd of many Puerto Ricans,''
said center Jose Ortiz of Puerto Rico, a former member of the Utah
Jazz, who finished with 17 points and 10 rebounds. ``Usually when
you have the home-court advantage, it plays a great part in one's
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   In the preceding game, guard Shane Heal scored 18 points to lead
Australia to an 84-72 victory over Argentina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
