<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR SEEKS TO KNOW WHEN PRESIDENT'S LAWYERS VISITED WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Whitewater independent counsel has subpoenaed
records of White House visits made by President Clinton's private
lawyers, David Kendall and Robert Bennett, a television news
program reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas, first reported Sunday on the CBS News program
``Face the Nation,'' could provide the independent counsel, Kenneth
Starr, with logs or dates that would allow him to explore whether
other White House aides had attended meetings between the president
and his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   If the sessions included other members of the White House staff,
Starr might be able to argue that those aides were not covered by
lawyer-client privilege and could be called to testify, legal
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the White House nor Starr's office would comment on
whether subpoenas had been issued. Starr's spokesman, Charles G.
Bakaly III, said, ``It has never been our intention to pierce the
president's attorney-client privilege with his personal lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, called on Sunday for
Clinton to testify about whether he had a sexual relationship with
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern, and lied about it.
Clinton has denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, truth will set you free,'' Lott, R-Miss., said on ``Fox
News Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he did not understand why the administration had tried
to shield the Secret Service agents from being questioned about the
man they are sworn to protect. ``They appear to be hiding
something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a White House spokesman, said, ``It's regrettable
that the majority leader appears to question the integrity of
people who put their lives on the line every day.'' Kennedy said he
would not confirm or deny that Starr has sought records on visits
to the White House by Kendall and Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Clinton's bodyguards testified to a grand jury here
on Friday after the administration lost an emergency bid to the
Supreme Court to keep the agents off the witness stand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2042EDT &QL; 
