<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS AND PALESTINIANS AGREE TO MEET AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Senior Israeli and Palestinian officials sat down
face-to-face on Sunday for the first time in months, but they
apparently agreed only to talk some more.
</P>
<P>
   After half a year without any contacts and with the entire peace
effort begun in Oslo, Norway, tottering on the edge of collapse.
the meeting between Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Mahmoud
Abbas, a senior Palestinian negotiator better known as Abu Mazen,
took on an air of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was preceded by what Israeli police described as an
abortive car-bombing attempt in the center of Jerusalem. A van
driven by a Palestinian and packed with flammable liquids, gas
canisters and nails caught fire at a major intersection, but did
not explode. No one was injured except the driver, identified as
Jalal Roumaneh, who was severely burned.
</P>
<P>
   He was described as a 30-year-old father of three from a
Palestinian refugee camp in Ramallah, who had been arrested eight
years earlier and spent 20 months in prison as a member of Hamas,
the militant Islamic organization.
</P>
<P>
   The episode seemed to reduce expectations further from the
high-level meeting, which was held in a Tel Aviv hotel. It lasted
three hours, part of it only between Mordechai and Abbas, and part
of it with other negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, both Mordechai and Abbas issued noncommittal
statements, stressing only that they would meet again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to focus in coming days on the central issues and
to look for solutions to bridge the gap, with the aim of advancing
the agreement between the two sides,'' Mordechai said.
</P>
<P>
   And Abbas said: ``We discussed all outstanding issues. We agreed
to continue to follow up and listen to the ideas, hoping that such
an endeavor will bridge the gap between the two sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was reportedly sought by the Clinton administration,
which, after months of intensive effort, has all but despaired of
wresting from Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu the decisions
needed to revive the moribund negotiating process. The Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, has essentially agreed to the U.S.
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. proposals are centered on an Israeli withdrawal from a
further 13 percent of the West Bank and Palestinian adherence to
specific security requirements. The dispute is currently said to be
around Netanyahu's requirement that 3 percent of that 13 be given a
new status, with Israel retaining a veto over any Palestinian
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has also demanded that Arafat convene the full
parliament of the Palestine Liberation Organization to draft a new
charter explicitly excluding demands for Israel's destruction, and
that the Palestinian Authority agree to turn over terror suspects
wanted by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   There was every indication that both Netanyahu and Arafat
accepted the talks reluctantly, and there was considerable
speculation about whether either gave his representative any leeway
to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   At a news briefing Sunday, Netanyahu insisted that Mordechai had
a ``full mandate.'' He also said he was willing to open
round-the-clock talks, presumably with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat made no comment. But he has insisted that all he wants to
hear is a ``yes'' or a ``no'' from Israel to the U.S. proposals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hanan Ashrawi, a Palestinian Authority minister who was not
present at the talks, dismissed them as a futile exercise. ``I
never expected much from this meeting,'' she said. ``It is clear
that this Israeli government is not interested in progress in the
peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   With contacts already so strained, both Israel and the
Palestinians seemed to take pains to play down the attempted terror
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see with today's car bomb attempt in Jerusalem why we
are so concerned and preoccupied with having the Palestinians live
up to their obligations to fight terrorism,'' Netanyahu said. But
he added, ``I do not lay responsibility on anyone right now,
because we are checking the incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Shaath, the Palestinian minister of planning, said, ``What
happened today is something we condemn, something we are doing our
best to prevent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
