<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-GOODWILL-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GYMNAST MOCEANU IS OUT TO PROVE HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (Eds: See also RUN-GOODWILL-GAMES, BKO-GOODWILL-GAMES) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ At 10, Dominique Moceanu was the youngest
gymnast ever to make the U.S. junior national team. At 13, she was
the youngest to win the U.S. senior championship. And at 14, when
she was part of the U.S. gold-medal team in the Atlanta Olympics,
she became the youngest athlete ever on a Wheaties box.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, when Goodwill Games gymnastics began before a
slim crowd at the Nassau Coliseum, an older, taller and wiser
Dominique Moceanu took part. She was one of 11 women from seven
nations in the women's all-around. They included Svetlana Khorkina,
the 19-year-old Russian who won the 1996 Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   First, that matter of Moceanu's size. At the Olympics, in a
sport in which smaller is better because the small gymnast can
tumble more quickly, Moceanu was the smallest of the small. The
American-born child of former Romanian gymnasts was 4 feet 5 inches
and weighed maybe 75 pounds after a good meal. In the last 18
months, she has sprouted to 5 feet and 95 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Quick growth like that has ruined careers in such sports as
gymnastics and figure skating because it changes the center of
gravity and thus affects balance. Moceanu survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of problems,'' she said. ``I hurt my knees and my
back. I had trouble getting used to the whole thing. My balance was
a little different, and I had to get used to that. I'm fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   She also seems happy. She trains in Houston with Luminita
Miscenco, a coach from Romania. Next month, she will start her
senior year in high school. And at 16, she is philosophical beyond
her years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics were the biggest thing in my life,'' she said.
``I had a couple of mess-ups there, but I learned from my mistakes.
That's what life teaches you. I think I've matured a lot over the
past year. I'm learning a lot about life. I take things as they
come. I can't look too far ahead. I can't look to my next goal
until I pass this one first.''
</P>
<P>
   Her goal here was a medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked hard the last six months,'' she said. ``People
don't know how much I've put into it. I have a lot I want to prove.
I've improved a lot of things. I'm doing drills I never did before
in my life. I'm working on a new vault, a new bar connection, a new
dismount from the bars, a triple twist on the floor. It's a big
progression for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Olympics, I could have given up and quit. And people
consider me not that good anymore because I haven't done anything
extraordinary since 1996. Like everybody, I had a little downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get to the top, it's harder to stay there,'' Moceanu
continued, ``and when you fall from the top it's harder to come
back. Everybody has their obstacles. You've just got to get up
every day and prove you belong there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu is still a darling of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've made an impact on a lot of people,'' she said.
``People keep sending me good-luck notes on the Internet. It makes
you feel good that people out there are still rooting for you. It's
neat to make an impact on other people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight-day gymnastics schedule consists of an all-around and
six apparatus events for men, an all-around and four apparatus
events for women, a mixed competition and a final-night exhibition.
There is no team competition. Kendall Beck of San Antonio,
scheduled to compete on the balance beam, withdrew after injuring
her right knee during training in Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
