<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH OPEN ALSO-RANS FEEL THE PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also GLF-BRITISH-OPEN) 
(mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ A handful of golfers left Sunday's British
Open dealing with deep disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, who finished one stroke out of a playoff in third
place, might have won if he had putted better. On Saturday, Woods
missed six putts from 8 feet or less. But he tried to look at the
positive side of his best showing at a major this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could beat yourself up forever,'' said Woods, who had
shared the first-round lead with a 65. ``You have to look at the
positive, the fact I started good, finished good, and I hit a lot
of good shots this week. Most importantly, I came back today and
birdied three of the last four holes to give myself a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk, who finished tied for fourth place at 2 over par
(282), did not try to hide his dejection. In the last six majors,
Furyk has five top-six finishes without a victory. And since the
start of 1997, Furyk has 22 top-10 finishes, more than anyone in
the world, but he has not won since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Furyk barely missed putts at Nos. 15, 16 and 17 that
denied him a potential victory. ``The putts at 15 and 16, I
couldn't have hit an inch better,'' he said. ``I thought I had made
them both, and I lipped them both out. There is nothing you can do
about that. I played well today. I guarantee I played as well as
anyone, and I feel like the worst I should have been was even par
for the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik, who also finished tied for fourth, had to deal
with his third close call at the British Open. Parnevik finished
second in 1994 and tied for second last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to win this event once, but it seems
impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Turning Pro
</P>
<P>
   Justin Rose, the 17-year-old amateur from England who tied for
fourth, confirmed that he would turn professional this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole week has been really special for me,'' said Rose,
who will play in the Dutch Open next weekend. ``I was put at ease
by the crowd, the incredible support.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood Battle
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara and Tiger Woods are close friends and neighbors
near Orlando, Fla., and winning another major gave O'Meara a chance
to tease Woods. O'Meara said he would let Woods sip from the claret
jug, the trophy given to the British Open winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tiger wants a sip, he's more than welcome, because I
imagine his name will be on this trophy someday, too,'' O'Meara
said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he wanted strokes from O'Meara the next time they
play. ``No shots for Tiger,'' O'Meara said. ``Not when he hits it
60 by me on every hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods used O'Meara's backup putter this week. ``I finished
first, he finished one shot off,'' O'Meara said. ``That's why it's
the backup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
