<HEADLINE>
SATURN WORKERS VOTE TO AUTHORIZE STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Tenn.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Workers at General Motors Corp.'s giant Saturn
factory, which was once a model of cooperation between labor and
management, voted overwhelmingly Sunday to authorize their leaders
to call a strike to protest GM's moves this spring to buy more auto
parts from outside suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The strike authorization, which carried with 95 percent of the
vote, was the latest sign of the worker dissatisfaction that has
swept the world's largest automaker since workers went on strike at
two parts factories here seven weeks ago. The Saturn factory in
Spring Hill, Tenn., is the only GM assembly plant in the United
States still producing vehicles; other factories have been forced
to close for lack of parts.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's strike vote, the first in Saturn's 12 years of
operations, authorizes leaders of the United Auto Workers union to
call a strike, but it does not require them to do so. Joseph
Rypkowski, the local union president, said talks would soon be held
with GM officials. Company officials had no immediate reaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
