<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISH-LEDE20-COX     07-19 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-LEDE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Meara major general
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Yes, Mark O'Meara can win a major. After
Sunday, that bears repeating.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara can win another major.
</P>
<P>
   In less than four months, O'Meara has gone from someone who
couldn't win a major to joining an exclusive group that includes
the likes of Nicklaus, Watson, Trevino, Player, Palmer, Hogan and
Snead.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara's two-shot playoff victory over Brian Watts in the 127th
British Open at Royal Birkdale, after they both finished at
even-par 280, enabled O'Meara to become just the 12th player since
the birth of the Masters in 1934 to win two majors in the same
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't put myself in their class,'' O'Meara said.
``They're great players who have won a lot of great championships
and have been incredible am- bassadors for the game. Me, I consider
myself a consistent player who more times than not can finish the
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, who took 57 tries in majors before he finally broke
through at this year's Masters, just happened to be a late bloomer.
At 41, he's the oldest player to achieve a double-major year.
</P>
<P>
   And, with apologies to Augusta National, he says the Auld Claret
Jug he'll be taking to his Orlando home today after his 16th career
PGA Tour victory means more than the green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incredibly gratifying to know my name is on this trophy
right here,'' he said. ``I want to savor this victory more than
what happened at Augusta National, because this tournament is all
about the history of the game. Links courses are where golf
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his victory in the Masters, when he didn't lead alone until
he birdied the final hole, O'Meara's British tri- umph wasn't
assured until late in the proceedings. And no less than seven
players had a chance at winning, in- cluding Tiger Woods (66_ 281,
whose two closing bird- ies left him a shot back.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara took advantage of calmer conditions Sunday to shoot a
two-under 68 and make up a two-shot deficit to Watts. He then had
to wait to see if Watts could save par from a downhill lie in a
green-H side bunker on the 18th. After Watts almost holed the shot,
they headed for the British Open's first fourhole playoff since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   For Watts, an American who has won 11 tournaments in Japan after
he lost his Tour card in 1992, just making it to the playoff could
have been considered a victory. The runner-up share of $329,000
would enable him to get his Tour card for 1999 and finally return
to America, where his wife and infant son live.
</P>
<P>
   But Watts, who won the 1987 NCAA individual championship for
national champion Oklahoma State, said he wasn't worrying about
coming home as he headed to the 15th tee for the start of the
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about any doors being opened for me,'' Watts
said. ``I was just thinking about trying to win the British Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts quickly fell behind when O'Meara birdied No. 15 and Watts'
3-foot birdie attempt lipped out. After the players both parred the
next two holes, Watts' chance of winning the Open and earning an
immediate Tour card ended when his approach at the 18th landed in
another green-H side bunker.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Meara on the green, Watts tried to make his sand shot,
but knocked it 30 feet past the cup. He two- putted for bogey, then
L watched O'Meara two-putt for par for an anticlimatic finish to a
hectic four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite proud of myself to be here, but I'm disappointed I
didn't win because I had the opportunity,'' said Watts, who will
improve on his No. 35 spot on the world ranking. ``I don't know
what this will do for my career. Hopefully, I moved up a little
notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as much as O'Meara, however. He now has won as many majors
as Greg Norman and Johnny Miller.
</P>
<P>
   After O'Meara's Masters victory, he had to endure accusations
from Sweden's L Jarmo Sandelin that O'Meara had cheated when he won
last fall's Lancome Trophy because he marked a ball incorrectly.
Now, O'Meara has made his mark in golf in a much better way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody used to write that Mark couldn't win a major,'' said
his caddy, Jerry Higginbotham. ``Now he's won two, so everybody
should shut up, and that includes Jarmo Sandelin. Jarmo Sandelin
couldn't carry Mark's bag.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara says he's content to stay on a plateau of players behind
the superstars. But what if he wins next month's PGA Championship
at Sahalee to join Ben Hogan as the only players to win three
professional majors in a year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that, but if you guys want to think that,
that's great,'' O'Meara said. ``I really don't know why I've been
able to take my game to the next level at my age. I just try to not
put much pressure on myself. And like I've said, the golf ball
doesn't know how old you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
