<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-NOTEBOOK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three-putts haunt Woods
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Tiger Woods came up one birdie short
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Woods chipped in for birdie on the 17th hole and rolled in a
30-foot birdie putt on 18 to move into a temporary first-place tie,
celebrating each shot with his familiar pumping fist. But his
four-under 66 eventually left him one shot out of the British Open
playoff at Royal Birkdale, won by Mark O'Meara over Brian Watts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm very happy with the 66, but going out I knew
that probably even par was going to be the number and I just didn't
do it,'' said Woods, who finished at one-over 281.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who led this tournament after an opening 65, could look
back on his three-putt bogey at the first hole, a missed 4-foot
birdie try at the 10th or the 77 he shot Saturday as reasons why he
didn't win his second major. But Woods said he won't play those
mind games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could do that and beat yourself up forever,'' he said.
``You could play `What if?' in every tournament. You have to look
at the positive: I started out good and I finished with three
birdies in the last four holes to give myself a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other positives Woods could take with him on his
private plane back to the United States: This was his best finish
in a major (and just his second top-10) since his record-setting
Masters victory last year; and his practice rounds with buddy
O'Meara soon might become more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need more shots,'' Woods said, smiling. ``I can't wait until
we get home and play.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a mixed weekend for Woods, who was heckled by some fans
and saw his mother sprain an ankle Saturday while walking the
course. But he has come a long way from the kid who once said
winning was his lone desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finishing third is not something you should be upset about,''
Woods said. ``I was one shot out of the playoff. That's been the
story of my year. I've been right there, but I haven't been able to
get a victory out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rose's parting shot: Justin Rose couldn't have picked a better
shot on which to end his amateur career.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old Englishman thrilled the home crowd when he holed
out a 45-yard sand wedge on the 18th hole for birdie, a fitting end
to a week in which he finished in a four-way tie for fourth, two
shots out of the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it went in because it was a tough shot out
of the rough over a bunker,'' Rose said. ``I could have bailed out,
but I told my caddy I was going to go for it. I had nothing to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose missed out on a $134,167 payday because he's an amateur,
but that will change this week when he turns pro and plays in the
Dutch Open. The 69 he shot Sunday under intense pressure left him
no doubt he was making the correct decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that has been weighing on my mind, but I was
going to use this week to help me,'' said Rose, who turns 18 later
this month. ``The way it's gone, I would be silly not to, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose's fourth-place finish was the best showing by an amateur in
the British Open since West Palm Beach's Frank Stranahan finished
second in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unusual Grand Slam: O'Meara's victory means Orlando's
Isleworth is three-quarters of the way to a unique Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Besides O'Meara, U.S. Open winner Lee Janzen is a member at
Isleworth. This might be a good omen for the PGA Championship for
fellow Isleworth members Payne Stewart, Stuart Appleby, Craig Parry
and Scott Hoch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can you hold? Brad Faxon had a phone call Saturday from a man
who identified himself only as Gary, congratulating him on his play
so far in the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I answered the phone in the hotel and this voice said it was
Gary, but then room service came in and I asked him to wait and it
took a few minutes,'' Faxon said. ``I didn't know who it was, but I
didn't like to ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I got back to the phone, I said `Hi' and realized
I was talking to Gary Player. I had made Gary Player wait for room
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Faxon said Player had called to give him some advice on his
driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me the same advice four years ago, so I guess I
haven't been listening,'' Faxon said, ``but I'm trying.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Noteworthy: Lee Westwood, who would have won a $1 million
bonus had he followed up his Loch Lomond Invitational victory with
a win at the British Open, shot 78_298 and tied for 64th. ... Nick
Price rebounded from Saturday's humbling 82 with a 72. Asked how
much easier the course played Sunday, Price said: ``For me, 10
shots.'' ... Mark Calcavecchia of West Palm Beach shot 74_293 and
tied for 35th. ... Attendance for the four tournament days was
158,600.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
