<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-SIDEBAR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No easy answers from Parnevik
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ First, the words came in Swedish. Then
English. Then jibberish.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the language, the answers didn't come easy for Jesper
Parnevik.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, he had a chance to win the British Open, and once
again he was left thirsting to take a victory swig from the Auld
Claret Jug. Parnevik is becoming the Tom Lehman of this country's
national open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's very frustrating,'' Parnevik said. ``This is
my favorite tournament and I'd like to win it once. But I'm getting
used to it now.''
</P>
<P>
   He should. Sunday marked the third time in the last five years
the Jupiter resident has come close but failed to win the British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   And he's not getting any closer. After finishing second in 1994
and last year, Parnevik tied for fourth Sunday, two shots out of
the playoff won by Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik thought this would his day. He was in the final group,
two shots behind unheralded partner/leader Brian Watts. But
Parnevik never got closer to the lead during an even-par 70 that
included three birdies and three bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was walking uphill for 18 holes today,'' Parnevik
said. ``I played so well early and I thought the putts would start
dropping soon. Nobody was really doing anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt if I could be one-over going to the last two
holes and birdie the par-5s to get to minus-one, that would be the
winning score. You need to have the breaks the last day, and I had
a few putts today I thought I made and lipped out, and that turns
the whole round around.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his putter, Parnevik fought an erratic driver.
Errant tee shots led to all three bogeys _ on the sixth, eighth and
13th holes.
</P>
<P>
   He answered the first two bogeys with birdies on the next hole,
but the bogey at 13 proved too large to overcome. His par putt
there had looked to be in until it curled around the edge of the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hole the putt on 13 _ and I thought I had _ that was
big,'' Parnevik said. ``That put so much pressure on me to make
three birdies in the last four holes, which is very difficult to do
on this golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik has lost the British three ways. His back-nine rally in
1994 at Turnberry came up a shot short. He lost a two-shot lead
last year when his 73 wasn't close to matching Justin Leonard's
closing 65. And Sunday he failed to win from somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the near-misses, Parnevik said he doesn't think this
tournament owes him a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you have to do it,'' he said. ``Sometimes, the other
players give it to you, but so far it hasn't been that way. I just
have to keep on trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, 33, figures to have more chances. But one never knows
how many times he'll find himself in this position. Parnevik admits
the game may be becoming more mental in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be I'm getting jinxed in my head,'' he said. ``You
kind of wonder if you'll get back close to one.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Parnevik muttered a few words that nobody could
understand. But with the sad look on his face, no translation was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
