<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKE-LEGISLATION-500     07-19 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-LEGISLATION-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN:N.C. )  
 JUDGE VOIDS STUDY LINKING CANCER TO SECONDHAND SMOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge held Friday that the Environmental Protection
Agency made procedural and scientific mistakes when it declared in
a 1993 report that secondhand cigarette smoke caused as many as
3,000 cancer deaths a year among nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark report was considered critical in helping to launch
an era in which hundreds of municipalities nationwide passed full
or partial bans on smoking indoors.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge's ruling, while sharply critical of EPA officials
and the methods they used, is likely to have little immediate
impact on those laws, said regulators, antismoking advocates and
some cigarette industry officials. That is because the
environmental agency does not regulate indoor smoke and because
local governments have wide discretion to set their own regulatory
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the EPA review is not the only scientific study to
have associated second-hand smoke with health risks. But its
findings were cited by a number of other government agencies and
were widely trumpeted by antismoking advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, two cigarette industry officials said Sunday that
they believed the ruling, which government lawyers expect to
appeal, should make it more difficult for other cities to pass
similar laws and for plaintiffs to successfully sue over injuries
claimed to be the result of secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any legislative body that was considering passing a law based
on the EPA report is going to have to rethink it,'' said Seth
Moskowitz, a spokesman for R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., a unit of
R.J.R. Nabisco Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling, Judge William Osteen of U.S. District Court in
Greensboro, N.C., held that EPA officials made significant mistakes
when the agency brought together scientists to study secondhand
smoke. The ruling came in a lawsuit by major cigarette companies
seeking to have the report declared invalid.
</P>
<P>
   Osteen found that the composition of the study panel was flawed
because, among other things, none of its representatives were drawn
from industry. But in a far more damning finding, Osteen held that
agency researchers, rather than rigorously proving their case,
frequently shifted theories and selected the data they wanted in
order to reach a preordained conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the EPA publicly committed to a conclusion
before research had begun,'' Osteen wrote. He vacated the bulk of
the report, entitled, ``Respiratory Health Effects of Passive
Smoking: Lung Cancer and Other Disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Browner, EPA administrator, said the ruling should have no
effect on local antismoking ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inasmuch as the tobacco guys will claim that secondhand smoke
has no health effects, we are clearly upset,'' Ms. Browner said.
``But the important thing that people should understand is that
secondhand smoke is a real health risk. Nothing in this ruling
should be used to overturn any public health decision taken by any
business or any city to ban smoking.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Matthew Myers, a lawyer with the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids,
an advocacy group in Washington, said that he did not believe the
industry would use the ruling to challenge secondhand smoke laws
already in place. And a cigarette industry official, speaking on
the condition of anonymity, agreed. But one regulator, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said tobacco companies might seek to repeal
laws in communities where support for antismoking measures was not
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   At least one cigarette producer, R.J. Reynolds, indicated that
it might challenge laws in place. In a statement released Sunday,
Charles Blixt, the company's general counsel, said the court's
finding ``destroys the basis for those agencies and state and local
governments that have banned or restricted smoking because of the
EPA classification.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael York, a lawyer with Philip Morris Cos., the nation's
largest cigarette maker, said that he believed Osteen's ruling
would be a setback to those suing for injuries said to be caused by
secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent of those actions was a class action lawsuit
brought by flight attendants who claimed a variety of injuries from
secondhand smoke on airplanes. That lawsuit was settled by the
industry last year for $349 million, though producers said they
resolved the action to pave the way for last year's $368.5 billion
tobacco settlement proposal between the industry and 40 state
attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the agency issued its 1993 finding that secondhand
tobacco smoke was a Class A carcinogen, putting it in the same
category as radon, the EPA's methods had come under attack by the
tobacco industry, which filed its lawsuit in 1993 soon after the
report was issued. The report's findings were also questioned by
some independent authorities, like the Congressional Research
Service, an arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1988 that the EPA started drafting policy
recommendations about controlling secondhand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   But in his ruling, Osteen found that just a year later the
agency, rather than reaching a conclusion after ``collecting
information, researching and making findings,'' categorized
secondhand smoke as a ``known cause of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   With that conclusion in already in hand, Osteen wrote, EPA
officials spent the following years before their report's
publication making ``findings on selective information.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
