<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE MATTERS, A LOT, FOR FLORIDA DEMOCRATS  
 A FAST-TRACK BATTLE OF A DIFFERENT KIND  
 DRAWING A BATTLE LINE AT A RALLY FOR UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida Democrats are moving to end the raw racial rift that
threatens to cripple their party in this fall's elections and leave
it weaker than at any point in more than a century. But is the move
too little, too late?
</P>
<P>
   The rift opened in January when white Democrats in the Florida
House voted to replace a black representative, Willie Logan of
Opa-Locka, as their leader, saying he was not aggressive enough in
the job. In his place they installed a white woman, Rep. Anne
Mackenzie of Fort Lauderdale, who they argued would be a stronger
leader in the coming battle for control of this ever more populous
and politically important state.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, after six frustrating months of struggling to
close the rift, raise campaign money and recruit candidates for a
solid showing in the 1998 elections (Republicans control the State
House now and probably will again next year), Ms. Mackenzie
announced she was retiring from politics.
</P>
<P>
   Other top House Democrats immediately began maneuvering to
replace her in the leadership post with a black candidate. They
warned possible white contenders for the job that if blacks were
not given more say in Florida politics, the deeply angered black
vote might become the swing vote in the fall and tip the balance to
the Republicans in crucial legislative contests and the governor's
race.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Logan is already moving in that direction. A few weeks
ago he set up a political action committee that he says will be
financed with money from Republicans and dissident Democrats and
will support Republican candidates running against House Democrats
who opposed him in January. He says he is no longer interested in
being the House Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   By this weekend, several white legislators who had considered
running for Ms. Mackenzie's job had been persuaded by other top
Democrats to drop out. Of the three contestants left, all of them
black, party insiders said Rep. Les Miller of Tampa was most likely
to get the nod for the post when the Democratic House caucus next
meets, possibly as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to pull every facet of our party together,'' Miller
promised. ``I'm a loyal Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   A FAST-TRACK BATTLE OF A DIFFERENT KIND
</P>
<P>
   This year's House race in Kentucky's 4th Congressional District,
in the northeast corner of the state, is one of the more closely
watched elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The seat is wide open because the incumbent, Rep. Jim Bunning, a
Republican, is leaving the House to run for the Senate. The
district is fairly evenly divided between Republicans and
Democrats. And the contenders to replace Bunning _ Ken Lucas, a
former county judge who is a conservative Democrat, and Gex
Williams, a state senator who is a conservative Republican _ are
fairly evenly matched.
</P>
<P>
   The result of all this is a political dogfight. And it's getting
meaner.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lucas accused Williams of casting two ``horrendous''
votes in the Kentucky Senate that were _ varoooom!!! _
``anti-NASCAR,'' as in anti-stock-car.
</P>
<P>
   This is serious. In a good-ol'-boy state like Kentucky _ and in
a congressional district like the 4th, in which ground was broken
this weekend for a $130 million speedway _ being against NASCAR
(the National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing) is like being
against motherhood, apple pie, bourbon and bluegrass.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Lucas tell it, Williams voted ``no'' on two resolutions
that would have honored Kentucky drivers, among them the legendary
Darrell Waltrip. In each case the vote was 37-1, and Lucas sees
that as proof positive that Williams is one seriously out-of-touch
Kentucky politician.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Williams says his votes were cast for packages of
resolutions and bills that he did not know contained the stock-car
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as that was pointed out to me, I corrected it,'' he
said on Friday, adding that he was a fan of stock cars and Waltrip
and, indeed, had worked to get that new racing track located in the
4th District.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWING A BATTLE LINE AT A RALLY FOR UNITY
</P>
<P>
   In 20 years on Capitol Hill, Rep. Doug Bereuter of Nebraska has
built a reputation as a solid Republican moderate, seldom given to
partisan, in-your-face confrontation. The Republicanism practiced
in his 1st Congressional District, centered on Lincoln, the
capital, tends to be considerably less conservative and strident
than the brand practiced in Nebraska's two other districts, where
the Christian right increasingly holds sway.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Bereuter felt the urge to speak out against the
ever harder political line being taken by the state's religious
conservatives. He held his tongue, however _ partly by nature,
partly because he was considering running for statewide office.
</P>
<P>
   But a few months back Bereuter gave up the notion of seeking
higher office. And a few days ago he spoke his mind on the issue of
Republicans and religion, with a vehemence that is resonating well
beyond the Cornhusker State.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a Republican ``unity rally'' at Grand Island,
Bereuter declared that the party was being held captive by
``misguided leaders'' who were more interested in ideology than
consensus and who were spending so much time and energy criticizing
abortion rights and ``bashing'' public schools that many voters
were being alienated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people got religion lately when it seemed to be
especially good politics with certain voting blocs,'' he went on.
</P>
<P>
   Bereuter described himself as a Christian, but not one who wears
his religion ``like an armband.'' He also said he was ``pro-life by
commitment,'' but asserted that ``the average Nebraska Republican
doesn't believe the abortion issue should absolutely dominate all
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the audience walked out. Others refused to stand and
clap when the congressman finished. Here and there a few cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jon Christensen of Omaha, one of the leaders of Nebraska's
Christian right, said, with mockery in his voice, ``In light of
Doug's speech, can we pray?''
</P>
<P>
   Several party stalwarts declared that Bereuter was more
dangerous to the party than Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Nebraska, Bereuter's blunt remarks and call for party
inclusion have given a lift to other moderate and centrist
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington last week, the Republican Leadership Council,
whose board includes Gov. Pete Wilson of California, Gov. John
Engler of Michigan and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York, hailed the
congressman as a man of courage and ``common-sense conservative
convictions'' who understood that ``narrow, single-issue politics
is the surest way to put the Democrats back in power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2226EDT &QL; 
