u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TAXI-PARTITIONS-56     07-19 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXI-PARTITIONS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES TO TAXI PARTITIONS URGED AS INJURIES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four years ago, at the height of a crime wave against
taxi drivers in New York City, regulators voted to require a
seemingly simple precaution: a partition of bulletproof plastic
between the front and back seats in most yellow cabs.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, robberies and murders of cabdrivers have plummeted,
along with other crimes. But injuries in taxi accidents have
increased, in part because riders have been hurled against the
partitions, with many suffering concussions or broken bones, or in
some cases jagged, disfiguring facial cuts from metal hinges and
screws.
</P>
<P>
   While no statistics are kept on the percentage of passenger
injuries caused by partitions, some doctors, personal-injury
lawyers and safety experts are pressing for changes in their design
to reduce the risk and severity of injuries. Some also complain
that the administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani failed to tackle
these problems in its recent package of safety reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say they are also concerned about the
hazards, which lead to costly insurance claims. Although few in the
industry would be willing to do away with the partitions out of
concern for drivers' safety, regulators at the city's Taxi and
Limousine Commission say they are preparing to seek information
from partition manufacturers about ways to decrease some of the
dangers.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. John Sherman, an assistant clinical professor of surgery
at New York Hospital-Cornell University Medical College and a vocal
critic of the partitions, said some of the blame rests with the
commission, which he noted has specifications for the design,
placement and padding of the partition so vague that the partitions
vary greatly from cab to cab. Some are so close to the back seat or
have so many protruding parts, he said, that even passengers who
wear seat belts _ and few riders do _ are sometimes thrown into
them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some say the options are limited. Industry executives had
hoped that roomier minivans and sport utility vehicles would lead
to safer and more comfortable rides. Almost 500 of the bigger
vehicles, mostly Honda Odysseys and Isuzu Oasises, are now on the
road, and some owners love them. But officials of the biggest group
of fleet owners, the Metropolitan Taxicab Board of Trade, said the
vans have not proved tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the taxi commission said the solution is not as
simple as mandating the use of roomier cabs, because some
automakers have proved unwilling to provide the support and
warranties for the vehicles to be used as cabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, what we're desperately searching for is options,''
said Diane McGrath-McKechnie, the chairwoman of the commission. The
commission is now pushing the Chevrolet Venture, an even bigger
minivan than the Honda. Unlike the Honda, the Venture is
manufactured in a special heavy-duty taxi version.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGrath-McKechnie said that when it came to avoiding
injuries from the partitions, the most important preventive measure
was seat belts. In the last year, the commission has begun
requiring recorded messages in every taxi urging riders to wear
their belts, and has stepped up enforcement to make sure the belts
are available and not jammed between the seat cushions.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sherman said that partition injuries had declined
somewhat at his hospital over the past year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The growing public awareness of the dangers of the partition and
of the increase in accidents may also be spurring more passengers
to buckle up. David Grant, the president of a Manhattan public
relations firm, who was not wearing a seat belt when a cab he was
riding in in 1996 struck another and he slammed into the partition,
breaking six bones in his neck, said he never gets in a cab without
putting on a belt now.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said many of the worst injuries could be avoided simply
by moving the partition's change tray from the right side of the
partition to the center, where passengers usually do not sit.
Others have suggested putting padding around the tray. A few people
have suggested doing away with the partitions altogether, given the
overall drop in crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partitions came about at a time when there was a problem
with security,'' said Glen Wiener, a personal-injury lawyer who
represented a woman who was wearing a belt but still slammed into
the partition and suffered a brain injury when a cab she was riding
in struck another in 1996. ``But I can't think of the last time I
was in a cab and the driver had the partition window closed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. McGrath-McKechnie said the partitions were here to stay.
And Michael Higgins, a cabby who publishes the trade newspaper Taxi
Talk, said it made no sense to get rid of them just because crime
had fallen, adding that many drivers closed the partition window at
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime is down because people have taken steps to protect
themselves, whether it's electing a crime-fighting mayor or putting
in partitions,'' he said. ``If you start taking away some of the
protective measures, then crime comes back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
