r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWBOYSNOTES-TEX     07-19 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS LOSE CORNERBACK TO KNEE INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys cornerback Wendell Davis
has been lost for the year with a torn anterior cruciate ligament
in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Davis sustained the injury Friday, and a
magnetic-resonance-imaging test confirmed his worst fears. He is
expected to undergo surgery in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was bad the instant it happened,'' said Davis, a
third-year veteran from Oklahoma. ``When I jumped, it popped.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who is no stranger to knee injuries, said he's worried
whether the injury is career-threatening. Davis underwent
arthroscopic surgery after the 1996 season to repair a lateral
meniscus tear in his right knee. He sprained his left knee during
training camp last year and underwent surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys replaced Davis on the roster with cornerback Ron
Bailey, who signed a rookie free-agent contract with the Cowboys in
May but was cut two weeks ago. GETTING PHYSICAL
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys resume practice tomorrow, after taking today
off for the team's annual training-camp golf tournament, expect the
intensity to go up a few notches.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the only negative thing he saw
after the first four days of practice was that the team wasn't
being physical enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made progress every day, especially offensively,''
Gailey said in his daily news conference before Sunday's afternoon
practice. ``I've seen the timing coming back to the passing game. I
like our team speed on defense. But we are going to have to be more
physical on both sides of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the coaches will create more situations for the team
to be physical this week in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defensive end Leon Lett must have heard Gailey. Roughly
an hour after the news conference, Lett delivered the biggest hit
of training camp when he leveled running back Chris Warren. MILLS,
EUBANKS IMPRESSIVE
</P>
<P>
   Gailey won't comment on position battles because he says it's
too early in camp to make assessments.
</P>
<P>
   However, receivers Ernie Mills and Anthony Eubanks are proving
that it's not too early to make impressions, drawing raves for
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   If Mills, an eight-year veteran who signed with Cowboys as a
free agent in the off-season, continues his sizzling performance,
he would likely surface as the team's No. 2 receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Mills has the advantage of knowing Gailey's offense from his
days with the Pittsburgh Steelers. Now, he is proving that he has
recovered from a 1996 knee injury and that last season's 11-catch
performance with Carolina was an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of exactly what we had in Pittsburgh,'' Gailey
said. ``That's good enough for me. He didn't have the best year in
Carolina. But we thought he would be a good addition to the
football team. We've been through a lot of wars together. And I've
seen him make a lot of plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks, a rookie free agent from Arkansas, will be hard-pressed
to win a spot on the roster. Gailey said the Cowboys hope to keep
six wide receivers and maybe seven. He also said the number could
be reduced to five.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks is unlikely to bump Irvin, Mills, Billy Davis, Stepfret
Williams, Jimmy Oliver or Macey Brooks. However, he has been
noticed, which could lead to a practice-squad spot or a contract
with another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He catches everything that goes up in the air just about,''
Gailey said. ``He was the same way in minicamp. He's not a guy with
blazing speed. But he catches the ball. You got to give the guy
credit.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Gailey said the Cowboys will change their practice schedule
next week, going with full pads in the morning and without pads in
the afternoon workouts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rookie linebacker Darren Hambrick practiced Sunday for the
first time after missing the past two days because of a tooth
extraction.
He Said It
</P>
<P>
   ``Just call me Bill.'' _ Bill Bates former Cowboys safety and
new assistant coach when queried about who would known as coach
Bates between him and defensive-end coach Jim Bates
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
