<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JONES HAS A STANDARD TO SET OFF THE TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Shana Williams was on Cloud Nine late Sunday
afternoon. The Seton Hall graduate student had just won the Marion
Jones-less long jump competition at the Goodwill Games. With a host
of reporters surrounding her in the interview tent, Williams didn't
wait for the swarm to ask about the ghost who hadn't competed; she
brought it up herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was this your biggest victory of the year?'' someone asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest victory would have been to have beaten Marion
Jones,'' Williams said. Jones, a sprinter, has become omnipresent
for female sprinters and long jumpers. She won the 100 meters
Sunday night in a Goodwill Games record 10.90. She has quickly
filled the void expected to be left by Jackie Joyner-Kersee _ who
is at the Goodwill Games, making one of her final appearances
before her retirement _ in the bustling world of women's track and
field. At 22, Jones has been proclaimed as the sport's next
superstar.
</P>
<P>
   A former high school track sensation, Jones, who also played
basketball in college, has been a transformation of marketing
hungry for the new, the fresh. Williams shrugged Sunday afternoon:
She is resigned to the fact that from now until the 2000 Olympics
in Sydney, Jones will be the standard by which all sprinters and
jumpers will be judged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not intimidated by her,'' Williams said. ``She's just so
intense; she comes out of the blue, blows everybody out of the
water with two jumps. She reminds you of Jackie Joyner in her
prime.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of Marion Jones goes further than Madison Avenue and
the current field of competitors. She is being watched closely by a
cadre of girls five, six, seven years younger, who look up to her
the way she looked at Joyner-Kersee. A role model, a beacon light.
A target.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the meet on Sunday, about 150 runners _ high school
age and younger _ from the New York metropolitan area participated
in a hastily arranged exhibition. They ran dashes and spirited
relays. Robert Taylor watched proudly as members of his girls team,
the Bronx-based Zodiac club, held their own against runners from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has been involved with the Zodiacs for 20 years, going
back to when his daughter was 16, and has coached the team for 17
years. At age 55, Taylor has watched the evolution of female
superstars from Wilma Rudolph to Jackie Joyner-Kersee and now
Marion Jones. The impression Jones has made on his runners is
striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's replaced Gail Devers in the eyes of the young kids,''
Taylor said. ``You hear them talking: `I want to run like her,' `I
want to do what she does.'''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Jones, one of his sprinters, 16-year-old Shirvonne
McCarthy, plans to compete in the long jump. Nolle Graham, one of
New York city's most promising sprinters and long jumpers, said
that Jones has become a performance role model.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the sudden attention and adulation, Jones has a steep
mountain to climb before she joins the icon ranks of Rudolph and
Joyner-Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   Whether she gets there depends on what she does, not on the
track but off it. Taylor was 17 when Rudolph won three gold medals
at the Rome Olympics. On her return to the United States, the city
of Clarksville, Tenn., wanted to honor her with a parade and a
banquet. Rudolph told the city that she would not participate in a
segregated parade or in a segregated banquet. Rudolph made her
stand, and Clarksville had its first integrated parade and banquet.
</P>
<P>
   In intervening years, Taylor saw Rudolph dedicate her time to a
number of national community groups serving children _ especially
children from disadvantaged backgrounds. A couple of weeks ago,
Joyner-Kersee went to a recreation center in New York and worked
with young athletes on everything from running form to life skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``When kids get to see Jackie, they know it's not phony _ they
know she really cares,'' Taylor said.``I don't know if she was like
that at the beginning of her career, but I think pretty quickly,
because of her background, she knew what kids needed,'' he added,
referring to Joyner-Kersee's upbringing in East St. Louis. ``I'm
not sure if Marion had the same background.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is young yet, in years and experience. The world is just
beginning to come to her. As a runner, Jones is having a dramatic
impact on young female runners. But she hasn't brought herself to
the same level as Kersee and Rudolph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' Taylor said as he rounded his girls up and prepared
to leave Mitchell Field. ``Not in the eyes of kids. Young kids talk
about running like Marion Jones, but Jackie Joyner-Kersee still has
the biggest impact on their lives. She's above Marion in the way
kids perceive her, even though everyone wants to run like Marion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
