<P>
   (NYT11) FLINT, Mich. -- July 19, 1998 -- GM-STRIKE-JUDGE, 7-19
-- Judge Paul Gadola Jr., with memorabilia from the 1937 case
involving the General Motors Corp. and the United Auto Workers, in
which his father, Paul Gadola, a state judge, played a key role.
Now, for the first time since 1937, the company has sued the union
in a bid to end a major strike. And in a remarkable coincidence
that is the talk of the town, the federal judge assigned to the
case is Paul Gadola Jr. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNIONDALE, N.Y. -- July 19, 1998 -- RUN-GOODWILL-GAMES,
7-19 -- Chris Huffins, floating in midair, won the decathlon's long
jump competition at the Goodwill Games on Sunday. Huffins finished
the first five events with a narrow lead over Dan O'Brien. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PLANTATION, Fla. -- July 19, 1998 -- TEENSMOKERS-COURT-3,
7-19 -- Earl Mogk, 60, in Teen Smoking Court in Plantation, Fla.,
talking to teen-agers about his larynx cancer, the product, he
says, of 40 years of smoking. ``When I was your age, there was
nobody out there to tell me about the dangers of smoking,'' says
Mogk, talking through an electronic device he has used since his
larynx, and vocal cords were surgically removed. ``The reason I'm
here today is for a reality check.'' (Andrew Itkoff/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PLANTATION, Fla. -- July 19, 1998 -- TEENSMOKERS-COURT-2,
7-19 -- A crowd of mostly teen-agers inside the courtroom of Judge
Steven Shutter in Plantation, Fla., for a recent session of Teen
Smoking Court. In Florida's fight against teen-age smoking,
Shutter's courtroom in Plantation, Fla., is a new weapon that
combines education, health warnings and parental nagging with the
weight of the law. Violators are given the choice of a $53 fine,
including court costs, or eight hours of community service. (Andrew
Itkoff/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PLANTATION, Fla. -- July 19, 1998 -- TEENSMOKERS-COURT-1,
7-19 -- Judge Steven Shutter, presiding over Florida's Teen Smoking
Court. In Florida's fight against teen-age smoking, Shutter's
courtroom in Plantation, Fla., a suburb just west of Fort
Lauderdale, is a new weapon that combines education, health
warnings and parental nagging with the weight of the law. ``This is
not a crime,'' says Shutter. ``It's wrong, it's stupid, it's
dangerous, but it's not a crime. You ruin your health, you ruin
your life, but you don't care. So let's talk about the legal
consequences.'' (Andrew Itkoff/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) DALLIKON, Switzerland -- July 19, 1998 --
FARMING-GENETICS-2, 7-19 -- Kaspar Gunthardt inspecting his carrot
crop at his organic farm near Zurich. A traditionalist who has
nevertheless embraced the future, by using various technological
advances in farming, when it comes to playing with the rules of
nature Gunthardt draws a line that he says he will never cross. ``A
bunch of people are trying to get rich by telling us that nature
isn't good enough and that we will have to take genes out of a fish
and put them in a strawberry if we want to survive,'' he says.
(Michael Specter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CIAMPINO, Italy -- July 19, 1998 -- FARMING-GENETICS-1,
7-19 -- Organically grown grain being harvested at the Boncompagni
Farm in Ciampino, outside Rome. Resistance to engineering
modifications in plant genetics is widespread among Europe's
farmers, as well as consumers. Throughout the world last year more
than 30 million acres of commercial farmland were planted with
genetically modified seeds -- 10 times as much as the year before.
But not one of those acres was in the 15 countries of the European
Union. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 19, 1998 -- HENRYHOLT-CEO, 7-19 --
Michael Naumann, 56, the chief executive of Henry Holt &AMP; Co., has
agreed to become Germany's Minister of Culture if the Social
Democrats win the elections next September. ``I grew up in a
country which was savaged by its own history,'' says Naumann, who
is a German citizen. ``And I belong to that generation born during
the war that had numerous questions and tried to redefine the
course of our country. I've started to really enjoy the democratic
institutions in my country.'' (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KATONAH, N.Y. -- July 19, 1998 -- BORGIA-OPERA-REVIEW,
7-19 -- Vivica Genaux as Maffio Orsini, a trouser role, with
carnival revelers and members of the Orchestra of St. Luke's in a
concert production of Donizetti's ``Lucrezia Borgia,'' at the
yearly ``Bel Canto at Caramoor'' festival. For many opera buffs,
it's hard to distinguish ``Lucrezia Borgia'' among the nearly 70
operas Donizetti churned out during his 20 working years. (Richard
L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 19, 1998 -- RELIGION-HEALTHCARE, 7-17 --
The Dalai Lama, discussed how Buddhist practices might apply to
Western medicine at Beth Israel Medical Center in May. Dr. Mathew
Krzan, of Beth Israel Medical Center, on a gurney, played a
patient. Today, the many boundaries between religion and medicine
in the United States, are being eroded as doctors and nurses,
priests and rabbis acknowledge that they may have a better chance
to cure ills and promote health by working together, not apart.
(Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 19, 1998 -- NY-SHELTER, 7-17 -- Kris
Hernden, 21, is among a group of homeless young people, most of
them gay and runaways, who hang out at the piers in the West
Village of Manhattan. Local community activists are seeking to
build a shelter for the homeless youth. Hernden, who left Baltimore
for New York with a close friend, once dreamed of moving to the
storied West Village. ``I just had to leave Baltimore,'' he says.
``I was basically working here and there. I got tired of that. I'm
21. I should be stable by now.'' (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
