<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-PROSTITUTES     07-19 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-PROSTITUTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S MOST RESPECTED OFFICERS LED PRECINCT WHERE SEX SCANDAL
FESTERED
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI and DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They include the police commissioner of Philadelphia,
a Manhattan criminal court judge, and the chiefs who supervise New
York City's detective and transit police bureaus. The list of
former supervisors at the Midtown South precinct over the last 15
years reads like a ``Who's Who'' in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Police Commissioner Howard Safir has blamed a ``breakdown in
supervision'' at Midtown South for enabling officers there to have
sex with prostitutes routinely, often while on duty, without being
caught. He said the activity went on for as long as a decade and a
half.
</P>
<P>
   Although police say there is no evidence to suggest that
supervisors knew about the activity, were the internal inquiry to
show otherwise, the department could find itself in the unenviable
position of having to interview former ranking officers at Midtown
South, one of the city's busiest station houses and one of its most
prestigious commands.
</P>
<P>
   As the department confronts the scandal, which has enveloped 23
officers so far, it remains unclear how deep investigators will dig
in exhuming the precinct's past.
</P>
<P>
   Some investigators say the inquiry might have led to other
supervisors had a leak to the press not prompted the department to
end it on Thursday. In the last two weeks, they said, two officers
had told investigators the illegal activity was more extensive and
had gone on for longer than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers agreed to cooperate by obtaining incriminating
statements from other officers, the investigators said. It is
unknown whether the two cooperating officers named any supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a break, and it looked like it might take us into a
whole new realm,'' said an Internal Affairs Bureau investigator who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``But we never got the chance to
follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Few details have emerged about how extensive the relationships
were over time between the police and prostitutes at the brothel,
at 335 W. 39th St., and at a massage parlor where officers were
filmed at least once entering and demanding sex.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Safir has transferred three precinct supervisors at
Midtown South, including the commander, Deputy Inspector Joseph
McKeever. But Manhattan police supervisors confirmed that McKeever
arrived at the precinct a year and a half ago, only after the
Internal Affairs Bureau and the Manhattan District Attorney's
office had begun their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mayronne, who commanded Midtown South in 1987 and 1988
before going on to become the department's chief spokesman, finally
retiring in 1996, said he could not believe that his officers were
frequenting the brothel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say definitely, but I would be very much surprised,''
he said by telephone from his home in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. But he
added that commanding officers ``rely on the lieutenants and the
sergeants, because they're out there more than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it seemed impossible that police officers could have
kept the ring secret for so long. ``Fifteen years?'' he said. ``I
mean, cops are tight-lipped, but they go to parties. Eventually it
would get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the prominent officers who led Midtown South are John
Timoney, once the precinct's executive officer, who later rose to
first deputy commissioner before leaving to become police
commissioner in Philadelphia; Chief of Detectives William Allee,
also once the precinct's No. 2, now one of the ``superchiefs'' who
make up Safir's cabinet; Chief George Brown, formerly its
commanding officer, who now heads the Transit Division; Deputy
Chief Michael Fox, also once commanding officer, now the
second-in-command of Patrol Borough Manhattan South, and Capt. John
Wasiak, once the precinct's executive officer, who heads the
dignitary protection unit in the Intelligence Division.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Mayronne, none of those former precinct supervisors
could be reached for comment Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who oversaw Midtown South during the time the sex
ring is said to have existed developed reputations for being tough
on corruption, prostitution, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Brown became known for aggressive vice crackdowns when he ran
Midtown South. His officers figured out when prostitutes began
their workdays and arrested them as soon as they hit the street,
cutting into their earnings and driving many out of the precinct.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980719.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-19 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT     07-19 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TAKE PHILLIES' GIFT AND HAND IT RIGHT BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets held Family Day before their game with
Philadelphia Sunday when the children of players and executives
took turns hitting plastic balls and running around the bases. The
real family day came later, though, when the game was on the line
and when Al Leiter watched Mark Leiter pitch and Hal McRae watched
Brian McRae bat.
</P>
<P>
   The game didn't have to come down to that matchup in the 10th
inning or any of the other confrontations Mark Leiter had with the
Mets that inning and the one before. But the Mets' pitchers
squandered what had appeared to be a good lead, and then their
hitters suddenly couldn't hit to salvage a victory.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Phillies won, 7-6, in 10 innings and benefited
instead of the Mets in the National League wild-card race that has
10 weeks left.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies won by erupting for three runs to take a 6-5 lead
in the seventh inning against Jeff Tam and Bill Pulsipher, then by
scoring a run in the 10th against Dennis Cook. That one came on
Mike Lieberthal's fourth hit of the game, a single, and a double by
Ruben Amaro Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost, too, by getting only two hits in the last six
innings after John Olerud led off the fifth inning with a home run
for a 5-2 lead. They struck out for all three outs in three of
those innings, including the ninth, in which they tied the game
because Mark Leiter walked just about everybody in the ball park
except the children of the Mets' players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in the dugout after the game and I brought my
son in there,'' Leiter related later. ``I said, `Mark, I almost
blew the game. I walked four guys in one inning.' He said, `Yeah,
but Dad, I walked six guys in one inning this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter was not present for his 7-year-old nephew's Little
League travails, but he sat in the Mets' dugout watching his older
brother pitch a symmetrically wild ninth inning. The Phillies
closer struck out McRae, then walked Edgardo Alfonzo and Mike
Piazza. He next struck out Butch Huskey and walked Olerud and
Bernard Gilkey, forcing in the tying run, before he struck out Luis
Lopez for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter professed at first to not being torn between wanting
his brother to pitch well in those circumstances and wanting his
team to tie and even win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be like that, when we were younger,'' Al said.
``We've both been around long enough. He's got plenty of other
chances to get saves.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later he added: ``If our guys get hits and we score
runs, great, we win. If he does well, I'm happy for him. It's out
of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   And after another moment he said: ``It's definitely a
double-edged sword. He's still my brother. It's definitely tough to
watch. Now I know what my mom goes through.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark was incredulous that Al had initially taken the position
that he essentially is a big boy and is on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's on the mound, I root for him,'' Mark said. ``Last
night he threw a great game, I was happy for him. I don't root
against my team, but when he does a good job, I'm happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   And furthermore, Mark went on, how could Al not feel for him in
that awful ninth inning? ``I don't know how he sat watching in the
ninth without being a wreck,'' Mark said. ``When he used to walk a
lot of guys, I used to go crazy watching. I'd say, `Throw a darn
strike.' If he didn't get frustrated watching me, that would
surprise me. If he could say he watched that game and wasn't
pulling for me to throw a strike, I'd be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   After Amaro drove in the tie-breaking run with only his second
hit in 16 at-bats right-handed this season, the Leiters got to go
through the agony again in the 10th. But this time Hal McRae, the
Phillies' hitting coach, was on the Al Leiter end of the family
drama.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Matt Franco lined a pinch-hit double to left
field, bringing up Brian McRae, the Mets' leadoff batter, who had
made five outs in five times at bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to see him do well and be successful but not in that
situation,'' the elder McRae said. ``If he drives in a run, hits
the ball out of the ball park, which he almost did, we lose the
ball game. I want him to have a good day, but I don't want him to
make a play or get a hit to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   So he was rooting for his son to make another out? ``I would
like him to maybe hit it hard right at someone,'' the father said,
grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Brian's fly to deep right field did not beat the Phillies
because Bobby Abreu caught it. Franco went to third after the
catch, and Leiter walked Alfonzo again. That brought up Piazza,
whose father roots hard for him to win games.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the first pitch, the catcher lined a hanging
slider toward the left-field fence, but it was clearly going foul.
``I hit it well and just pulled it foul,'' Piazza said. ``I just
got out in front of it a little bit. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The next pitch was even more frustrating because Piazza missed
it completely, ending the game. ``It was a fastball away,'' Mark
Leiter said. ``I think he got himself out because it was down and I
don't think he was expecting me to throw a fastball 0-2. I think he
was looking off-speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither batter nor pitcher was looking for another walk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
