<HEADLINE>
NATION'S 4TH-LARGEST VINEYARD MAY GO PUBLIC TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
The initial public offering of Golden State Vintners, the nation's
fourth-largest vineyard, is expected to get priced and rolled out
as early as tomorrow, financial industry sources say.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The offering is expected to raise about $40.9 million, with 4.3
million shares going on the block at a price between $16 and $19.
Lead manager of the offering is Goldman Sachs with Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist and J.P. Morgan as co-managers of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Buying wine stocks can be as tricky as collecting vintage vino.
But investors who like to drink wine are finding it fun (and
sometimes profitable) to own shares in vineyards. &UR;  &LR; The October IPO
of Beringer Wine Estates, also underwritten by Goldman, was so
popular it shot up 25 percent to $32.50 on its first day of
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State, based in Greenbrae, may be the biggest California
vineyard and winery you've never heard of. &UR;  &LR; And while its name may
sound more like a motor oil than a fine wine, you probably have
sipped its grape without even knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State, among other things, is a private label producer of
bulk wines that supplies such established brands as Sebastiani
Vineyards and Sutter Home Winery. It also produces wines, usually
in the $10 or less category, under its own proprietary names, such
as Summerfield.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's more to Golden State than just wine-making. It also
provides various services to larger wineries that like to outsource
in order to slash costs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Robert Mondavi Winery and Beringer Wine Estates,
two of California's largest publicly held wine concerns, have
contracts with Golden State for services such as barrel
fermentation and storage, according to Securities and Exchange
Commission filings.
</P>
<P>
   And before you turn up your nose at wine that costs less than 10
bucks a bottle, consider that 83 percent of all wine consumed in
the United States is in this category, according to Lewis Perdue,
publisher of Wine Investment News in Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 category is under such severe price pressure these days
from oversupply that vineyards are looking for ways to squeeze
margins and become more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine prices are dropping like a lead blimp,'' Perdue says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  While Golden State has a Northern California address, 9,600
acres of its vineyards are in the Central Valley, which is better
known for its table grapes and raisins than it is for Chardonnay
vines.
</P>
<P>
   And at first blush, that causes some wine drinkers to pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a definite effort on their part to change their
Central Valley image,'' says George Schofield, a vineyard
consultant in St. Helena.
</P>
<P>
   Modesto may not ring as impressively as Sonoma, but Golden
State's refined and advanced wine-making processes have allowed it
to make some decent wines for under a sawbuck &UR; ,  &LR; Perdue says. For
example, three of the top 13 Chardonnays rated by Wine Spectator
magazine in the under-$10 category were made exclusively from
Golden State's wine.
</P>
<P>
   Wine snobs ``would call anything from the Central Valley crap,''
but Golden State ``has been known to make good wine from Central
Valley grapes,'' Perdue says.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody must be drinking the stuff. Over the past five years,
the company has seen its revenues increased 19 percent a year.
Revenues in fiscal year 1997 were $95.8 million while net income
was $6.17 million, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are risks. A couple of clouds hang over Golden
State that investors should be aware of, Perdue says.
</P>
<P>
   The company is carrying a heavy amount of debt, $30.2 million,
and it may be losing future business with E.J. Gallo Winery, a
major customer, Perdue says. A spokeswoman for Golden State was
unable to comment due to the pre-offering quiet period.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Still, the strengths of Golden State's diversified operation
may outweigh any negatives. Says Perdue: The winery is ``as
well-positioned as any wine company in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached at 901 Mission St., S.F. 94103,
phone at (415) 777-8444, or e-mail at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He also
appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak program on Tuesdays and Thursdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
