<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRESS THE BOSS WITH YOUR WORK, NOT KISSING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:  I just got a new job and want to start out on a good foot.
What's the best way to be on good terms with my manager without
kissing up to him?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Good managers don't want ``yes people'' who will follow
their orders without an independent thought. They want employees
who are enthusiastic, work hard and can work cooperatively as part
of a team _ but that's not the same thing as ``kissing up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a manager, I look for someone who lives and breathes our
mission,'' said Abby Snay, executive director of Jewish Vocational
Services, a San Francisco career counseling agency. ``A manager can
tell if someone is just kissing up or if they're sincerely
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of worrying about how to be on good terms with your
manager, focus on how to succeed in your job. If you're doing your
work well, chances are that you'll get along just fine with your
boss.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few tips for starting out at a new workplace:
</P>
<P>
   _ Scope out the organizational culture. If everyone works until
5:30 p.m., don't leave at 4:45 p.m. Find out what skills or styles
are most valued. Figure out who the truly respected employees are _
and then befriend one or two from whom you can learn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't be afraid to ask questions. Clarify what your boss
really wants from you. ``Sometimes a manager will say, `Get the
report done soon,' '' said John Vercelli, a former manager who is
now a career coach with Coaching Resource Inc. in Burlingame. ``The
employee assumes he means next Wednesday. But the manager means by
lunchtime.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Do your own job really well, no matter how elementary it
seems. Then find ways to help the company that go beyond the basics
of your job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set up a time line for performance reviews with your boss _
maybe after your first month but certainly by the end of your first
90 days. That way, little issues won't have a chance to grow into
big problems.
</P>
<P>
   Want to read more? Take a look at ``Your First 30 Days: Building
a Professional Image in a New Job,'' by Elwood Chapman. It's a
short, very basic how-to book that's available for $10.95 from
Crisp Publications in Menlo Park at (800) 442-7477.
</P>
<P>
   For another easy-to-read book that takes a somewhat longer-range
view, try ``Rules for the Road: Surviving Your First Job Out of
School,'' by Eve Luppert (Perigee, $13).
</P>
<P>
   You also can check out ``How to Be a Star at Work,'' by Robert
E. Kelley (Times Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I had knee surgery last fall that kept me home for two
months. When I came back to work, my boss called me in and told me
I wasn't needed anymore because the people who had filled in for me
were doing such a good job. Is it legal for them to fire me like
that?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Your company sounds like it's on shaky legal ground here.
By firing you, it may have violated federal and state laws that
protect employees on medical leave.
</P>
<P>
   The Family &AMP; Medical Leave Act, signed by President Clinton in
1993, applies to workplaces with 50 or more employees. It states
that companies must give eligible workers 12 weeks of unpaid time
off each year if they have or adopt a baby, face a serious health
problem or have a family member with a serious health problem.
</P>
<P>
   The FMLA requires companies to give workers their jobs back
after those 12 weeks unless something happens while they're gone,
such as a broad set of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knee surgery would probably qualify as a serious health
condition, so this would be a job-protected leave,'' said Claudia
Center, an attorney with the nonprofit Employment Law Center in San
Francisco. ``They can't take this person's job away unless there's
a legitimate reduction in force that would have occurred anyhow.''
</P>
<P>
   You can get more information on FMLA _ including an excellent
free question-and-answer booklet _ from the National Partnership
for Women &AMP; Families. Call (202) 986-2600, or visit their Web site
at www.nationalpartnership.org.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, talk to a lawyer about your case. If your company has
violated your FMLA rights, federal law could require it to pay you
twice the amount of your lost wages. State law could hold the
company liable for punitive damages, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Employment Law Center offers free advice on FMLA issues, at
(800) 880-8047. The National Employment Lawyers Association can
refer you to a private attorney with experience in FMLA cases, at
(415) 227-4655.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I'm a bottom-rung supervisor on salary, and my boss
recently has started to schedule me for five 10-hour days each
week. Is this proper and/or legal?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; The answer depends on whether you're being correctly
classified as an exempt employee.
</P>
<P>
   If you're truly exempt from overtime laws, you're required to
put in as many hours as necessary to get the job done. That might
be 35 hours, 50 hours or 80 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're not an exempt employee, California law says your
company must pay you time-and-a-half whenever you put in more than
40 hours in one week.
</P>
<P>
   Simply being paid a salary rather than an hourly wage doesn't
automatically mean that you're exempt from overtime pay. Instead,
exempt status depends on a variety of factors related to the
content of your job _ such as whether you supervise two or more
other people, have hiring and firing authority, and spend more than
half your time on managerial tasks.
</P>
<P>
   This can be a really confusing area. And in fact, there's a
growing number of lawsuits by bottom-rung supervisors who claim
that their firms misclassified them as exempt in an effort to avoid
paying overtime.
</P>
<P>
   So check with a lawyer to see whether you've been classified
correctly. Or call the California Labor Commissioner at (415)
557-7878 to get a copy of the exemption criteria for your specific
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Have a question about your workplace or career, your boss or an
employee? Send it to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San Francisco
Chronicle, 901 Mission Street, San Francisco 94103. Or send e-mail
to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415) 764-2815. We can't respond to
each query in person, but we will answer as many in print as we
can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
