</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBJOBS-CLASSIFIEDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETTING A JOB THROUGH SPECIALIZED WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL EMERT  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Scott Dahl had been given notice by his employer and needed to find
a new job fast.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newspaper classifieds were of little help because Dahl's field _
funeral-parlor marketing _ is an esoteric one. But after 20 minutes
surfing the World Wide Web, Dahl, a resident of Cleveland, found a
want ad at Funeralnet (www.funeralnet.com) that seemed promising.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, he received a response to an e-mail query, and
in two days, he had a face-to-face interview. One month after his
Web search began, he was on the job at Brunner Funeral Home, 20
miles from his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so easy, as opposed to sending out resumes in the mail,
waiting a week and then getting a postcard saying, `You may hear
from us in six more weeks,''' said Dahl, who before his Web search
had mailed out dozens of paper resumes with no results.
</P>
<P>
   Dahl's experience is not typical, of course. Job hunting over
the Web generally involves a substantial time commitment and many
megabytes of frustration, just like conventional job searches.
</P>
<P>
   But Dahl's case does illustrate the value of the Web for
job-seeking in highly specialized fields. In the mortuary business,
for example, there are no nationwide trade publications, so a Web
site is the perfect way to reach members in the geographically
diverse industry.
</P>
<P>
   In just the past two years, hundreds of helpful Web sites have
been created with information for highly specialized groups. Some
of the sites are strictly employment related while others,
including Funeralnet, list classifieds as one of many features.
</P>
<P>
   Employment experts recommend that job seekers try targeted Web
sites before approaching humongous career sites such as America's
Job Bank (www.ajb.dni.us) whose hundreds of thousands of job
listings can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a smattering of examples of specialized sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ Starchefs (www.starchefs.com), which started as a
consumer-oriented Web site with recipes and chef profiles, has
become an important employment resource in the restaurant industry.
It currently lists about 300 job listings and 200 resumes for chefs
and other restaurant personnel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forty Plus of Northern California (www.sirius.com/40plus)
posts resumes for professionals aged 40 and over. To use the site,
people must pay a membership fee, attend meetings and volunteer
time to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   _ Saludos Web (www.saludos.com) offers a job bank and a resume
database for Spanish-speaking professionals and recent college
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Produce Job Exchange (www.producejobs.com) lists resumes
and jobs for positions such as produce brokers and grocery store
vegetable buyers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Layover.com (www.layover.com) is a key resource for truckers
who stay connected to the non-interstate world through their
laptops. It contains listings for full-time jobs and individual
hauls for independent truckers, as well as information on labor
disputes, trucker health and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asia-Net (www.asia-net.com) matches job openings with job
seekers who speak English and Asian languages such as Japanese,
Korean or Mandarin. Asia-Net posts helpful information such as a
salary index and job listings. It also e-mails new listings to a
database of 40,000 bilingual professionals, mostly in technical and
financial fields.
</P>
<P>
   _ List Foundation (www.listfoundation.org) caters mainly to
multimedia types. It lists Bay Area jobs and other information for
the South of Market crowd, including apartment classifieds and art
gallery openings.
</P>
<P>
   _ COACH (www.coachhelp.com) lists football-coaching openings as
far away as Australia and has resumes for coaches of all sports.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women in Technology International (www.witi.com) offers job
and resume databases, employer profiles and electronic networking
opportunities for women in technical fields.
</P>
<P>
   Search engines are the best way to find relevant Web sites. Dahl
said he found Funeralnet quickly by plugging in the search words
``funeral industry'' on Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Another good resource is the book Career Xroads
(www.careerxroads.com), by Gerry Crispin and Mark Mehler, which is
updated annually. The 1998 version lists the 500 top job-hunting
sites, and next year's may have as many as 700.
</P>
<P>
   Job seekers may be charged a small fee, such as $20, to post a
resume on some sites, but most get paid only by employers.
</P>
<P>
   Asia-Net, for example, charges employers $795 to e-mail job
notices to thousands of potential applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites operate their classifieds for free. Funeralnet and
Starchefs, for example, provide the ads as a service to both
employers and job seekers. Starchefs is thinking about starting to
charge, though, now that its classified section has become so
popular, said site co-founder Fern Berman.
</P>
<P>
   Career Xroads co-author Mehler advises job hunters to use
services that e-mail job notices to them, rather than posting their
resumes in Web databanks. That minimizes the chance a current
employer will come across the resume, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites will post ``blind'' resumes _ without names, home
addresses and, sometimes, current employers _ to protect job
candidates' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANY SITES
</P>
<P>
   Job postings on corporate home pages are another good way for
Web job seekers to target their searches as long as they know for
which companies they want to work.
</P>
<P>
   QVC Inc., for example, uses newspaper classifieds less often
since it began posting jobs on its Web site (www.IQVC.com). This
year, more than a quarter of new hires responded to job notices on
the corporate home page, said Jean Brown, manager of human
resources at the Westchester, Pa.-based cable network.
</P>
<P>
   IQVC's job section is getting so much traffic that QVC is
planning to launch a separate employment-related Web site, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the standard job listings, a few businesses post
interactive exercises to help job hunters evaluate whether they
would be a good fit at the company.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Texas Instruments' ``Fit Check'' (www.ti.com)
allows potential applicants to answer a range of questions on
topics such as whether they prefer a smoke-free environment,
whether they are team players and what type of corporate dress code
they like best.
</P>
<P>
   Then, TI compares the applicants' responses to the answers that
fit best with Texas Instruments' corporate policies and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting's Web site (www.ac.com) allows potential
applicants to plug in various criteria such as their area of
expertise, salary requirement, preferred city of residence and
willingness to travel. The site then churns out matches.
</P>
<P>
   To research potential employers, Mehler recommends Hoover's
Online (www.hoovers.com), a storehouse of corporate information.
E-mail addresses for human resources staff or other personnel at
your employer of choice often can be found through the HotBot
search engine (www.hotbot.com).
</P>
<P>
   Advice on laying out a resume for computer purposes can be found
at the Web site of Resumix (www.resumix.com), a maker of staffing
software.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER OPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   If the targeted Web sites don't bear fruit, Mehler suggests that
applicants check one of the mega job sites such as Monster Board,
Career Mosaic (www.careermosaic.com), Online Career Center
(www.occ.com) and Nation Job (www.nationjob.com).
</P>
<P>
   Other good sites include Job Smart (www.jobsmart.org), which
specializes in California-based jobs, and Career Path
(www.careerpath.com), an assemblage of classifieds from 58
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Recent college grads should check out JobDirect
(www.jobdirect.com), JobTrak (www.jobtrak.com), JobWeb
(www.jobweb.org) and BridgePath Employment Services
(www.bridgepath.com).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the plethora of resources available on the Web, Mehler
encourages job applicants to use conventional search techniques as
well, especially networking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is still just a tool _ it will never replace
face-to-face communication,'' Mehler said. ``I believe in three to
five years, the maximum the Web will have is 25 to 35 percent of
the job market,'' up from an estimated 3 to 5 percent today.
</P>
</TEXT>
