<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD EASE ROTH IRA INCOME-LIMIT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY DOAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
For those with annual incomes hovering near the $100,000 limit, the
conversion to Roth IRAs from traditional IRAs has been tricky. Roth
IRAs are those popular new individual retirement accounts that
offer the chance to accumulate tax-free retirement income versus
tax-deferred income for regular IRAs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   To convert a traditional IRA to a Roth, your adjusted gross
income for the year can't exceed $100,000. That can be a problem
for some investors because it's not always easy to predict what
your income will be at the end of the year, given variables such as
investments and other sources of income.
</P>
<P>
   Because IRS penalties for exceeding the income limit still are
murky, many individuals near the $100,000 income mark have
hesitated to convert their accounts, fearing potential taxes or
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   But a bill now awaiting the president's approval would allow
investors until April 15 of the following year to reverse an IRA
conversion _ with no penalties _ if their income ended up being
above the limit. The amendment is part of the IRS reform bill that
the president is expected to sign tomorrow. You can keep up with
the latest news on Roth IRAs at www.rothira.com.
</P>
<P>
   HOME OWNERSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Americans' optimism about home ownership is at a seven-year
high, according to a recent survey by Fannie Mae. About 29 percent
of those surveyed in 1998 said that not having enough cash for a
down payment and closing costs is an obstacle to buying a home.
That's down from 52 percent who cited the same obstacle in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And the percentage of respondents who named job insecurity as an
obstacle to home-buying dropped from 48 percent in 1996 to 13
percent this year. Low interest rates and continued economic growth
are driving the trends, Fannie Mae said. Fannie Mae is a private
company with a federal charter to buy mortgages from lenders and
then sell them to investors.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-CARD SCAM
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of opportunists are taking advantage of
non-U.S. citizens hoping to win in the annual green-card, or
``diversity,'' lottery, according to the State Department. The
lottery is a program that gives out 50,000 permanent resident
visas, or green cards, to natives of countries that historically
haven't had many emigrants.
</P>
<P>
   There is no charge to enter the lottery, but every year, scam
artists send out misleading information to would-be entrants,
charging up to $100 to expedite the process. You can find out more
about the legitimate entry requirements by calling the Bureau of
Consular Affairs at (800) 884-8840 (the call costs $5.10) or by
checking out http:// travel.state.gov.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG INVESTOR FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   I received many calls last week for contact information for
Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham's Young Investor Fund after last Monday's
story, ``Fund for Youngsters Appeals to Adults, Too.'' You can
phone (800) 338-2550 for a prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Amy Doan can be reached at
doana &LR; sfgate.com or by calling (415) 536-5134.
</P>
</TEXT>
