<HEADLINE>
DOOMSAYERS RANT, BUT YEAR 2000 MAY NOT BE ARMAGEDDON 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
As the end of the Millennium approaches, a few economists have
joined preachers of the apocalypse to warn that computers sent
haywire by the Year 2000 problem will drag the economy down with
them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most famous of these doomsayers is Edward Yardeni, chief
economist at Deutsche Bank Securities. He now estimates the
probability of a ``severe global Y2K recession'' at 70 percent.
Stock investors, he warns, easily could lose $1 trillion in the
resulting market collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But more-sober experts liken its probable effects to a
good-sized natural disaster _ plenty costly but far from hobbling
the economy. ``We view Y2K as a tremor, not a quake,'' said
economist Alex Patelis in a recent analysis for Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates for fixing the problem range from a low of about $50
billion (from Federal Reserve Board Governor Edward Kelley Jr.) to
$200 billion (Gartner Group). This cost, while large, represents
0.6 percent to 2.4 percent of the gross domestic product. And the
impact will be softened because it will be spread out over several
years.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of fixing or replacing defective computer code is
analogous to fixing or replacing lost bridges, highways and
buildings after an earthquake or hurricane, Patelis argues. Modern
economies have survived disasters in which costs approach those of
the so-called Y2K problem, including the Kobe earthquake ($100
billion) and Northridge temblor ($60 billion).
</P>
<P>
   Based on history and economic logic, Patelis sees several likely
aftershocks from the Y2K problem:
</P>
<P>
   _ The economy will suffer a loss of productivity as programmers
and information systems managers divert attention from other issues
to fixing or converting date fields in their software.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spending in the information sector will rise as the government
and private sector focus resources on the problem. Ironically, that
could show up in the statistics as an increase in GDP, much as
disaster-recovery spending does.
</P>
<P>
   _ The demand for specialized programmers will continue to drive
up wages in the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   _ The costs of conversion will show as lower corporate profits
or higher consumer prices _ or both.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, there will be unknown costs stemming from disruption
of institutions that fail to convert their systems in time. But
most programmers are focusing on fixing critical applications
first, so the disruption should be minimized.
</P>
<P>
   Unless many more computers fail than expected when Jan. 1, 2000,
rolls around, ``The impact would be similar to the economic effects
of a snowstorm,'' said Rick Egelton, an economist at Harris
Bank/Bank of Montreal. He predicts ``a temporary reduction in sales
as suppliers are unable to produce or deliver their products and
consumers are unable to spend because paychecks have been
delayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Patelis notes that the current economic expansion has chugged
along unperturbed by the 1994 Northridge earthquake, the 22-day
closure of the federal government in December 1995 and the shutdown
of the Northeast by winter storms in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economies are resilient and can adjust quickly to temporary
shocks,'' Patelis concludes, ``especially when such shocks are
anticipated, as is the case with Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GAP WIDENS
</P>
<P>
   As if caught on the wrong side of an economic fault line, most
California workers are losing ground relative to the rest of the
country as their wages continue to slip.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the median (middle-ranking) worker in California made
$11.43 an hour, a drop (adjusted for inflation) of 1.5 percent over
1996. By contrast, the median worker nationally gained 2.4 percent,
to earn $10.82 an hour in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the median worker in only five states made more than
the median wage in California. But California's median has
plummeted 11 percent since then, adjusted for inflation, putting 13
states ahead of it.
</P>
<P>
   California paychecks shrank in the face of the state's unusually
long and steep recession earlier this decade. The effects of that
recession still are felt in California's unemployment rate, which
at 5.7 percent is much higher than the national rate of 4.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The tight labor market has done wonders for low-paid workers in
the rest of the country. Last year, real hourly wages of workers at
the 20th percentile of pay jumped 3 percent, according to new
tabulations by the Economic Policy Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But in California, wages of relatively poor workers fell nearly
1 percent last year. Their economic plight has been compounded,
among other factors, by growing numbers of low-skilled immigrants
who put pressure on the low end of the state's labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``California wages at the middle and bottom both took a big hit
in the 1990s,'' said Economic Policy Institute economist Jared
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is doing badly in California. Data from the
Franchise Tax Board, recently released by the state Assembly Select
Committee on the California Middle Class _ no kidding about that
name _ shows that 40,000 taxpayers declared incomes of $1 million
to $25 million in 1996, up from 23,000 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And an amazing 376 taxpayers _ termed ``Supernova earners'' by
the committee _ declared incomes of $25 million or more, nearly
triple the number in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 study by the Public Policy Institute of California found
a sharp rise in income inequality in California during the past 30
years, particularly since 1980. By 1989, only five states,
including Arkansas and Louisiana, had a wider gap between rich and
poor households.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Marshall can be reached by e-mail at
marshall &LR; sfgate.com. This is his last On Economics column at The
Chronicle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
