<HEADLINE>
MCCARRON WINS THREE STAKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Chris McCarron is about to win the Hollywood
Park riding title. Or is it the Hollywood Park Film Festival?
</P>
<P>
   McCarron, a 43-year-old Hall of Famer, credits morning study
sessions in the officials' film room for his return to the top of
the local jockey standings. And Sunday he added to his personal
highlight reel by winning three stakes, one short of the national
record for a single card, to take a 52-50 lead over Corey Nakatani
into closing day.
</P>
<P>
   While Nakatani went winless Sunday, McCarron rode Old Trieste to
a fabulous, 12-length victory in the Swaps Stakes, and won aboard
Uncaged Fury in the Answer Do, and Spirited Jacklyn in the Valkyr
Handicap. McCarron didn't ride in the Sunset Handicap, won by River
Bay and Alex Solis, or the Hollywood Juvenile Championship, won by
Yes It's True and Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I no longer start a meet thinking, `I want to be leading
rider,''' said McCarron, whose 1995 Del Mar title was his last of
24 in California. ``I concentrate more on the quality of my mounts
than the quantity.... But when I'm in contention, my competitive
juices get going.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hollywood Park's 67-day meet, ``I started with a bang and my
adrenaline started flowing.'' So, in addition to exercising horses
six mornings a week, he spent from 20 to 90 minutes each racing day
analyzing tapes of his upcoming mounts and their competition.
</P>
<P>
   In the $500,000 Swaps, though, the difference wasn't study, it
was the early speed of Old Trieste, who put away his 3-year-old
opponents on the turn to embarrass Grand Slam, Old Topper and
slow-starting fifth-place finisher Shot of Gold. Look out for Old
Trieste at any distance short of 1\ miles.
</P>
<P>
   Today, McCarron rides four horses, including favored Sam's in
the Robert K. Kerlan Memorial Handicap, and Nakatani six.
</P>
<P>
   Among trainers, meanwhile, Craig Dollase got his 19th winner,
Six Point Eight, clinching at least a tie for his first title.
Sandy Shulman has 16 and three horses today.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Del Mar's opening feature Wednesday, the Oceanside for
3-year-olds without a stakes win, overflowed with entries and was
divided for the 10th straight year and the 15th of 18.... Today
marks the last major-track thoroughbred racing in Los Angeles
County for 10 weeks _ until Oak Tree at Santa Anita opens Sept. 30.
Del Mar will be followed by minor-league Fairplex Park, Sept.
10-27....
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick edged Tomorrows Cat in the 1 1/16-mile Long
Branch Breeders' Cup Stakes at Monmouth. It was the first start for
the 1997 Horse of the Year since he ran eighth in the Kentucky
Derby.... Santa Anita-based Classic Cat won the Ohio Derby in a
photo over One Bold Stroke at Thistledown. Shane Sellers rode....
Hollywood Park will finish with a track record for average daily
wagering, $11 million, up 8 percent from 1997. Chairman R.D.
Hubbard said the increase more than makes up for declines of 2
percent in on-track wagering and 4 percent in on-track attendance.
</P>
</TEXT>
