<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BECOME A STAR IN THE WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
OK, so your thighs are too thick, your brows are too bushy and your
diction too drawling to ever make it as a Hollywood star.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But you _ in fact, almost anyone _ still can be a star at work.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message of a new book by Robert E. Kelley, a Carnegie
Mellon University professor who spent 10 years researching the
kinds of people who are considered star performers in their
workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a slew of books out there by self-styled career
gurus offering up their personal tips on how to succeed in the
business world.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelley's effort was different because he attempted to survey
_ objectively and scientifically _ the actual common
characteristics of star performers.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley went in assuming that workplace stars all would share
some common personality traits _ such as above-average
intelligence, driving ambition, willingness to work 14-hour days,
or good schmoozing skills. He assumed that workplace stars were
born, not made.
</P>
<P>
   The results completely shocked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After testing, we found no difference between stars and
average performers in any of these (personality) categories,'' said
Kelley, whose book is titled, ``How to Be a Star at Work'' (Times
Books, $25). ``The day I had to go in and tell the sponsors of my
research that we hadn't come up with anything was a very, very sad
day in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   His assumptions blown to smithereens, Kelley switched gears. He
took another look at his research data and concluded that stars did
in fact have something in common _ but it wasn't personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (initial setback) forced us to stop focusing on what
people bring to the party and focus instead on how they do their
jobs,'' he said. ``What we discovered is that stars are made, not
born. They have a fundamentally different conception of what work
is.''
</P>
<P>
   So you, too, can be one of your company's stars _ even if you're
not a 180-IQ, Type A, Harvard graduate with the glad-handing skills
of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Just what do you have to do?
</P>
<P>
   Kelley singles out nine specific work strategies common to star
performers, whether they're white-collar computer executives or
blue-collar telephone repair people.
</P>
<P>
   The strategies at first sound cliched _ not very different from
the conventional advice offered up by many other career gurus.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelley says star performers implement this advice in very
different ways from average performers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what he calls the nine ``breakthrough strategies'' of
star employees:
</P>
<P>
   _ Initiative _ Average performers think that they're taking
initiative when they come up with a faster or better way to do
their job.
</P>
<P>
   Star performers go beyond that _ excelling at their own work but
also coming up with new ideas outside the bounds of their own job
that help the company achieve its most important goals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Networking _ Average performers think of networking as
something to do at cocktail parties in order to find a new job. But
star performers use networking as a way to do their current job
better _ sharing information with knowledgeable people who can help
them get things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Average performers wait until they need some information, then
cold-call someone to get it,'' Kelley said. ``Stars know that you
can't get work done today without a knowledge network and that
you've got to put it in place beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Self-management _ Average performers think that they're
managing their time well if their desk is clean, their DayTimer is
full and their projects are being finished on time. Star performers
look at a bigger picture _ figuring out which parts of their work
are most important to the company's success and to their own
careers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Average performers spend a lot of time checking their to-do
list, while stars spend more time figuring out what should be ON
their to-do list,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perspective _ Average performers tend to see things from their
own points of view. Stars are able to view things from a variety of
different angles _ from the viewpoint of their boss, co-workers,
clients and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good followers _ We tend to think of stars as leaders, but
everyone's got to be a follower sometimes, too. Star performers
know how to work cooperatively with a leader even when there are
personality differences. They continue to be creative and use
independent judgment even when they're not in charge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leadership _ Average performers often think that being a
leader requires huge amounts of charisma, vision or at least a
corner office. But star performers lead by knowing how to bring out
the best in other people, even without a high-ranking job title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most stars don't have the power to hire or fire or give
raises,'' Kelley said. ``So they try to understand, `What do the
people following me get out of it?' They pay real close attention
to the needs of their followers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Teamwork _ Everyone talks about teams these days, but star
performers are selective about what kinds of workplace teams to
join. They try to avoid meetings-for-meetings'-sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``When stars ARE on a team,'' Kelley said, ``they pay very close
attention to the team and whether it's accomplishing its goals.
They make sure there are periodic checkpoints, that people are on
board. They make commitments and deliver on them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Organizational savvy _ Many average performers turn up their
noses at office politics as something dirty. Stars avoid needless
involvement in workplace melodramas, but they pay close attention
to how their organization works. They identify the competing
interests within their company, and how to manage those interests
to achieve their work goals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Show-and-tell _ The workplace of the 1990s requires people to
present their ideas to groups more than ever before. Star
performers have the skills to get their points across _ whether at
a formal meeting or around the water cooler. Or if they really
don't feel comfortable making presentations, they team up with a
buddy who can handle that part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, employees also must have the basic skills and
intelligence needed to do their job before they can even think
about becoming a star.
</P>
<P>
   If someone's never been any good with numbers, even the greatest
teamwork or leadership abilities won't make him or her into a star
accountant.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelley said his research should send an encouraging message
not just to employees, but to their managers: There's no innate
gene for workplace stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that when people learned these work strategies,
within a year their productivity rates went up 100 percent,''
Kelley said. ``Theoretically, it's possible that everyone can be a
star performer. And even if they don't become a star, they can
still improve their performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
