<HEADER>
A2553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-35     07-19 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD TRIP ROBS YANKS OF THEIR USUAL GUSTO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The dog days of August do not officially begin for a
couple of weeks, but the New York Yankees' play on Sunday had that
dog-days feel to it, a staleness, as if they had been standing in
the sun too long.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Yankees may or may not prove to be one of the great
clubs of this century, but on Sunday they played like just another
team at the end of a long road trip, losing to Toronto, 9-3. Andy
Pettitte (12-6) allowed three home runs _ Jose Canseco hit two of
them _ in his first defeat in seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As they begin a weeklong homestand Monday with a double-header
against the Detroit Tigers, the Yankees have a 92-game record of
68-24, which is one victory behind that of the 1902 Pittsburgh
Pirates. The Yankees will play 42 of their final 70 games at Yankee
Stadium, where they have won 33 of 39 so far.
</P>
<P>
   They respond to most losses with indignation, but as they packed
their bags Sunday, they seemed relieved, mostly. Some of the
Yankees have not been home since before the All-Star Game break;
Derek Jeter joked that he could not remember his way back to his
apartment. ``I'm going to see the Empire State Building,'' Jeter
said, like an excited tourist. ``The Statue of Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said: ``I can't wait to get home. This has been a long
trip, man. Four cities. We had a great trip.''
</P>
<P>
   They won seven of 11 overall. But, as Manager Joe Torre noted,
it ended poorly, three losses in the last four games. They made
more mistakes Sunday than they usually do in a week, and in spite
of the one-sided final score, there were a handful of moments when
the Yankees could have turned the game in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   They forced Woody Williams (9-4), Toronto's starting pitcher,
into throwing 37 pitches in the first two innings and then loaded
the bases with nobody out in the third. Bernie Williams, batting
with a full count, got a shoulder-high fastball _ and swung and
missed, a strikeout that crippled the rally; the Yankees mustered
just one run. ``A bad at-bat,'' said the Yankees' center fielder.
``A terrible at-bat.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pettitte had great stuff and great control in the first two
innings, retiring six straight batters, overmatching Toronto, a
poor offensive team. A shutout seemed within the realm of
possibility. After a double and a walk in the third, Toronto had
two on and one out, and Tony Phillips at the plate. Pettitte fired
a fastball past Phillips for strike three, and with the runners
moving, catcher Joe Girardi threw to third, the ball beating
Toronto's Craig Grebeck. Inning over, Pettitte thought, pumping a
fist as he turned and headed for the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   But Grebeck was called safe by Mark Johnson, the third-base
umpire. Scott Brosius, the third baseman, argued the call along
with Torre, but Brosius acknowledged that his own movement may have
confused Johnson: Brosius had delayed his break to the third-base
bag because of the 3-2 count to Phillips, and then tripped,
catching the ball off balance as a result, and made the tag with a
lunge rather than being set and deft with his tag. ``It may have
looked funny to him,'' Brosius said, ``because I was stumbling and
bumbling.''
</P>
<P>
   With first base open, Pettitte worked around Shannon Stewart,
issuing a four-pitch walk to get to Canseco. Pettitte was confident
he could retire Canseco with inside fastballs. Pettitte fell behind
two balls and no strikes, then tried throwing a fastball inside. He
missed his target, leaving the ball over the plate. Canseco, his
biceps twitching below his shirt sleeves, hammered the ball over
the wall in left, a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very satisfying at-bat,'' said Canseco,
offended that Pettitte preferred to pitch to him rather than
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on it later, Pettitte said he might have lost his
concentration after believing he had been out of the inning on
Girardi's throw to third. Maybe, he said, he just lost his focus.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Pettitte gave up seven walks, matching a
career high, and two additional home runs, monster shots. In the
fifth inning, Carlos Delgado became the first left-handed hitter to
drive a ball into the upper deck at the Skydome, a 469-footer, and
in the seventh, Canseco launched a ball off the facing of the fifth
deck in left field, 460 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Chad Curtis was picked off second in the fourth
inning, and an inning later, the same thing happened to Paul
O'Neill, Girardi throwing a towel in the dugout in frustration.
Mistakes were acknowledged afterward, but nobody seemed in the mood
for self-examination. The road warriors had run out of gas, and
they were ready to go home, finally.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' first-base coach, was hit in the
right side of his head by an errant throw in the fifth inning and
went down, frightened that he was hit in the same place where he
fractured his skull six years ago. In 1992 Cardenal was hit by a
batted ball as he was working with a Cincinnati minor-league
player, and with his life in jeopardy, he was rushed to a hospital.
A plate was inserted into the right side of his head, at about the
same spot where he was hit Sunday. Cardenal was replaced by Chris
Chambliss before the sixth inning, but he reported only a light
headache after the game and made a few jokes at his own expense.
... Orlando Hernandez may start against Detroit on Wednesday with
three days' rest, if Ramiro Mendoza is needed in relief during
Monday's double-header.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
