<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DIARY:
</P>
<P>
   I was early for my tennis game at Central Park and decided to
look at the skirts in the tennis house shop. I took one to the
women's locker room, where two women, probably in their 70s,
scrutinized me as I tried it on.
</P>
<P>
   One of them said, ``Nice, how much does it cost?'' I replied,
``$45.'' Both frowned and the second woman said I should wait for
the sales or try the new sports store that replaced a Woolworth's.
``Why are you telling her to go there _ it's expensive,'' the first
woman said. The two then began a back and forth and I was obviously
irrelevant. I escaped, returned the skirt, met my partner and went
to our court.
</P>
<P>
   We began playing, and a half-hour later I looked up and noticed
the two women were on an adjacent court. After I retrieved a ball
for one of them, she looked at me and said, ``The way you play
tennis, buy the skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   _JUDITH STEIN
</P>
<P>
   Amy Hanan's friend, ``a lady of certain age,'' had searched,
without success, for a bathing suit with an overskirt that gently
grazed the thighs. Finally, to her delight, she saw the perfect
suit in a SoHo store window. She dashed into the store and
addressed the 20-something salesclerk. ``That bathing suit in the
window, do you have it in a size 14?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   The young saleswoman was incredulous. ``Madam,'' she said.
``That's a dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Goldreich reports that Kenneth Abrahami, a friend, took a
taxi in lower Manhattan and asked to be taken to the Jewish Museum.
He read a newspaper during the trip and looked up when the driver
informed him that they had arrived. They were outside the
Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I asked to be taken to the Jewish Museum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, this isn't a Jewish museum?'' the driver replied
indignantly.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the little boy next door, who was reputed to be a
fussy eater, watched me work in my vegetable garden. As he kneeled
beside me one day, I tried to tempt him into picking a fresh snack.
Pointing out various vegetables, I said, ``This is how yummy
tomatoes grow; these are crunchy cucumbers,'' and so on with
lettuce, carrots and green beans. He said ``no'' to everything, so
I gave up and continued weeding.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes passed before he thought of a plant he was willing
to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does the pizza grow?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   _SARA NUSS-GALLES
</P>
<P>
   FOR BONNARD
</P>
<P>
   come back Pierre
</P>
<P>
   bathe me in crimson, scarlet and vermilion
</P>
<P>
   splash me with emerald green
</P>
<P>
   wash my hands in chinese white
</P>
<P>
   splatter Naples yellow
</P>
<P>
   paint my toes in cerulean
</P>
<P>
   dry me wrapped in fuchsia
</P>
<P>
   wipe my neck with pink and peaches
</P>
<P>
   lie with me on your dressing gown
</P>
<P>
   thick with burgundy and light
</P>
<P>
   look out shuttered windows into
</P>
<P>
   burnt sienna and green earth
</P>
<P>
   _MARIE M. SMITH
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement earlier this year for the restaurant Palio
featured a ``pre-fixe'' lunch. Flora Lazar telephoned and pointed
out that the correct spelling was ``prix fixe.'' The man at the
other end of the line wasn't concerned, she reported. ``Oh, madam,
don't worry,'' he replied, ``we're not a French restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   The man and woman approaching the Henry Hudson Bridge were each
on a motorcycle. As the lanes split for people paying with cash or
an E-Z Pass, the woman headed for cash and the man toward E-Z Pass.
Michael Golden and his wife, Anne, driving alongside, were curious.
Did the man have his pass fastened to his chest or his helmet? As
they watched in the rear-view mirror, the man unzipped his jacket,
reached for the E-Z Pass, put it in his mouth and zoomed without
problem through the toll.
</P>
<P>
   If this isn't the Catch-22 School of Instruction, what is? On
one wall of Valerie Anderson's local post office, the sign read,
``To see the manager, you must have an appointment.'' On the
opposite wall, another sign read, ``To get an appointment, you must
see the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Lieber was waiting in line in the ladies' room of a
theater when she heard the following exchange.
</P>
<P>
   First woman: ``So, are you a widow?''
</P>
<P>
   Second woman: ``No, I'm divorced _ but I would be. He's dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My 90-year-old mother and I were visiting my son. As we started
to go out to dinner, my son said, ``Just a minute, Grandma, I have
to read my mail.'' The two of them went into his computer room and
she stood by as he pulled up his mail. As we walked out the door to
go to dinner, she turned to me and asked, ``How did he open the
envelopes?''
</P>
<P>
   _ALBERT D. WOOD
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Dickler and her husband, Gerry, both in their 80s, were
almost at their destination on a Fifth Avenue bus when a
thunderstorm erupted, the rain coming down in torrents. No sooner
had she suggested that they run for and take any shelter they could
find, than a young man on the bus thrust his umbrella into
Dickler's hand and a business card into his breast pocket.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Dickler demurred, the good Samaritan said, ``Don't
worry, I'll get a beer until it stops and you can send the umbrella
back when you get a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The card read ``Andy Robson'' and he did get his umbrella back.
The Dicklers are convinced that he's the New York version of Sir
Galahad.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Donte recently had a very short haircut that brought out
the natural curl in her hair. As she stepped into the elevator in
her building, another passenger looked at her admiringly and asked,
``Where did you get those curls?''
</P>
<P>
   ``God,'' Ms. Donte replied.
</P>
<P>
   Not skipping a beat, the other woman asked, ``Are they on the
Upper West Side?''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor's waiting room was crowded and the rambunctious and
very vocal 3-year-old was annoying everyone. Evelyn Chapman pegged
the mother as an obvious New Age parent. The woman followed her son
as he roamed around the room, repeatedly admonishing him with
``Please, Brian, you must remember to shout quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Recently, three friends and I headed to Chelsea to check out the
new trendy bar Lot 61. A polite bouncer informed us that he could
admit only people with reservations.
</P>
<P>
   We conferred under our umbrellas near the roped-off entrance.
``So, let's make a reservation,'' one of the men suggested. The
other took out his cellular phone, dialed and handed the phone to
me. The woman who answered took the reservation with no hesitation
and agreed to give my name to the doorman. We waited 10 minutes to
be safe, returned to the doorman and entered the hallowed chamber,
leaving a cluster of shivering, reservationless people behind.
</P>
<P>
   _KAREN ANGEL
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
