<SLUG> BC-RAC-FAVORITE-TRICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVORITE TRICK REDISCOVERS WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Favorite Trick, the 1997 juvenile champion and Horse of the
Year, won the Long Branch Stakes by a head at Monmouth Park in
Oceanport, N.J., Sunday in his first appearance since he finished
eighth in the Kentucky Derby two and a half months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not run with breakaway speed, nor did he shake off
the colt stalking him the entire route, Tomorrows Cat, who has won
only two races in his career. And Bill Mott, who trains Favorite
Trick, said he still was not sure where his champion would run
next.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile at Belmont Park, in Elmont, N.Y., Parade Ground, who
ran sixth in the Derby, made a successful transition from dirt
racing to grass racing when he won the Lexington Stakes by a length
and a half over Ay Rouge. His trainer, Neil Howard, said that he
was not ruling out a return to dirt at times, but ``this race
serves as a sign as to what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight at Monmouth fell entirely on Favorite Trick, who
won all eight of his starts as a 2-year-old, won the Eclipse Award
as the juvenile champion and then was voted Horse of the Year over
Skip Away. He was the first juvenile champion to win both honors
since Secretariat in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   But this season has been a struggle. He won the Swale Stakes at
Gulfstream Park in March, but then suffered his first defeat when
he ran third in the Arkansas Derby in April, and then lost again in
the Kentucky Derby in May.
</P>
<P>
   Mott, who became his trainer this year when Patrick Byrne became
an exclusive trainer for Frank Stronach of Canada, has handled the
champion with care, pointing out that he had distance limitations.
The Long Branch, at a mile and one-sixteenth, probably offered his
best distance. But the $1 million Haskell on Aug. 9 at Monmouth and
the $250,000 Jim Dandy at Saratoga on the same day both are run at
a mile and an eighth. The Travers, on Aug. 29, is run at a mile and
one-quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick raced stride for stride Sunday with Tomorrows
Cat, a 3-year-old son of Storm Cat, and they entered the
homestretch still locked in a duel. They stayed that way until
Favorite Trick prevailed by the length of his head, with Arctic
Sweep third and Eastern Daydream fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick, who paid $2.40 on a $2 bet to win as the
favorite, ran the mile and a sixteenth under Pat Day in 1 minute 43
seconds, which was almost three seconds slower than Formal Gold ran
it when he set the Monmouth track record last August.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his disposition and temperament, not to run away from
horses,'' Mott said. ``But he's a good horse, a class horse, and he
deserves to win. We want to preserve his reputation. He didn't draw
away in the stretch, but I think he knew all along that he had the
other horse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mott was less certain about the next chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next week,'' he said, ``I'll sit down with the owner,
Joseph LaCombe, and decide. We'll give the Haskell serious
consideration. It's one of the chief reasons we came here for this
race. But it's only one of several options we have in the month of
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can go a mile and an eighth, but it's probably not his best
distance. And one and a quarter is beyond his realm, so I don't
expect him to run in the Travers.''
</P>
<P>
   Parade Ground, the winner of the Lexington, had run 12 times on
dirt, never on grass. He had won three of his races and finished in
the money 10 times. He ran third in the Wood Memorial in April,
sixth in the Derby in May, third in the Peter Pan three weeks later
and fourth in the Belmont Stakes. But he was a fast closer with
speed in his pedigree from his sire, Kingmambo, and his mare,
Battle Creek Girl. So Howard decided to try him on the turf.
</P>
<P>
   After running a tight second for most of a mile, Parade Ground
took charge as they turned for home and was a length and a half in
front of Ay Rouge at the end, with La Reine's Terms two and a
quarter lengths back in third. The winner ran the mile and a
quarter on the inner turf course in 2:00 2/5. The favorite, he
returned $5.50 for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran a dynamite race,'' said Mike Smith, the jockey, ``and
he definitely took a liking to the turf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
