<HEADLINE>
A VICTORY IN MAHWAH IS A BOOST FOR GRAF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAHWAH, N.J. _ The situation was hardly unfamiliar to Steffi
Graf, standing before an adoring crowd at center court with an
oversized champion's trophy in her hands. But the first question
asked while she stood there seemed to catch her off guard. It
seemed simple enough, ``Is Graf back?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She laughed nervously, finding it hard, as she held the silver
trophy, to do anything but admit, ``I am, I guess.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graf impressively disposed of Amanda Coetzer, 6-3, 6-3, in the
A&AMP;P Classic today at Crossroads Center before a sellout crowd of
7,101.
</P>
<P>
   Winning an exhibition is hardly the sort of accomplishment that
would falsely raise the hopes of a player who has been on top of
her sport longer than any other woman in tennis history,
particularly since Graf has won the Mahwah tournament six times,
while no other player has won here more than twice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for Graf, who missed eight months after knee surgery, this
marked the first victory since her return, providing a much-needed
boost of confidence. Her time away dropped her ranking to the
unfamiliar territory of No. 57.
</P>
<P>
   The victory over Coetzer, who is ranked No. 8 and who beat Graf
three times in 1997, offered hope.
</P>
<P>
   Still, inside the interview room shortly after the match, Graf
acknowledged the reality of her comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the beginning,'' Graf said. ``I arrived on Wednesday,
so I think I made the best out of these few days. I couldn't expect
to come here and win all three matches, especially today. I haven't
really felt that great, and I haven't been in the heat for quite
some time. But it's a great way to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the percentage thing, it's so American,'' she said,
laughing again. ``I'm 85, 80 percent. I don't know. It doesn't
concern me. I've felt like in another one or two weeks, another
tournament, I think I'll be where I want to be.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graf has three more tournaments lined up as a prelude to the
U.S. Open, hoping that the return to match play will get her ready
for the rigors of the Grand Slam event. She opted to pass on
playing in the Federation Cup, choosing instead to remain in the
United States and continue her rehabilitation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the competitor in Graf has set her sights on the U.S.
Open, wondering aloud whether she can be a factor again, she
asserted again day that she will not judge her comeback on rankings
or titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a long break,'' she said. ``The good thing about
winning everything before, you don't have to prove anything
anymore. I've done this many times before. What I can enjoy out
there now is to enjoy myself. That's a privilege I have. I'm not
going for titles. Obviously I want to do well, no question about
it. But there is not a number in my mind or a certain amount of
titles.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to convince Coetzer of that. The 26-year-old
South African struggled with her own serve and could see little
evidence of any injury or layoff in Graf. After defeating No.
2-ranked Jana Novotna on Friday to reach the final, she found
herself run around the court by Graf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some of what she had before,'' Coetzer said. ``I thought
her serve was really, really good, and she moved really well. Both
of us made a lot of errors, and both of us have to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``She's got so much pride, and no matter where she's
playing, she's not going to go out and lose. I really respect that.
That's a good thing. It's nice to see that somebody doesn't play
for money.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This exhibition was marred by a number of players opting out,
with Anna Kournikova and Mirjana Lucic withdrawing during the week
because of injury and illness, as well as the embarrassment of the
winner of the USTA Challenger Tournament, Amy Frazier, choosing to
skip an invitation to play in the Classic.
</P>
<P>
   So Graf's performance was a welcome change, playing through her
rehabilitation as well as a sinus infection that prevented her from
flying to New Jersey until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often been proud to go through a variety of injuries and
difficulties and been able to prevail,'' Graf said. ``I've very
proud of that. I've always had that. That's the good thing about
this sport, you always have to challenge yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
