<SLUG> BC-BBA-SMITH-COLUMN-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: IT'S NOT ART, BUT THAT'S AL WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In summing up one of the uglier victories of the season on
Saturday, Texas Manager Johnny Oates captured the essence of the
division affectionately known as the American League Worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't artistic, but we'll take it,'' Oates aptly told
reporters after watching his Rangers commit two errors, give up one
passed ball and leave nine men on base, but survive, 9-8, in 10
innings against the visiting Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   What is artistic about the AL West? If you want art, look to the
Braves or the Yankees. If you want herculean performances, look to
the Indians, the Astros, the Padres. If you want superstars, think
Mark McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr., Sammy Sosa and Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   AL West clubs have players on record-breaking paces, like
Seattle's Griffey, who leads the league with 39 home runs, and Juan
Gonzalez of Texas, who leads the majors with 103 runs batted in.
Yet those feats cannot camouflage the pedestrian nature of what the
teams are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Oakland Athletics, young and lacking expectations, can
be considered a pleasant surprise. They are the only third-place
team in the majors with a single-digit deficit. While the A's good
fortune has a lot to do with promising youngsters like Ben Grieve,
it has more to do with the underachievers surrounding them.
</P>
<P>
   What is unfolding in central Texas, on Walt Disney's diamond in
Anaheim and in the Pacific Northwest doesn't inspire praise. Not
when the three top teams seem capable of ruling the division yet
appear incapable of seizing the opportunity. The division-leading
Angels had won just four of their last 15 games leading into Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The offense has been stunted, as shown by the Angels' inability
to score more than four runs in six of their first 10 games after
the All-Star Game break. It is why the disappointing Cecil Fielder
has been benched and why frustrated Manager Terry Collins looks
like a juggler with his lineup as he tries to shake a teamwide
slump.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels seem unable to avoid the jinx that has dogged the
team throughout its history, avidly illustrated when the team
managed to blow a double-digit division lead in early August 1995.
The Angels eventually lost a one-game playoff with the Mariners,
who had trailed by 13 games as late as Aug. 2 only to rally in what
became the fourth-largest comeback in major-league history.
</P>
<P>
   Not even changing the team's name from the California Angels to
the Anaheim Angels has provided enough camouflage to hide this team
from ill fates. Consider Chuck Finley. The Angels' top pitcher was
expected to miss his next start because of a cut on his right knee
from his last game. On Saturday, while sitting in the dugout, he
was injured when he was hit in the right arm by a line drive foul
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Angels are hanging on to first, thanks mostly to the
fact that second-place Texas is also treading water, losing five
straight before beating Tampa Bay on Friday and Saturday. The
Angels and Rangers have looked more like weary shadowboxers than
true contenders, with the Angels clinging to a half-game lead
heading into Sunday night's game.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Rangers' struggles go beyond bad luck. The pitching went
belly up after an impressive spring. John Wetteland, a usually
reliable reliever, has blown four of his last 17 save
opportunities, including one Saturday against Tampa Bay, forcing
the game into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gonzalez is performing poorly. The main piston in the
Rangers' offense, Gonzalez's 101 runs batted in in the first half
of the season appeared to make him a lock to surpass Hack Wilson's
RBI record of 190. But Gonzalez did not collect another RBI until
Saturday when he twice doubled in a run, breaking a nine-game
drought.
</P>
<P>
   If the Texas heat and league pitching combine to wilt Gonzalez
in that category, it could devastate the Rangers. The club is 18-27
in games in which Gonzalez does not drive in at least one run,
including 4-5 since the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are also heavily dependent on offense in lieu of
consistent pitching. And that offense has ignited a glimmer of
pennant fever on a team that allowed its pitching to all but bury
it in the cellar in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey and Alex Rodriguez stand 1-2 in the league in home runs
with 39 and 30, respectively. Griffey, pursuing Roger Maris'
single-season record of 61 home runs, has been scorching the ball,
with 25 hits and 17 RBIs in his last 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, feeding off their leader, rang up 26 runs and 36
hits in the team's first two games against the Royals over the
weekend, but had only one run and four hits in Sunday's 4-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion at the plate had resulted in six straight
victories for Seattle before Sunday's loss. The Mariners, who were
16 games out on June 30, had made up seven games in the standings.
before failing to sweep the Royals. The Mariners entered play
Sunday just nine games behind the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mariners hinting at another historic second-half
charge, and the Angels fiddling while their lead burns around them,
the West may once again provide baseball's most intriguing race.
Artistic? No, but it seems this is the only way the AL Worst knows
how to perform as its teams backpedal toward a destiny under
constant threat of devaluation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
