<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GEYELIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY R. GEYELIN, 79, ORGANIZER OF FLOTILLA FOR BICENTENNIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Rawle Geyelin Jr., a retired New York business executive
who helped start Operation Sail for the 1976 Bicentennial and the
tall ships' birthday salute to the Statue of Liberty in 1986, died
July 5 at his home in Manhattan. He was 79 and also had a home in
Seal Harbor, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Geyelin retired in 1988 as president of the Council of the
Americas in Manhattan, a business affiliate of the broader based
Americas Society. He had assumed leadership of the council as
executive vice president in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The council, founded in 1965, is a forum for the consideration
of economic, political and social issues from Canada to South
America. When he took over, Geyelin was involved in Chase Manhattan
Bank's overseas operations as vice president in the international
department and executive secretary of the international advisory
committee.
</P>
<P>
   He was an originator of the idea for Operation Sail to celebrate
the country's 200th birthday with an international flotilla of tall
ships in New York Harbor and up the Hudson River, and he played a
leading role in its planning.
</P>
<P>
   He took part in getting the tall ships under sail for the 100th
anniversary of the Statue of Liberty. Geyelin was a great-nephew of
Emma Lazarus, whose sonnet ``The New Colossus'' is engraved on the
statue's pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Manhattan, he graduated from Yale University in 1939
after majoring in American history. After his discharge from the
Navy, in which he served as an officer in Cuba and the Pacific in
World War II, he was an advertising executive at the Metropolitan
Life Insurance Co. He joined Chase in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former member of the Council on Foreign Relations and a
director of the Americas Society.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his daughter, Antoinette Hoar of Manhattan; a
brother, Peter, of Philadelphia; a sister, Patricia Drexel of
Northeast Harbor, Maine, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
