<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOLSON-INDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZANARDI OVERCOMES A LOT TO WIN HIS FOURTH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Alex Zanardi overcame an engine failure, a rare
driving mistake that caused him to spin, and several very close
calls in a most improbable and dramatic victory on Sunday in the
Molson Indy.
</P>
<P>
   With an aggressive pass of Michael Andretti with two laps left,
Zanardi emerged with a victory on a road course that curls along
the banks of Lake Ontario in the shadows of Toronto's skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a record-tying fourth straight triumph and the sixth this
season for Zanardi, the defending Championship Auto Racing Teams
champion. He now has an almost insurmountable 69-point lead in this
season's points race. Andretti took second, and Zanardi's teammate,
Jimmy Vasser, finished third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything happened to me today,'' said Zanardi, who tied Al
Unser Jr.'s 1990 record for consecutive victories. ``I spun. I got
stuck behind an accident. I had problems with my brakes, my tires
and my engine. And still I'm here with another victory. I'm almost
sorry for all of the luck I'm having.''
</P>
<P>
   Zanardi, who won by 1.92 seconds, was lucky. But it was a
combination of luck and his ability behind the wheel that won him
the race.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 laps left, Zanardi was in fourth place, and did not seem
to have the handling or the power to move up. His red Reynard Honda
was sliding through the hairpin turns, and Dario Franchitti of
Britain was driving away from the field, leading by 11 seconds. But
it was then that Zanardi got the break he needed. Franchitti, the
pole-winner for the second straight year, lost control of his car
in Turn 1, the same turn where he crashed on the first lap in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti, who finished 20th, was horizontal, his green Reynard
Honda blocking the middle of the track just beyond the turn. First,
Andretti came speeding around the corner, saw Franchitti and got by
on the left. Then, Vasser did the same, clipping the nose of
Franchitti's car. Finally, there was Zanardi, who, heeding the
advice of his car owner, Chip Ganassi, steered right, overtaking
Vasser for second place.
</P>
<P>
   So now, with Vasser's tires ruined and Franchitti out of the
race, it came down to two cars _ those of Andretti and Zanardi.
</P>
<P>
   Despite handling problems, Andretti, in his black Kmart
Swift-Ford/Cosworth, was able to hold off Zanardi until Lap 93 of
95, when at the entrance to Turn 3, Zanardi boldly dived to the
inside. Andretti locked all four wheels, allowing Zanardi to make a
spectacular pass and accelerate out of the turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had made a mistake,'' Andretti said, ``then I would be
upset. I drove OK, but it wasn't enough. I did the best I could
with the equipment I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Zanardi's day surely ended better than it had begun. His engine
failed during the morning practice, and he was forced to borrow a
backup engine from Franchitti's team.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not all that threatened Zanardi on Sunday. On Lap
63, Zanardi spun out of control while challenging Vasser for third
place. Several times before that, he almost lost control while
pushing his car past its limit.
</P>
<P>
   For a second straight year, Franchitti was driving the best car
but wasted the opportunity to get his first victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' Franchitti said. ``I just can't believe it.
The brakes were a worry all day. When I spun in Turn 1, I caught
the throttle as I was braking. It's really disappointing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
