<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST KNOCKDOWN BREAKS THE MONOTONY FOR JONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roy Jones Jr. has six-pack stomach muscles, the
biceps of a weight-lifter and the knockout record of a marauder.
But before Saturday night's light heavyweight title fight, he had a
dream: the soft-punching Lou DelValle would knock him down.
</P>
<P>
   This was an odd premonition. For the way Jones tells it, he has
not been knocked off his feet since he was a 12-year-old holding
the heavy punching bag for a heavyweight fighter in his hometown of
Pensacola, Fla. The puncher hit the bag, the bag hit Jones, and the
next thing he knew, he was looking up. That was 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when the next knockdown blow came on Saturday night in the
eighth round of Jones' victory before a raucous crowd at Madison
Square Garden's Theater, he said to himself, ``I knew this was
going to happen _ and I still let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones gets bored, and that made him vulnerable, he
explained. ``I'm going to get lackadaisical,'' he said. Thus, he
fought sideways to start the fifth round. ``I did it to keep myself
from getting bored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DelValle, a world champion himself who sparred 38 rounds with
Jones three years ago, knows all of his tricks _ turning sideways,
shifting to southpaw, vaulting off the ropes _ and he did not let
Jones sucker him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult fighting your sparring partner,'' Jones
said. ``He knows all your tricks. That's why I don't like to fight
sparring partners.''
</P>
<P>
   DelValle won that eighth round with his left-right knockdown
after Jones dropped his guard. Jones quickly got up. It was the
only round he lost on the three judges' scorecards in gaining a
unanimous decision in the 12-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   He did, after all, throw 483 punches to DelValle's 286, landing
233 to DelValle's 113.
</P>
<P>
   DelValle, an admitted former drug dealer who lives in the Morris
Park section of the Bronx, proved not only courageous, but also
lived up to Borough President Fernando Ferrer's assessment of
fighters from the Bronx. ``They may lose,'' Ferrer said before the
bout, ``but there's not a chump among them.''
</P>
<P>
   This victory, though, did little for Jones' ultimate dream:
fighting for Evander Holyfield's heavyweight title. Even though
Jones dominates a fight, there probably will not be a huge public
demand for a fight with Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll fight all the top fighters at his weight,'' said HBO's
boxing director, Lou DiBella, whose company televised Saturday's
bout. ``He has to clear up the light heavyweight division first. I
don't think Evander will happen any time soon.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With his 37th victory in 38 fights, the 175-pound Jones not only
retained his World Boxing Council crown, but wrested away
DelValle's World Boxing Association title. Now there will be a
mandatory title defense, followed by a winter meeting with the
International Boxing Federation champion, Reggie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who knocks out almost 90 percent of his opponents, never
had DelValle down. DelValle (27-2) came away with a severely
battered face that included cuts around the left eye, perhaps from
a head butt, and bruises on his arms, cheeks and forehead.
</P>
<P>
   One of Jones' Pensacola pals, junior lightweight Derrick Gainer,
may have convinced Kevin Kelley that it is finally time to
seriously consider moving from the ring to ring side. Kelley, 31,
the former two-time featherweight champion from Flushing, Queens,
suffered only the third loss in a fine career that has seen 48
victories and a pair of draws.
</P>
<P>
   He understood what he had to do against Gainer, who at 5 feet 9
inches was 2 inches taller. Each weighed 126 pounds. But even
though Gainer stayed away the last two rounds, using his reach,
Kelley did not have the stamina to bull inside. He was knocked down
twice in dropping a unanimous 10-round decision to the 25-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Gainer increased his record to 24-4. One of those losses was an
eighth-round knockout by Kelley two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
