<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION REPRESENTATIVES SCHEDULE MEETING WITH STERN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For the first time since the National Basketball
Association instituted its lockout at the end of last month,
representatives of the players association will meet with
Commissioner David Stern on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see where he is and whether there's any possibility
of reaching an accord between now and the time to go to camp,'' the
players association's executive director, Billy Hunter, said Sunday
at Miami Arena before a charity game organized by Heat center
Alonzo Mourning. ``Is there any light at the end of the tunnel?''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter requested the meeting with Stern, as he had promised to
do after meeting with all but four of the league's player
representatives last week in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the dispute is over the owners' desire to put a
ceiling on how much players earn. The owners would like to change a
system in which player salaries account for more than 57 percent of
basketball-related revenue taken in by the league.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter calculated that there were more than 100 NBA players last
season making the minimum salary _ $272,000 _ compared with 22 whom
the league feels may be excessively compensated. ``So the issue is
about the owners being able to cap the guys who are responsible for
putting the fans in the seats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter reiterated that he seriously doubted the league's
assertion that nearly half its 29 teams lost money last season.
``Maybe there's one or two at the most,'' he said. ``And there's
nothing there that couldn't be overcome by better management.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter came here to offer assurances about the union's strength
to 30 of his constituents, including Gary Payton, Mitch Richmond,
Juwan Howard, Allen Iverson, Glen Rice and Vin Baker, who
participated in Sunday's game, and Patrick Ewing, the players
association president, who was here for moral support.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, sporting a blue wrap on his long-mending right wrist,
said the union had never been more unified and was ready for
anything. He declined to answer further questions.
</P>
<P>
   For Ewing and Hunter, Sunday's game _ dubbed Zo's Summer Groove
II _ was a chance to laugh and clap with the rest of the fans,
estimated at 7,000, who paid from $17.50 to $33.50 for tickets.
Proceeds went to two charities in the South Florida area.
</P>
<P>
   The players seemed divided on how long the lockout would last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a feeling it's going to be a long summer,'' Heat
forward P.J. Brown said. ``I'm thinking this thing may last up to
the season _ or beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the locker room, Payton was far more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're much stronger than we were three years ago, much more
together,'' he said of another labor impasse. ``I'm thinking it'll
be done by sometime in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to Payton, Washington Wizards point guard Rod Strickland
nodded agreement. ``I believe that, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Damon Stoudamire, who is a Toronto free agent, said
he had heard of Ted Turner's idea to play exhibition games, and
maybe even form a league, with the NBA's 180 or so free agents, but
he was noncommittal about the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how much money they're talking,'' Stoudamire
said. After a pause, he added: ``Who knows? If this thing lasts a
long time and it came down to it, maybe I would be interested.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His fellow free agent Ike Austin, the Los Angeles Clippers'
center, said he would be interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm game for anything,'' Austin said. ``If the NBA is going to
keep us locked out and we don't come to terms, this may be an
alternative for players. The main thing is we're going to stick
together, all the free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   The only player who hinted at any doubt of solidarity _
hypothetical as it might be _ was Heat point guard Tim Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get closer to the season, who knows what might
happen?'' Hardaway said. ``Some guys may say: `Man, I've got bills
to pay. I can't deal with this much longer.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
