<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: JAZZ FESTIVAL IN NEW YORK; PROMS IN LONDON; HARLEM'S
ART IN LOS ANGELES; SONG CYCLE AT TANGLEWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For some musicians there's ``June in January.'' For
others, there's Jazz in July, which runs until July 30 at the 92nd
Street Y.
</P>
<P>
   It begins Tuesday in Kaufmann Concert Hall with ``Happy
Birthday, Judge,'' an all-star tribute to the 60-year career of the
gifted bassist Milt ``the Judge'' Hinton.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the opening week of the festival, under the
artistic direction of the jazz pianist and historian Dick Hyman,
include ``1937 _ When Swing Was King'' on Wednesday at 8 p.m. and
``Three Piano Crossover,'' with Hyman, Ruth Laredo and Marian
McPartland, on Thursday at 8 p.m. Information: (212) 996-1100.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hear This
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Now in their 104th season and billed as the world's
greatest music festival, the Henry Wood Promenade Concerts, also
known as the Proms or the BBC Proms, are off and running at the
Royal Albert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Before they end on Sept. 12 with the Last Night outpouring of
traditional Britannia, expected to draw 35,000 people, including
those witnessing the event via a relay to Hyde Park, the Proms will
present 73 concerts.
</P>
<P>
   There will be tributes to George Gershwin (born 1898), Hanns
Eisler (1898) and Hildegard of Bingen (1098), and 30 world,
European, British and London premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, for example, brings the premiere of the first
opera commissioned for the Proms, John Harle's ``Angel Magick.'' On
Aug. 15, a new event, Choral Day, will attract choruses from all
over Britain to Royal Albert Hall, where they will join with other
choirs to bring a thousand voices to Carl Orff's ``Carmina
Burana.'' Information: 011-44-171-589-8212.
</P>
<P>
   Full Flower
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ More than 100 paintings, sculptures, photographs,
prints and drawings, plus rare archival film and sound recordings,
will be arrayed beginning on Sunday at the Los Angeles County
Museum of Art to illuminate the flourishing culture of Harlem in
the 1920s and the Depression years.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Rhapsodies in Black: Art of the Harlem Renaissance''
and continuing through Oct. 19, the exhibition includes the
jazz-inspired paintings of Aaron Douglas and the Jacob Lawrence
series ``Toussaint L'Ouverture,'' as well as works by Archibald J.
Motley Jr., Richmond Barthe and Meta Vaux Warrick Fuller, among
many others. Information: (323) 857-6000.
</P>
<P>
   First Hearing
</P>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ The composer is John Williams. The text is by
Rita Dove, a former poet laureate of the United States. The soloist
is Cynthia Haymon. The setting is Tanglewood, and the event is the
world premiere of Williams' ``Seven for Luck,'' a song cycle for
soprano and orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at 8:30 p.m. in the Shed, Williams will lead the
Boston Symphony Orchestra in the premiere during a program in which
the violinist Gil Shaham will play Williams' Violin Concerto.
Information: (413) 637-5165.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
