<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-CREW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROSTARS PUSH BACK OVER .500 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Are the New York MetroStars an average
team that is going to wobble toward the playoffs? Or are they a
special team that can do damage when the postseason arrives?
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-0 domination of the Columbus Crew Sunday lends credence
to the latter view. But the MetroStars have found themselves here
before: over .500 and seemingly on their way to greater
achievements, only to stumble into a losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm, hazy afternoon in front of 13,826 fans at Giants
Stadium, the MetroStars (10-9, 28 points) snapped a two-game skid
while seizing second place in Major League Soccer's Eastern
Conference from the Crew (9-9, 27 points).
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars did it by penetrating a Columbus defense that
virtually waved them into the last third of the field. The
MetroStars got goals from the two men they count on to finish: two
by Eduardo Hurtado and one by Giovanni Savarese. And they stopped
Columbus' attack before it could start. The Crew managed four shots
on goal, but only two were threats, requiring leaping grabs by
goalkeeper Tony Meola.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you saw the potential of this team,'' MetroStars Coach
Alfonso Mondelo said. ``Without a doubt, the first 45 minutes were
the best 45 minutes this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Defender Alexi Lalas said: ``I hope we're the team we saw today.
We understand that in order to have a chance in the postseason,
we'll have to put together games like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Tab Ramos contributed his most aggressive play since
returning from a second knee surgery and the United States'
disappointing showing in the World Cup. Ramos, in full sprint,
hooked a perfect crossing pass that Hurtado headed in from 15 yards
out in the 42nd minute to give the Metros a 2-0 lead. Then Ramos
was ejected in the 60th minute for an overly aggressive mouth with
the official. ``I take the blame,'' said Ramos, who felt he was
pushed by a defender.
</P>
<P>
   In the 26th minute, Hurtado used his head to serve up an assist
to the streaking Savarese. Savarese cradled the pass with his right
shoulder, hesitated and then scooted an 8-yard roller by the
sliding goalkeeper Juergen Sommer. The goal was Savarese's
team-leading ninth of the season and 36th in his career. Hurtado's
assist gave him 11, a MetroStars season record.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado completed his potent performance with a breakaway goal
in the 86th minute, letting defender Ansil Elcock slip by him, then
tapping in a 5-yarder with his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had good games like this before,'' Hurtado said, ``but
today's was very important. We wanted second place. We were
thinking, `Let's win the game,' but not by 3-0.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Columbus Coach Tom Fitzgerald said of Hurtado: ``That's the
first time I've seen him play like this since he played in L.A.
Unfortunately, he had to do it against us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
