<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM 34 GOES AT LESS THAN FULL BORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Oh, that Team 34 Racing. Look out Busch Grand
National tour. Those boys are going to be tough. Oh, baby.
</P>
<P>
   That was the buzz around California Speedway in the days
preceding Sunday's Busch Kenwood Home &AMP; Car Audio 300.
</P>
<P>
   Team 34 came into Sunday's race with Mike McLaughlin leading the
Busch points race. And in recent weeks, owner Frank Cicci had
caught the attention of his rivals in a big way by adding
top-flight drivers David Green and Todd Bodine _ both recently let
go from Winston Cup teams _ to his three-car stable.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers Matt Kenseth and Dale Earnhardt Jr., running close
behind McLaughlin in the points chase, were among those who
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those guys had been here from the start of the season,''
Kenseth said, ``this would be a five-man points race instead of a
three-man race. I think having teammates like that is going to be a
big advantage (to McLaughlin).''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But not on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Some not-so-funny things happened to Team 34 on the way to its
Kenwood domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those days,'' said McLaughlin, who finished 24th
and slipped behind Earnhardt and Kenseth in season points.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin's troubles began Friday with a poor showing in
qualifying that put him in the 30th starting position.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he had moved up to ninth position midway through
the race and figured he was on his way to a top-10 finish when he
rear-ended Kevin Lepage and sheared off the bolts that hold down
the hood on his Chevy Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the hood start to fly up in the air, I knew we were
done,'' said McLaughlin, who lost two laps and a lot of points to
the leaders while his pit crew worked on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine's return to Team 34 was a homecoming. Before moving to
Winston Cup racing with the Tabasco racing team earlier this year,
Bodine had eight Busch wins _ including last year's Kenwood _ for
Team 34 and was second in last year's Busch points race. So when he
and Tabasco parted ways last week, Cicci eagerly invited him back.
</P>
<P>
   He was in position for a while to make his return triumphant.
But his pit crew failed to get his left-front tire back on tight
during a stop on lap 100 while he was running fourth. And as he
sped away, the wheel came off and he had to limp back into the pit
and have another put on.
</P>
<P>
   He finished 33rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they just got excited because they were running
well,'' said Cicci. ``They just got overanxious and the crew chief
said go before they were finished with the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine was gracious.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make mistakes,'' he said. ``We're all human. I could
get mad at them, but I wouldn't be as mad as they probably are at
themselves. And they're a good bunch of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Green survived his mistake _ running out of gas _ thanks to some
help from Bodine and finished fifth. Just as Bodine was getting
back on the track with a new wheel, he got a message over his
radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `David's out of gas on the backstretch, see if you
can push him in,''' Bodine said. ``I said, `Sure. Glad to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Green said he knew help was on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a brother (Mark, who finished 19th) and two teammates
out there,'' he said. ``So I knew somebody would help me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cicci also took the day's travail in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be back,'' he said. ``I don't think anyone is going to
count us out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
