<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAMILY LIFE WITH A VENGEANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 20:
</P>
<P>
   The facts are incomplete. The allegations have not yet been
sifted nor indictments handed down. Still unknown is the fate of
Irene Silverman, the wealthy widow who disappeared in early July
from her East 65th Street town house. But already the story has
shifted from the potentially tragic mystery of Mrs. Silverman's
whereabouts to the strange lives of the only pair of suspects in
this case _ Sante Kimes, 63, and her 23-year-old son, Kenneth, who
were arrested in Manhattan on another matter the same day Mrs.
Silverman vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kimes, described by her former lawyer as having ``mounds of
hair,'' has allegedly made a calling, at least since 1961, of
violence, intimidation, and fraud. Only while she was in prison did
her son, free at last from her overweening control, seem to have a
reasonably normal life. In those days, his father, Kenneth Kimes,
an indulgent, if distant businessman, was still alive. He died in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the claims of past friends that Kenneth Kimes Jr.
hated his mother, he has become her accomplice, against his will or
not. Side by side, they stare balefully at the public from
newspapers and television, she with a slightly blurred mien, he
with sharp-edged malevolence and evident loathing of the
photographer. You can only imagine what expressions mother and son
would wear if they were looking at each other and if, still harder
to imagine, they actually let their guard down.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Aeschylus would have known what to make of this pair, or
Jim Thompson, author of ``The Grifters.'' The temptation is
certainly to psychologize and, perhaps, to sexualize _ with
Aeschylean austerity or with Thompson's blunt leer _ the predation
that the Kimeses have inflicted on themselves and, by allegation,
on many others.
</P>
<P>
   But among the inversions so apparent in the Kimes story, the
most interesting is the inversion of what we call normal life. In
1989, Kenneth Kimes Jr. is poised on the edge of an ordinary
existence, but it slips away when his mother returns from prison.
The crimes chalked up to Mrs. Kimes include insurance fraud, the
enslavement of Mexican servants, the murders of two men unfortunate
enough to stumble into her business and now the possible murder of
poor Mrs. Silverman _ are in themselves oddly domestic crimes,
hostile variations, you might call them, on the themes of normal
life: housing, comfort, cleanliness and security. This is family
life with a pathological vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   A crime story is nearly always a kind of living obituary, of the
accused as well as the victims. At first there is only the fact _
the crime itself, the death. But almost immediately we begin to
tell the story again and again, adding, refining, connecting,
always looping back as far as we can into the past until the
narrative makes sense. Our taste, at the moment, is to believe in
cause rather than chance. Either way, ``there is trouble here,'' as
the chorus says in Aeschylus, and ``there is more to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-19-98 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
