u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MENDENHALL-NYT &LR;      07-19 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MENDENHALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS MENDENHALL, 88, ROWING AUTHOR AND SMITH COLLEGE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn., Wis.)  (lh) 
 By WILLIAM N. WALLACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Corwin Mendenhall, the foremost U.S. historian of the
sport of rowing and a former president of Smith College, died
Saturday at Windemere, a long-term care facility on Martha's
Vineyard, Mass., where he and his wife lived. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cardiac arrest following a long illness, said his
wife, Cornelia Baker Mendenhall.
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall was the president of Smith College in Northampton,
Mass., from 1959 until he retired in 1979. He was a noted professor
of history at Yale before that appointment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He wrote 10 books, earned numerous degrees and taught classes.
His students, friends and family, however, remember his engaging
humor and his many probing interests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall grew up in Madison, Wis., the son of the chairman of
the physics department at the University of Wisconsin, Charles E.
Mendenhall. His mother, Dr. Dorothy R. Mendenhall, was a
pediatrician. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall graduated from Andover and then from Yale in 1932. He
went on to Oxford as a Rhodes Scholar and was captain of the
Balliol College crew there. He began teaching at Yale in 1937 and
was named an associate professor in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Among many assignments at Yale, Mendenhall served as Master of
Berkeley College and coach of the Berkeley crew.
</P>
<P>
   Rowing always had his passionate attention, and among his books
are ``A Short History of American Rowing,'' and ``The Harvard-Yale
Boat Race 1852-1924.'' That book went beyond that event and
justified its subtitle, ``The Coming of Sport to the American
College.'' He also wrote ``Have Oar Will Travel,'' a history of
Yale's 1956 crew team, which won an Olympic gold medal in
Melbourne, Australia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mendenhall recalled that her husband was always busy when
he was teaching. During a typical day at Yale, she said, he might
teach three classes, attend two meetings, coach the Berkeley crew,
advise students and help clean up the dining hall in advance of a
rehearsal of the Berkeley Players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was not much room to sit down in Mendenhall's small
office, one jammed to its ceiling with books and papers.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Lamar, a history professor and later interim president of
Yale, told of a meeting of the history department faculty in
Mendenhall's office at which someone pulled out a drawer to sit on.
In the drawer was a paper bag that contained a forgotten sandwich.
It was not an example of an absent-minded professor, but of a busy
one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall continued to teach history at Smith, and he also
worked to bring the four neighboring colleges of the Connecticut
Valley into closer contact. Even as president, his popularity with
students did not diminish.
</P>
<P>
   Following his retirement, Mendenhall for many years attended
Smith reunions, where he tried to maintain a rule: ``I won't let
them kiss me,'' he said, ``until they tell me their maiden names.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with his wife, Mendenhall is survived by two daughters,
Bethany Mendenhall and Cornelia Small, and two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Mendenhall remained busy during his retirement at Vineyard Haven
on Martha's Vineyard, close to the ocean that had meant so much to
him. The most popular course he taught at Yale was ``The History of
Sea Power,'' and at the Vineyard what he liked to do best was to
take his sloop out for a sail on Nantucket Sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
